\chapter{Introduction}

This document is a literate reverse engineering of \emph{Ultima I: The
First Age of Darkness} for the Apple~II. Every byte of the original
program is reproduced by the assembly chunks herein: tangling this
document and assembling the result yields binaries identical to the
original disk image. The document is written for a reader who wants to
understand how the game was built --- in enough detail to reproduce or
port it in any language, on any platform. Platform-independent
descriptions of the game's design, data structures, and algorithms
accompany the annotated assembly throughout.

\section{The game}

\emph{Ultima} was written by Richard Garriott (``Lord British'') and
published by California Pacific Computer in 1981, the first entry in
what became one of the longest-running role-playing series in computer
gaming. The original was largely Applesoft BASIC. In 1986 Origin
Systems published a complete rewrite in 6502 assembly language for the
Apple~II --- faster, with redrawn graphics --- under the title
\emph{Ultima I: The First Age of Darkness}. That 1986 remake is the
program reverse engineered here. (The disk image is the ``4am crack''
preservation release, which removes only the original disk's copy
protection; the program itself is Origin's. The startup banner in the
binary reads ``Copyright 1986 by Origin Systems, Inc.'')

The player creates a character (race, sex, class, attribute points)
and explores the realm of Sosaria to defeat the evil wizard Mondain.
Play moves between six distinct modes, each with its own presentation:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Outdoors} --- a tile-scrolled overworld map of four
  continents, with towns, castles, and dungeon entrances.
\item \textbf{Towns} --- tile maps with shops (weapons, armour, food,
  magic, pubs) and citizens.
\item \textbf{Castles} --- tile maps where kings give quests and
  rewards.
\item \textbf{Dungeons} --- first-person three-dimensional wireframe
  mazes, ten levels deep, populated by monsters.
\item \textbf{Space} --- a first-person space-flight shooter sequence;
  destroying enemy craft earns the ``space ace'' status the endgame
  requires.
\item \textbf{Time machine} --- the endgame confrontation with
  Mondain, fought in the past.
\end{itemize}

The program is structured exactly along these lines: a memory-resident
engine provides shared services, and one overlay file per mode is
loaded over a common overlay region as the player moves between modes.
This architecture is visible directly in the disk's file listing and
drives the organization of this document.

This document is in two parts. Part~\ref{part:design},
\emph{Design}, recovers how the game works in platform-independent terms
--- architecture, data structures, algorithms, rendering, and the 6502
idioms a port must replace --- so that the game can be reproduced without
reading a line of assembly. Part~\ref{part:implementation},
\emph{Implementation}, is the annotated 6502 program itself, in load
order, every chunk of which assembles to bytes identical to the original
disk. The design part states each mechanism; the implementation part
proves it.

\section{How the program is organized}

The game runs under ProDOS, Apple's then-current operating system, and
its data lives in ordinary ProDOS files on a volume named
\texttt{/U1}. The boot chain is:

\begin{enumerate}
\item The Disk~II controller PROM loads the 512-byte \textbf{boot
  block} at [[$0800]] and jumps to it.
\item The boot block finds the file \texttt{PRODOS} in the volume
  directory, loads it at [[$2000]], and jumps to it. This file is the
  stock ProDOS~1.1.1 kernel (dated 18-SEP-84), byte-identical to
  Apple's release; it is treated as an external dependency in this
  document, like the monitor ROM.
\item ProDOS relocates itself high, then loads and runs the first
  \texttt{.SYSTEM} file in the directory: \texttt{U1.SYSTEM}, the
  game's launcher.
\item \texttt{U1.SYSTEM} loads and runs \texttt{U1.INTRO} (title and
  main menu), which in turn starts the game proper: the resident
  engine \texttt{MI.U1} at [[$7000]] plus one mode overlay at
  [[$8956]].
\end{enumerate}

\part{Design: how the game works}
\label{part:design}

\noindent
This first part recovers the game's design in platform-independent terms.
It describes the architecture, the persistent data structures, the
non-trivial algorithms, the rendering pipeline, and the 6502 idioms a port
must replace --- everything a programmer needs to reproduce the game in any
language, with no Apple~II assembly required. The annotated assembly that
proves each claim, byte for byte, is Part~\ref{part:implementation}.

\chapter{Architecture overview}
\label{ch:architecture}

This chapter recovers the \emph{shape} of the program --- how it is laid
out in memory, how control passes between its parts, and how its parts
share state --- in terms a porter can use without reading a line of 6502.
The chapters that follow it are the evidence: each documents one file of
the original, annotated to assemble byte-for-byte. Here we step back and
describe the machine those files build.

\section{The engine-and-overlays model}

\emph{Ultima I} does not fit in memory all at once. The 1986 remake
solves this the way most disk-based Apple~II games of its generation did:
a \textbf{resident engine} stays in memory for the whole session and
provides shared services, while the code for whichever \emph{mode} the
player is in --- outdoors, town, castle, dungeon, space, the endgame ---
is loaded on demand into a single shared region, one \textbf{overlay} at
a time. Only one mode's code is ever resident; switching modes means
loading a different overlay over the same addresses.

Three things live in memory at once during play:

\begin{description}
\item[The resident library (\texttt{STUPH}, [[$0800]]--[[$1FFF]]).]
  The lowest layer: the font and tile glyph banks, the hi-res blitter and
  double-buffering machinery, the keyboard and sound-effect queues, the
  pseudo-random generator, and the file loader (which wraps the disk in a
  transparent \texttt{/RAM} cache on 128K machines). It exposes a fixed
  \textbf{jump-vector table} --- a list of [[JMP]]s at known addresses ---
  so callers bind to stable entry points, not to the routines' shifting
  internal addresses. See chapter~\ref{ch:stuph}.
\item[The resident engine (\texttt{MI.U1}, [[$7000]]--[[$89BC]]).]
  The game layer shared by every mode: the player-state block, the
  packed string tables (every name the game prints), the text/window/%
  status-bar renderer, the inventory and ``ready'' screens, the BCD
  number formatter, the turn/food/time bookkeeping, the command parser,
  and the mode-switch loader. Overlays call \emph{into} the engine
  constantly; the engine never calls \emph{out} to a specific overlay ---
  it only jumps to the overlay's fixed entry point. See
  chapter~\ref{ch:engine}.
\item[The current mode overlay ([[OVERLAY_ENTRY]] = [[$8956]] upward).]
  One file --- \texttt{OUT}, \texttt{DNG}, \texttt{TWN}, \texttt{CAS},
  \texttt{SPA}, \texttt{GEN}, or \texttt{TM} --- loaded over the region
  above the engine. It owns the mode's main loop, command handlers, and
  mode-specific rendering, and it runs until the player does something
  that changes mode, at which point it asks the engine to load a
  different overlay over itself. See chapter~\ref{ch:overlays}.
\end{description}

