A porter does not need this address map --- on a machine with enough
memory, every overlay and the engine can be resident simultaneously and
``loading an overlay'' becomes ``calling that mode's entry point.'' What
\emph{is} essential is the \textbf{boundary}: the engine and library are a
fixed API, each mode is a module behind that API, and exactly one mode is
active at a time. The overlay scheme is the 1986 machine's answer to a
memory limit, not a design requirement.

\section{Boot and load flow}

Cold start walks a chain of progressively more game-specific loaders, each
loading the next (chapters~\ref{ch:boot}--\ref{ch:intro}):

\begin{enumerate}
\item The Disk~II PROM loads the 512-byte boot block and jumps to it.
\item The boot block loads the stock \textbf{ProDOS} kernel (treated here
  as an external dependency, like the ROM) and starts it.
\item ProDOS runs \texttt{U1.SYSTEM}, the launcher, which installs the
  resident file library and chains to the title program.
\item \texttt{MAKE.INDATA} (section~\ref{sec:makeindata}) builds the two
  title screens in memory once, then is discarded; \texttt{U1.INTRO}
  animates the title and waits for a key.
\item A keypress loads the resident engine \texttt{MI.U1} and the first
  overlay, and play begins.
\end{enumerate}

From there, \textbf{every mode change goes through one routine},
[[GAME_LOAD]] in the engine. The game keeps a table of the seven overlay
filenames ([[LOC_NAME]]) at fixed four-byte strides, in the order
\texttt{GEN OUT DNG TWN CAS SPA TM}. To change mode, code jumps to
[[GAME_LOAD]] with the accumulator holding the destination's offset into
that table (0, 4, 8, \dots); the routine resets the stack (there is no
return --- a mode switch abandons the old mode's call chain), loads that
overlay through the disk/\texttt{/RAM} cache, redraws the screen frame,
and jumps to the overlay's fixed entry point [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]]. Offset~0
(or any out-of-range value) is special: it loads \texttt{GEN}, the
character generator --- the new-game path. Death funnels through
[[RESPAWN]], which is just [[GAME_LOAD]] with the \texttt{OUT} offset, so
the slain player wakes up outdoors.

This is the cleanest single fact about the program's control flow: there
is one mode-dispatch function, it is identified by a small integer, and it
never returns. A port can implement it as a state-machine transition ---
\texttt{set\_mode(mode\_id)} that tears down the current mode and starts
the next --- with no stack gymnastics.

Because every mode change is one [[GAME_LOAD]] call, the whole game is a
small state machine over the seven overlays. Figure~\ref{fig:mode-fsm}
draws it: \texttt{GEN} (character generation) is the start state, all
exploration radiates from \texttt{OUT} (outdoors), and the single
win-path arrow \texttt{CAS}~$\to$~\texttt{TM} (highlighted) is the only
transition gated on a progress flag rather than a terrain tile or a menu
key --- the subject of section~\ref{sec:winfsm}.

