\section{The anatomy of a mode}

Every overlay is built to the same template, which makes the seven modes
far more alike than the screenshots suggest. A porter who implements one
mode's skeleton has implemented all seven:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Entry} ([[OVERLAY_ENTRY]]). Restore the mode's view from
  saved player state (e.g.\ the outdoor position, the dungeon level), set
  the movement-command vocabulary for this mode (the same four movement
  keys are labelled ``North/South/East/West'' outdoors but ``Forward/Turn
  around/Turn right/Turn left'' in a dungeon and ``Thrust/Retro/%
  Clockwise/Counter'' in space, via a single pointer the engine reads
  when echoing commands), load any mode-specific map or glyph data, and
  draw the first frame.
\item \textbf{Main loop.} Show the status line, poll for a key with a
  timeout. A timeout (no key) is an \textbf{idle turn}: the mode animates
  (monsters step, NPCs wander) and time/food tick. A key is parsed by the
  engine's [[GET_COMMAND]] into a command number, which the mode
  \textbf{dispatches} to a handler.
\item \textbf{Command handlers.} One routine per command. Movement
  handlers update position and redraw; action handlers (Attack, Cast,
  Get, Talk, \dots) do the mode-specific thing. A handler that ends the
  mode jumps to [[GAME_LOAD]].
\item \textbf{End-of-turn tick.} After a handled command, run the mode's
  per-turn world update (spawn checks, monster AI, hazards), then loop.
\end{enumerate}

Figure~\ref{fig:mode-loop} draws this template as a flowchart. Every
overlay's main loop is this shape; only the contents of the
\emph{dispatch} and \emph{tick} boxes differ by mode. The two ways out are
visible: the timeout branch (an idle turn that animates and ticks without a
command) folds back into the loop, while a mode-ending command leaves
through the one-way [[GAME_LOAD]] door at the bottom.

