\subsection*{The dispatch idiom}

The command dispatch deserves a porting note because its 6502 form looks
nothing like its intent. Each overlay has a table of handler addresses,
one per command. Rather than compute an indexed indirect jump, the code
\textbf{patches the operand of a [[JSR]] instruction} in place with the
handler's address and then executes that [[JSR]]. This ``patched-JSR
dispatch'' is self-modifying code: the call target is data, written into
the instruction stream a few bytes ahead, then run. (\texttt{SPA} is the
exception --- it self-modifies a [[JMP]] into its loop instead.) The
portable equivalent is a plain array of function pointers indexed by the
command number:

\begin{verbatim}
    handler = COMMAND_TABLE[command_number]
    handler()        // the patched JSR, expressed portably
\end{verbatim}

Several other 6502 idioms recur across the overlays and mean the same
thing everywhere; they are collected in the per-subsystem porting notes,
but the dispatch patch is the one a reader meets first and most often.

\section{Shared state}

Because only one mode is resident at a time, all state that must
\emph{survive} a mode change lives in the resident engine, not in the
overlays. The overlays are nearly stateless between visits: they read the
player block on entry and write it back before switching away. The
durable state falls into a few groups (the field-level reference is
chapter~\ref{ch:engine}; here is the shape):

\begin{description}
\item[The player block.] One contiguous record in the engine's space:
  name, race/sex/class, the six attributes, the vitals (hit points, food,
  experience, gold --- all 16-bit binary, converted to decimal only for
  display), the readied weapon/armour/spell, the owned-item and
  owned-spell arrays, the current position, and the quest/gem flags. This
  is exactly the record saved to and loaded from the \texttt{/U1.PLAYER}
  disk file, so its layout \emph{is} the save format.
\item[The world position.] Which continent, and where on it; which town,
  castle, or dungeon the player is standing in or has entered. The
  overlays translate this into their own coordinate systems on entry.
\item[The object records.] Outdoors, the monsters, ships, and loose
  items are a set of parallel fixed-length arrays (a slot's kind, screen
  position, tile, and hit points each in their own array) --- an
  ``array of structures'' stored as a ``structure of arrays.'' Towns and
  castles use a smaller NPC table of the same flavour.
\item[The progress flags.] The quest-completion flags, the four owned
  gems, the storeroom permission counter, the space-combat kill counter,
  and the single flag that arms the endgame. These thread the win
  condition together across modes (next section).
\end{description}

A handful of shared scratch locations in zero page (the draw pointers,
the double-buffer toggle, the random-number state) are also touched by
both engine and overlays; these are working storage, not game state, and
a port re-implements them however its host prefers.

\section{The win condition, as a state machine}
\label{sec:winfsm}

The modes are not peers in a menu; they are wired into a specific
progression that constitutes ``winning,'' and the linkage is entirely in
the shared progress flags. Recovered from the code, the path is:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Outdoors and towns} build the character: kill monsters for
  experience, buy gear, and gather the four \textbf{gems} that castles
  hand out for completing quests. One gem's prophecy tells the player a
  time machine is the only way to win; another that a princess will help
  a ``space ace'' travel through time.
\item \textbf{Space} is reached by boarding a shuttle and lifting off.
  Each enemy craft destroyed increments a kill counter; reaching twenty
  earns the rank of \textbf{Space Ace}. This is the only place that
  counter is written.
\item \textbf{A castle} is where the two threads meet. Rescuing the
  princess while holding Space-Ace rank (and enough experience) sets the
  single \textbf{endgame flag} and reveals the location of the time
  machine.
\item \textbf{The time machine} (the \texttt{TM} overlay) is the endgame:
  a confrontation with Mondain in the past. Mondain is invulnerable while
  he holds the Gem of Immortality; the player must \emph{destroy the gem}
  and \emph{then} kill him. Success melts the screen into the victory
  image and hooks the reset key --- the game is over.
\end{enumerate}

Every arrow in that chain is a flag written in one mode and read in
another: the kill counter (written in space, gated on in the castle), the
endgame flag (set in the castle, required by the time machine), the gems
(handed out by castles, their prophecies the only in-game statement of
the win condition). The progression is data, not control flow --- which is
why it survives the overlay swaps intact, and why a port can model the
whole game as one shared state object that the mode modules read and
write.

Figure~\ref{fig:win-fsm} traces that flag plumbing as a state machine
whose edges are guarded by the shared progress flags rather than by the
mode the player happens to be in. Read it as ``the player wins when these
flags reach these values, in this order'': the four [[OWNED_GEMS]] arrive
from castle quests; [[PLR_VESSELS]] reaches twenty only in space;
rescuing the princess with both in hand sets [[TM_REVEAL]]; and only then
does the [[TM]] overlay's destroy-gem-then-kill sequence end the game.

