\section{Rendering, in one paragraph}

Two presentation styles span the seven modes. The grid modes (outdoors,
towns, castles) draw a \textbf{tile viewport}: a window of map cells, each
cell a glyph blitted from a font-like tile bank, centred on the player.
The first-person modes (dungeons, space, the endgame) draw
\textbf{wireframe vector graphics}: line strokes computed from
perspective tables, with no stored bitmap. Both render to one of two
hi-res pages while the other is shown, then flip --- the standard
double-buffer. What is Apple~II-specific (the interleaved hi-res address
layout, the page-flip soft switches, the NTSC colour-artifact palette) is
isolated in the \texttt{STUPH} library and called through its vectors;
what is portable (the tile codes, the vector shape lists, the animation
timing) lives in the engine and overlays. The per-mode rendering chapters
mark the boundary explicitly.

\chapter{Data-structure reference}
\label{ch:datastructures}

This chapter describes every persistent game-state structure abstractly:
its fields, its invariants, and who reads and writes it. It is the
companion to the architecture overview (chapter~\ref{ch:architecture}):
where that chapter described how the modes communicate, this one
describes \emph{what they communicate through}. Each structure is given
as language-neutral pseudocode using the same symbol names as the
assembly, so a reader can drill from the abstract layout down to the
annotated bytes in the engine and overlay chapters.

A note on numbers throughout: the game stores every \emph{quantity} ---
hit points, food, experience, gold, attributes --- as a plain 16-bit
binary integer, little-endian, and converts to decimal digits only when
printing. The only structures stored in binary-coded decimal are the two
\emph{display counters} (the move count and the food fraction), which are
incremented directly in BCD to avoid a conversion every turn. A port uses
ordinary integers everywhere and formats on output; the BCD is an Apple~II
micro-optimisation, not a design choice.

\section{The player block: the save format}

The single most important structure is the \textbf{player block}, a
contiguous record in the resident engine's memory beginning at
[[PLR_SAVE]]. It is also exactly the byte image written to and read from
the \texttt{/U1.PLAYER} disk file --- the record's first word is its own
length ([[$01CA]] = 458 bytes), and saving the game is one block-write of
those 458 bytes. So this layout \emph{is} the save format; there is no
serialisation step.

\begin{verbatim}
struct PlayerBlock {            // at PLR_SAVE; 458 bytes; = /U1.PLAYER
  u16  length;                  // PLR_SAVE: own length, 0x01CA
  u8   continent;               // PLR_CONT: 0..3, which continent
  u8   continent_bits;          // PLR_CONT_BITS: continent << 6 (Y tag)
  u8   sound_on, sfx_on;        // PLR_SOUND/PLR_SFX: saved audio flags
  u8   out_x, out_y;            // PLR_OUT_X/Y: outdoor map position
  u8   gems[4];                 // OWNED_GEMS: red, green, blue, white
  u8   ready_spell;             // READY_SPELL: index, 0 = none
  u8   ready_weapon;            // READY_WEAPON: index, 0 = hands
  u8   ready_armour;            // READY_ARMOUR: index, 0 = skin
  u8   ready_transport;         // READY_TRANSPORT: current craft index
  u8   owned_armour[6];         // OWNED_ARMOUR: count per armour type
  u8   owned_weapons[16];       // OWNED_WEAPONS: count per weapon type
  u8   owned_spells[11];        // OWNED_SPELLS: count per spell
  u8   owned_transport[11];     // OWNED_TRANSPORT: count per craft type
  u8   quest_flags[8];          // QUEST_FLAGS: 0 unset, 1 active, FF done
  u8   court_cells[4];          // COURT_CELLS: 4 cells around last town
  u8   tm_reveal;               // TM_REVEAL: arm the endgame breadcrumb
  u8   vessels;                 // PLR_VESSELS: space kills (Space Ace=20)
  u8   sex;                     // PLR_SEX: 0 = male, else female
  char name[14];                // PLR_NAME: zero-padded
  u16  hits;                    // PLR_HITS: hit points (binary)
  u16  attr[6];                 // STR, AGI, STA, CHA, WIS, INT (binary)
  u16  coin;                    // PLR_COIN: gold (binary)
  u16  race;                    // PLR_RACE: index into STR_RACES
  u16  class;                   // PLR_CLASS: index into STR_CLASSES
  u8   move_count[10];          // MOVE_CNT: BCD, low byte first
  u8   food_fraction;           // FOOD_FRAC: BCD hundredths of a food
  u16  food;                    // PLR_FOOD: food (binary)
  u16  experience;              // PLR_EXP: experience (binary)
  u16  _reserved[2];            // two 1000-valued words, role unidentified
  u8   place;                   // PLR_PLACE: which of the 84 places, 0..83
  u8   last_landmark;           // PLR_LASTMARK: last boon site (no repeat)
  ...                           // object records follow (next section)
};
\end{verbatim}

\noindent Field notes and invariants:

\begin{description}
\item[The six attributes] live at [[PLR_HITS]]+2 as 16-bit words in the
  fixed order Strength, Agility, Stamina, Charisma, Wisdom, Intelligence.
  Character generation (chapter~\ref{ch:gen}) seeds them from a 30-point
  pool with a floor of 10 and a ceiling of 25, then adds race and class
  bonuses. Charisma drives shop prices; the others gate class abilities
  and combat.
\item[The owned-item arrays] are \emph{counts}, not booleans: index $i$
  holds how many of item~$i$ the player has. Index~0 of each is the
  ``empty'' choice (hands / skin / no spell) and is always available.
  Buying increments, using or selling decrements. The readied-item fields
  index into these arrays.
\item[Experience determines level] --- the displayed level is
  $\lfloor \mathit{experience} / 1000 \rfloor + 1$, recomputed on every
  stats draw; level is not stored.
\item[The coin purse is one number] shown three ways: the
  inventory screen splits the single [[PLR_COIN]] value into pence
  (ones), silver (tens), and gold (hundreds-and-up) for display only.
\item[continent\_bits] is [[PLR_CONT]] shifted into the top two bits,
  precomputed once so the object-record code can tag and test coordinates
  with a mask instead of a shift (see the next section).
\end{description}

\section{The object records: the mutable world}

The world map itself never changes (next section); everything that moves
or can be picked up --- monsters, ships, parked transports, the time
machines --- is an \textbf{object record}. The records are stored as a
\emph{structure of arrays}: five parallel 80-entry arrays, indexed by a
common slot number, with [[OBJ_COUNT]] giving the number of live slots.

\begin{verbatim}
struct ObjectRecords {          // max 80 slots, OBJ_COUNT live
  u8   count;                   // OBJ_COUNT: number of active slots
  u8   x[80];                   // OBJ_X:    world column
  u8   yc[80];                  // OBJ_YC:   world row | (continent << 6)
  u8   tile[80];                // OBJ_TILE: the cell glyph to draw
  u8   under[80];               // OBJ_UNDER: terrain cell beneath it
  u8   hp[80];                  // OBJ_HP: hit points (in UNSAVED RAM)
};
\end{verbatim}

\noindent Invariants and behaviour:

\begin{description}
\item[The continent tag.] [[OBJ_YC]] packs the row in its low six bits and
  the continent in its top two. Records for all four continents coexist in
  the arrays; a map redraw paints only the records whose top two bits
  match [[PLR_CONT_BITS]]. This is how a ship the player left on one
  continent is still there on return without a per-continent record set.
\item[under.] Because an object hides the terrain beneath it, the cell it
  is standing on is saved in [[OBJ_UNDER]] so the map can be repainted
  correctly when the object moves or is removed.
\item[Hit points are not saved.] [[OBJ_HP]] lives in unsaved RAM
  ([[OBJ_HP]] = the page at [[$B600]]), and [[OBJ_HP]]+0 doubles as a
  ``world has been initialised'' sentinel. Reloading a game respawns
  monster health; only the records' positions and kinds persist.
\item[Parked transports] are object records too: buying a ship or other
  craft writes a record at the player's location with the craft's tile;
  boarding removes it and sets [[READY_TRANSPORT]]. The outdoor overlay
  recounts [[OWNED_TRANSPORT]] from these records on entry, which is why
  that array is the one owned-item array not trusted from the save.
\end{description}

This single 80-slot table is the entire mutable overworld. A port that
keeps an entity list with these five fields per entity, tagged by
continent, reproduces the world model exactly.

\section{Town and castle maps: the TCMAPS records}

Towns and castles do not generate their layout; they load it. The
\texttt{TCMAPS} file (documented in detail in the game-data chapter) is a
directory of ten fixed \textbf{764-byte records}, one per town or castle.
On entry, the overlay copies the chosen record into a live buffer at
[[TOWN_MAP]] and works from there.

\begin{verbatim}
struct TownCastleMap {          // 764 bytes; copied to TOWN_MAP on entry
  u8   cells[38 * 18];          // 684 bytes: the displayed grid, row-major
  // NPC table: 5 parallel 16-entry arrays at offset 684 (= TOWN_MAP+684)
  u8   npc_type[16];            // NPC_TYPE: FF empty, kind code otherwise
  u8   npc_x[16];               // NPC_X: column on the grid
  u8   npc_y[16];               // NPC_Y: row on the grid
  u8   npc_hp_lo[16];           // NPC hit points, low byte
  u8   npc_hp_hi[16];           //               high byte
};
\end{verbatim}

\noindent Notes:

\begin{description}
\item[The grid is $38 \times 18$.] Each cell is a glyph code drawn through
  the town/castle tile bank (\texttt{MAPCHARS}); shop signs (``ARMOUR'',
  ``THE PUB'', \dots) are spelled into the grid as ASCII glyph codes.
  Walking off the $38\times18$ edge leaves the place. (An earlier draft of
  this document said $38\times19$; the move handler's bounds prove 18.)
\item[The NPC table] is the same structure-of-arrays flavour as the
  outdoor object records, 16 slots wide. The \emph{kind} code selects
  behaviour: hostiles home in and attack, wanderers drift (and may sing,
  pick a pocket, or, at a shop counter, trade). Counter NPCs with kind
  codes in a small range select one of six shop classes; a king's
  audience kind triggers the quest system.
\item[The live buffer persists] at [[TOWN_MAP]] across the visit so NPC
  positions and health survive turns; it is reloaded fresh from
  \texttt{TCMAPS} on the next entry.
\end{description}

The ten rendered maps appear as a figure in the game-data chapter.

\section{The world map}

The overworld is four continents, each a $64 \times 64$ grid of terrain
cells. The grids are stored \textbf{RLE-compressed and read-only}: they
arrive in the \texttt{/U1.VARS} file, sit packed above the overlay region
at [[MAP_PACKED]], and are decompressed into the working map area at
[[$6000]] on every continent change. Nothing the player does writes back
to the stored map --- the entire mutable overworld is the object-record
table of the previous section. (The \texttt{/U1.VARS} file is absent from
the preservation disk this document is built from, so the four continents
cannot be imaged here; the ten town and castle maps, which live in the
present \texttt{TCMAPS} file, are rendered in the game-data chapter.)

A terrain cell's value encodes both what to draw and what it means:
ordinary terrain classes (water, grass, forest, mountains, \dots) index
the tile bank directly, while higher cell-byte ranges mark towns,
castles, dungeon entrances, and landmark sites. The dungeon overlay, by
contrast, stores \emph{no} map at all --- each of the ten levels of each
dungeon is regenerated deterministically from a seed derived from the
player's position (chapter~\ref{ch:overlays} and the algorithm chapter).

\section{Coordinate systems}

Three distinct coordinate frames appear, and a porter must keep them
separate:

\begin{description}
\item[World coordinates] (continent, column~0--63, row~0--63) locate the
  player and the object records on the overworld grid. The continent is
  carried separately ([[PLR_CONT]]) and, for object rows, folded into the
  high bits of [[OBJ_YC]].
\item[Grid coordinates] (column~0--37, row~0--17) locate the player and
  NPCs inside a town or castle. They are unrelated to world coordinates;
  the overlay derives them on entry.
\item[Screen/viewport coordinates.] The grid modes draw a fixed
  \textbf{$19 \times 9$ tile viewport} centred on the player: world or
  grid cell $(x, y)$ maps to a viewport slot offset from the centre, and
  cells outside the window are not drawn. The first-person modes have no
  cell-to-pixel mapping at all --- they project depth and facing through
  perspective tables (the rendering chapter).
\end{description}

The recurring conversion ``centre the viewport on the player'' is the
same in every grid mode: for each of the $19 \times 9$ viewport slots,
read the map cell at the player's position plus the slot's signed offset,
and blit that cell's glyph. Keeping world/grid coordinates and viewport
coordinates distinct is the one thing a port must not conflate.

\chapter{Algorithm descriptions}
\label{ch:algorithms}

This chapter collects the game's non-trivial mechanics as
platform-independent pseudocode plus the design intent behind each. These
are the parts a porter cannot recover by translating instructions one for
one: the formulas are spread across the assembly, encoded in tables, and
tangled with 6502 idioms. Here each is stated as an algorithm, with the
assembly routines named for drill-down. The data structures they operate
on are in chapter~\ref{ch:datastructures}.

\section{The random-number generators}

The game uses \emph{two} pseudo-random sources, and the distinction
matters for reproducibility.

\textbf{The library PRNG} ([[RND]] in \texttt{STUPH}) is a 16-byte lagged
additive generator, reseeded from the timing of the cursor flash --- so it
is genuinely unpredictable from run to run. It supplies the
``atmospheric'' randomness: which flavour name a shopkeeper has, whether a
container is a chest or a coffin, idle-animation jitter, combat damage
spread.

\textbf{The maze PRNG} ([[SEED_RND]] in \texttt{DNG}) is a deterministic
two-byte Fibonacci-style generator used only to build dungeons:

\begin{verbatim}
    seed_step(A, B):            // SEED_RND
        A' = (A + B + 9) mod 256
        B' = A
        return (A, B) = (A', B')   // the new A is the random byte
\end{verbatim}

Because its seed is a pure function of \emph{where} the dungeon is and
\emph{how deep} the player has gone, the same dungeon level always
generates identically (next section). This is the key trick that lets the
game ship ten-level dungeons under every entrance without storing a single
dungeon map.

\section{The turn economy: food and time}

Every action that takes game-time calls the engine's [[TICK]] routine with
two parameters: a food cost and a move-counter increment. [[TICK]]
maintains the hunger clock and the move odometer:

\begin{verbatim}
    tick(food_cost, move_delta):           // TICK / TICK_SND
        food_fraction -= food_cost         // BCD hundredths of a food unit
        if borrow:
            if food > 0: food -= 1         // 16-bit binary, clamp at 0
        move_count += move_delta           // multi-byte BCD odometer
\end{verbatim}

Food is therefore spent in \emph{hundredths}: [[FOOD_FRAC]] is a fraction
that, when it underflows, costs one whole unit of [[PLR_FOOD]]. Different
activities tick at different rates --- and, importantly, faster transports
cost \emph{less} food and \emph{less} time per step than walking, which is
the whole point of owning a horse or a ship. The per-step costs are small
tables in each overlay. A port keeps food as a fixed-point value (the
hundredths are just two decimal places) and the move count as a plain
integer; the BCD is only so the Apple~II can print the odometer without a
binary-to-decimal conversion every turn.

Running out of food does not immediately kill; it begins starvation
damage, applied by the overlays' end-of-turn tick.

\section{Procedural dungeon generation}

No dungeon map exists on disk. Entering a dungeon, or moving between its
levels, rebuilds the current level from scratch with [[DNG_GEN]]. The seed
is derived entirely from fixed facts about the location:

\begin{verbatim}
    seed_A = (8 * place) XOR outdoor_x XOR level
    seed_B = (4 * outdoor_y) XOR continent
\end{verbatim}

so revisiting the same level of the same dungeon always yields the same
maze. Generation then runs five passes over a fresh template (a
$11 \times 11$ grid: solid border, with a lattice of pillars at every
even-column/even-row cell). All structural rolls come from the maze PRNG;
only container type and monsters use the library PRNG.

\begin{verbatim}
    generate_level(level):                 // DNG_GEN
      map = copy(DNG_TEMPLATE)             // border + even/even pillars

      // pass 1: edges -- the lattice openings between pillars
      for each edge cell (even col,odd row) or (odd col,even row):
          r = maze_rand() mod 20
          map[cell] = pick(r): open (6/20), secret door (6/20), door (8/20)

      // pass 2: walls and force fields
      repeat (2*level + 1) times:
          pos = WALL_POS[ maze_rand() ]    // transposed on odd levels
          map[pos] = (maze_rand() < 96/256) ? force_field : wall

      // pass 3: containers (the only library-RNG structural roll)
      repeat (level) times:
          pos = random edge cell
          map[pos] = (lib_rand() even) ? chest : coffin

      // pass 4: fixed cells
      map[(1,2)] = open                     // never face a wall on arrival
      place ladders at (7,3) and (3,7)      // up/down swapped by parity
      if level == 10: delete the down ladder    // no level 11
      if level == 1:  arrival up-ladder at (1,1), delete the (7,3) up

      // pass 5: populate monsters (see below), then return
\end{verbatim}

A cell byte packs two fields: the low nibble is the \textbf{feature}
(0~open, 1~wall, 2~trapdoor, 3~secret door, 4~door, 5~chest, 6~coffin,
7~ladder~down, 8~ladder~up, 9~revealed trapdoor, \texttt{C}~force field)
and the high nibble is a \textbf{monster slot} occupying the cell. A cell
blocks movement when its feature is a wall (1), a secret door (3), or a
force field (any value $\ge$ \texttt{A}).

The ``secret door'' weighting hides a vestige: the edge-feature table
actually lists trapdoor codes, which a later override rewrites to secret
doors --- evidence the design once put trapdoors on the lattice and
changed its mind. A faithful port can collapse this to the three outcomes
above.

Figure~\ref{fig:dng-gen} shows the five passes as a flowchart. The only
loop that varies with depth is pass~2 (walls scale as $2\times level+1$);
passes~3 and~4 add containers and ladders; the level-1 and level-10
special cases in pass~4 are the two decisions on the right.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[dg, >=Stealth, node distance=6.5mm and 10mm]
  \node[dgterminal] (e) {DNG\_GEN(level)};
  \node[dgprocess, below=of e] (seed)
        {seed maze PRNG\\\scriptsize from place/x/y/continent/level};
  \node[dgprocess, below=of seed] (tmpl)
        {map = copy(DNG\_TEMPLATE)\\\scriptsize border + even/even pillars};
