\section{The dungeon view: ray marching}

The first-person dungeon view is drawn by [[DNG_DRAW]], a \textbf{ray
marcher}. There is no stored 3-D model; the renderer walks the maze cell
by cell straight ahead and draws the wireframe in converging perspective
until it hits something solid:

\begin{verbatim}
    draw_view():                           // DNG_DRAW / DNG_MARCH
      cell = player_cell
      for depth in 1 .. VIEW_DEPTH:        // up to ~10 cells ahead
          cell += facing                   // step one cell forward
          ahead = feature_at(cell)
          // the two side cells: rotate facing +/-90 degrees
          left  = feature_at(cell + rot_left(facing))
          right = feature_at(cell + rot_right(facing))
          draw_slice(depth, ahead, left, right)   // walls/doors/openings
          if solid(ahead): break           // the view is blocked
\end{verbatim}

Rotating the facing vector is exact integer arithmetic: if facing is
$(dx, dy)$, then left is $(dy, -dx)$ and right is $(-dy, dx)$. The
\emph{perspective} is entirely in a table, not the code: [[DNG_GEOM]] is a
packed pool of converging screen coordinates --- ten entries (depths
1--10) for each box edge --- and each of the dozen drawing primitives
(left wall, right wall, ahead wall, door, ladder, force field, the 3-D
coffin box) reads its line endpoints from that table at the current depth
and strokes them. Drawing the same feature ``smaller and further in''
across depths is just indexing deeper into [[DNG_GEOM]].

Monsters and items in view are drawn by [[SHAPE_DRAW]], a scaled
vector-stroke interpreter. A shape is a list of $(x, y, \mathit{flag})$
vertex triples ($x$ relative to a centre, $y$ to a baseline, flag~0 =
move, nonzero = draw a line); a $(0,0)$ triple terminates. The shape is
scaled down by halving its coordinates once per unit of depth (a
sign-preserving shift), so the same monster outline shrinks with distance.
The 25 monster/object outlines are rendered as a figure in the dungeon
chapter.

\section{Shop pricing and haggling}

Every shop transaction prices an item as a base cost scaled by a
\textbf{charisma factor}, so a charismatic buyer pays less and sells for
more --- the game's only ``skill check'' on a social stat.

\begin{verbatim}
    price(item_index):                     // PRICE_MUL and callers
        base   = ITEM_COST[item_index]     // = item_index^2 (a squares table)
        factor = haggle_factor(charisma, wisdom, intelligence)
        return base * factor               // formed by repeated addition
\end{verbatim}

The base cost is the \emph{square} of the item's index --- later, better
items in each shop's list cost quadratically more --- read from a small
precomputed squares table ([[ITEM_COST]]) rather than multiplied at run
time. The charisma-derived factor discounts purchases and inflates sale
proceeds; charisma, wisdom, and intelligence all feed it. A port computes
$\mathit{index}^2 \times \mathit{factor}$ directly; the repeated-addition
multiply and the lookup table are 6502 conveniences.

The six shop classes (armour, grocery, weapons, magic, pub, transport)
share this pricing and a common buy/sell skeleton, differing only in which
owned-item array they touch and their flavour text. The transport shop is
special: a purchased craft is written into the world as an object record
(chapter~\ref{ch:datastructures}) at a free cell beside the shop, to be
boarded outdoors.

\section{Monster spawning and pursuit}

Outdoors, monsters are spawned into the object-record table by an
end-of-turn check gated on \textbf{difficulty}: each monster kind has a
\emph{tier} 0--10 ([[MON_TIER]]), and a kind can spawn only when its tier
is at or below a rising difficulty bar (so tougher monsters appear as the
player progresses). A spawned monster's hit points and the experience it
grants both scale from its tier ($\mathit{tier\_hp} = 10 \times
\mathit{tier}$). Spawn position respects terrain class --- sea monsters in
water, land monsters on land.

Pursuit is greedy distance-closing. Each turn an active monster steps to
reduce its distance to the player, where distance is an integer square
root of the squared coordinate differences (an explicit
integer-square-root routine appears in several overlays). Four monster
kinds are ranged attackers that fire instead of closing when in line.
Melee resolution rolls to hit against the defender's armour (plus charisma
for NPCs) and applies damage to the target's hit points; a monster reduced
to zero frees its object-record slot and grants its tier-scaled
experience.

Towns and castles use the same pursuit and melee logic on their 16-slot
NPC table, with the kind code selecting hostile (home and attack) versus
peaceful (wander, trade, or perform) behaviour. Figure~\ref{fig:npc-ai}
shows that per-NPC behaviour as a state machine keyed on the slot's kind
code: an empty slot is skipped, a hostile (kind~3) homes and strikes when
adjacent, and a wanderer (kind~4) drifts and occasionally sings or picks a
pocket. The whole table also has a global mood: once the player is caught
stealing, an [[AGGRO]] flag flips every NPC to the wander state and no one
will trade.

