\section{The space-flight model}

The space-combat mode ([[SPA]]) is the one part of the game that does
\emph{not} use the turn-based grid model. It is a real-time
rotation-and-thrust flight simulator --- closer to \emph{Asteroids} than to
the rest of \emph{Ultima} --- and a porter who treats it like the outdoor
move handler will get it wrong. The model is small and worth stating
exactly.

\textbf{Ship state.} The ship has an integer position on a wrap-around
torus, a \emph{signed} velocity vector, and a coarse heading that is one of
four cardinal directions:

\begin{verbatim}
    position   = (x, y)              // SHIP_X, SHIP_Y
    velocity   = (vx, vy)            // ZP_VX, ZP_VY, each signed -8..+8
    heading    = 0 | 1 | 2 | 3       // HEAD_CUR: up, right, down, left
\end{verbatim}

The original stores these in overlapping zero-page cells and shuffles them
between roles each step (the prior position doubles as a scratch base);
that juggling is a 6502 register-pressure artifact, not part of the model.
A port keeps position and velocity as two ordinary vectors.

\textbf{Integration.} Every physics step ([[PHYSICS]]) adds the velocity to
the position and wraps on the torus. The horizontal axis wraps in a narrow
band and the vertical axis is masked to seven bits:

\begin{verbatim}
    step():
        x = x + vx
        y = (y + vy) AND 0x7F                  // y wraps 0..127
        if x <  0x0E:  x = 0xF4                 // left edge -> right
        if x >= 0xF5:  x = 0x0E                 // right edge -> left
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Thrust and retro.} Acceleration is heading-indexed. Thrust adds a
fixed per-heading delta to the velocity; retro adds the negated delta. The
two delta tables ([[THRUST_DX]]/[[THRUST_DY]], [[RETRO_DX]]/[[RETRO_DY]])
are, by heading $0,1,2,3$:

\begin{verbatim}
    thrust delta = (0,-1) (+2,0) (0,+1) (-2,0)   // up right down left
    retro  delta = (0,+1) (-2,0) (0,-1) (+2,0)   // exactly negated
\end{verbatim}

Note the asymmetry: the horizontal thrust impulse is $\pm2$ but the
vertical is only $\pm1$, because the hi-res pixel aspect makes a vertical
step cover more visual distance. After each addition both velocity
components are clamped to $[-8, +8]$ ([[CLAMP_VEL]]), so the ship has a
top speed.

\textbf{Rotation.} The clockwise and counter-clockwise commands turn the
heading by one cardinal step, modulo four ([[CMD_CLOCKWISE]] adds $1$ and
masks with $3$; [[CMD_COUNTER]] subtracts $1$ and wraps $-1\to3$), and kick
a short turn-animation timer. The \emph{flight} heading is only this coarse
four-way value, but the \emph{rendered} ship is finer: the sprite index is
$\mathit{base}(\mathit{scale}) + \mathit{heading} + \mathit{rot\_step}$,
where the animation timer briefly sets $\mathit{rot\_step}$ to a non-zero
in-between frame so the turn looks smooth. A port can either reproduce the
27-frame rotation atlas (chapter~\ref{ch:rendering}) or simply draw the
four headings and skip the tween --- the simulation is identical either
way.

\textbf{Fuel.} Every manoeuvre burns from a 16-bit fuel reserve through
[[FUEL_BURN]]: thrust and retro cost $5$, each rotation costs $2$, firing
costs more. When fuel reaches zero every flight command is rejected (``No
fuel!! Wilt thou drift forever?!?''): the ship keeps its current velocity
and drifts. There is no friction --- velocity persists until thrust,
collision, or a rail clamp changes it.

\textbf{Hazards.} Two proximity tests run each step. Docking with the base
zeroes the velocity and refuels. Colliding with the enemy craft prints
``Crunch!'', reflects the velocity (a bounce), and subtracts shield. The
central star ([[STAR_HAZARD]]) is graded by distance ([[ACTOR_DIST]]):
inside the lethal radius the ship melts (``Thy ship melts near the star!''
$\to$ respawn); in the surrounding warning band only a hazard sound plays.

\textbf{The Space Ace counter.} A kill ([[HIT_ENEMY]]) awards $+100$
experience (saturating at $9999$) and increments the persistent vessel
counter [[PLR_VESSELS]] with saturation. This counter is the
\emph{only} bridge out of the flight model: reaching exactly $20$
($\$14$) announces the rank of Space Ace, and the castle quest reads the
same counter to gate the princess rescue that opens the endgame
(chapter~\ref{ch:architecture}). The flight model is otherwise self-contained.

\section{Character generation: the point-buy}

A new character ([[GEN]]) is built by distributing a fixed pool of points
across six attributes, then applying race and class bonuses. The exact
numbers matter because they define the legal range of a starting character.

\textbf{The six attributes} are 16-bit values in a fixed order ---
Strength, Agility, Stamina, Charisma, Wisdom, Intelligence --- stored
contiguously so that attribute $i$ ($1 \le i \le 6$) lives at
[[PLR_HITS]]$+2i$. Each starts at the floor and is raised by spending
points.

\textbf{The point-buy.} The editor ([[CHARGEN]]) seeds a pool of $30$
points ([[POINT_POOL]] $= \$1E$) and lets the player move points into the
six stats under two hard limits: a per-stat floor of $10$ ($\$0A$) and a
ceiling of $25$ ($\$19$). The player cannot leave the editor until the
pool is empty.

\begin{verbatim}
    point_buy():
        for each attribute: attribute = 10        // the floor
        pool = 30
        loop:
            on raise(stat):                        // right arrow
                if pool > 0 and stat < 25:
                    stat += 1; pool -= 1
            on lower(stat):                        // left arrow
                if stat > 10:
                    stat -= 1; pool += 1
            on done: if pool == 0: break
\end{verbatim}

So an unmodified character has every stat in $[10, 25]$ and their sum is
exactly $6\times10 + 30 = 90$.

\textbf{Race and class bonuses} are applied \emph{after} the point-buy,
from hardcoded per-choice deltas:

\begin{verbatim}
    race:   Human  +5 INT
            Elf    +5 AGI
            Dwarf  +5 STR
            Bobbit +10 WIS, -5 STR
    class:  Fighter +10 STR, +10 AGI
            Cleric  +10 WIS
            Wizard  +10 INT
            Thief   +10 AGI
\end{verbatim}

A subtlety a faithful port must preserve: these bonuses are added with
\emph{no ceiling re-check}, so a race or class bonus can legitimately push
an attribute above the $25$ point-buy ceiling (a Dwarf Fighter can reach
$25+5+10 = 40$ Strength). The ceiling governs only how the player
\emph{spends points}, not the final stat. Sex is purely cosmetic and
modifies no attribute.

\textbf{Derived starting values.} Hit points, food, coin, and the initial
world and inventory are \emph{not} computed from the attributes. They come
from [[GAME_IMAGE]], a 13-page snapshot of a fresh game embedded in the
overlay and stamped into the player and world state when the new game
launches; experience starts at zero, so the starting level is
$\lfloor 0/1000\rfloor + 1 = 1$ (chapter~\ref{ch:datastructures}). A port
can hold the same starting bundle as plain initialisation data.

\chapter{The rendering pipeline}
\label{ch:rendering}

This chapter describes how the game gets pixels on the screen, and ---
because that is where a port spends most of its surprises --- draws a sharp
line between what is \textbf{Apple~II-specific} (and must be replaced
wholesale) and what is \textbf{portable} (and can be carried over almost
verbatim). The machine-specific layer is concentrated in the
\texttt{STUPH} library (chapter~\ref{ch:stuph}), reached through its fixed
jump vectors; the overlays and engine above it deal in tile codes,
glyph indices, and vector shapes, none of which assume an Apple~II.

\section{The Apple II hi-res screen (replace entirely)}

Everything in this section a port discards and reimplements against its
own framebuffer.

\textbf{The bitmap layout is interleaved.} The Apple~II hi-res screen is
$280 \times 192$ pixels, but consecutive scanlines are \emph{not}
consecutive in memory: the row-to-address mapping shuffles rows so that
line $r$ begins at a non-linear offset (the formula appears verbatim in
the \texttt{MAKE.INDATA} decompressor and again in every blitter). A port
writes to a flat $\mathit{width} \times \mathit{height}$ buffer and never
thinks about this again.

\textbf{Colour is an NTSC artifact.} Each byte holds seven pixels; the
eighth bit selects one of two colour pairs, and the actual colour of an
on-pixel depends on its column parity and its neighbours (two adjacent
on-pixels read as white). The rendered figures throughout this document
approximate these artifact colours. A port targets RGB directly and treats
the palette as a fixed lookup, not an emergent property of bit positions.

\textbf{Two display pages, flipped.} Pages~1 ([[$2000]]) and~2
([[$4000]]) are two full screens; the hardware shows one while the program
draws the other, then flips. The library implements this with a single
zero-page value, [[ZP_PAGE_XOR]], XORed into the high byte of every screen
address before a write ([[$00]] selects page~1, [[$60]] selects page~2);
[[PAGE_FLIP]] shows the page just drawn and toggles that value. A port uses
ordinary double-buffering (draw to a back buffer, present it) --- the XOR
trick is just how you select a buffer when both live at fixed addresses.

\textbf{Soft switches and cycle timing.} Mode changes (graphics vs text,
page~1 vs page~2, hi-res on) are memory-mapped \emph{soft switches}; the
frame rate is paced off the vertical-blank interrupt. None of this
survives a port; the portable content is the \emph{timing} (how many
frames an animation step lasts), not the mechanism.

\section{The glyph banks (portable data)}

Both the text and the tile graphics are \textbf{glyph banks} --- small
bitmap fonts --- and these \emph{are} portable: they are just pixel data
with a documented layout, rendered as figures in the \texttt{STUPH}
chapter.

\begin{description}
\item[The text font] is 128 glyphs of $7 \times 8$ pixels, stored
  plane-major (all glyphs' scanline~0, then all glyphs' scanline~1, \dots)
  --- a storage order chosen so the blitter can walk one scanline across
  consecutive glyphs, irrelevant to a port that simply indexes a glyph
  array.
\item[The outdoor tile bank] is 48 map tiles, each two glyphs wide and
  taller, drawn through the same machinery. Terrain, towns, ships, and
  monsters are all tiles in this bank.
\item[The town/castle tile bank] (\texttt{MAPCHARS}) is an alternate
  128-glyph bank loaded over the font when inside a town or castle; it
  adds wall sections, counters, and an inverse-video alphabet so shop
  signs can be spelled into the map grid.
\end{description}

Two animation tricks live at this layer and are worth a porter's note:
text routines XOR an \textbf{inverse-video mask} ([[ZP_INVERSE]], [[$00]]
or [[$7F]]) into every emitted byte, which the engine flips to flash low
hit points and food; and several tiles animate by rotating or swapping
their plane bytes frame to frame (the water shimmer, creature wobble). The
first is a portable ``draw this glyph inverted'' flag; the second is
portable two-frame animation.

\section{The two rendering styles}

Above the pixel layer, the seven modes split cleanly into two rendering
styles, both portable.

\subsection*{Tile viewport (outdoors, towns, castles)}

The grid modes draw a fixed \textbf{$19 \times 9$ tile window} centred on
the player ([[DRAW_MAP]]). The algorithm is entirely portable:

\begin{verbatim}
    draw_viewport(center_x, center_y):     // DRAW_MAP
        for vy in 0 .. 8:
            for vx in 0 .. 18:
                cell = map[center_x + vx - 9, center_y + vy - 4]
                blit_tile(tile_of(cell), vx, vy)
        overlay object/NPC records whose position falls in the window
        draw the player tile at the centre
\end{verbatim}

The map cell's value chooses the tile; object and NPC records are painted
over the terrain at their window-relative positions; the player is always
the centre tile. Outdoors the map is the decompressed continent; in towns
and castles it is the live \texttt{TCMAPS} buffer
(chapter~\ref{ch:datastructures}). This is the whole grid renderer.

\subsection*{Wireframe vector (dungeons, space, the endgame)}

The first-person modes store \emph{no bitmap}; they stroke lines computed
at draw time. There are two variants:

\begin{description}
\item[The dungeon ray marcher] (chapter~\ref{ch:algorithms}) walks the
  maze ahead and draws box edges from a perspective table, plus
  depth-scaled monster outlines. Portable: the table is converging screen
  coordinates per depth, the shapes are vertex lists.
\item[The space and endgame views] project moving objects (enemy craft,
  stars, the planet, Mondain, the gem) through fixed-point perspective and
  stroke or blit them. Space additionally uses an XOR sprite blitter so a
  sprite can be drawn and then erased by drawing it again --- a portable
  idea (XOR onto the back buffer), implemented here as two unrolled passes
  selected by a draw-mode flag.
\end{description}

The line drawing itself ([[LINE_TO]]) is a standard Bresenham-style
stroke into the current draw page with the current colour; only its output
target (the interleaved hi-res page) is machine-specific.

