\chapter{Porting notes: the 6502 idioms}
\label{ch:porting}

The preceding synthesis chapters describe the game in portable terms. This
one is the opposite: a catalogue of the \textbf{6502 and Apple~II idioms}
that recur throughout the assembly, what each one \emph{means}, and what a
port replaces it with. A reader translating the code will meet these
patterns constantly; recognising them is the difference between a faithful
port and a pile of mysteries. Each idiom below is annotated at its sites in
the assembly chapters; here they are collected with their intent.

\section{Self-modifying code}

The single most important thing to understand about this codebase is that
\textbf{it writes to its own instruction stream}, deliberately, as a normal
technique. Three flavours appear, each encoding a different kind of state.

\subsection*{Patched-JSR (and JMP) dispatch}

The command dispatchers do not use an indexed jump. Instead they
\emph{write a handler's address into the operand of a [[JSR]]
instruction} a few bytes ahead, then execute that [[JSR]]. The call target
is data, stored into the code. Every grid overlay does this for its command
table; the space overlay patches a [[JMP]] in its main loop the same way.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} a function-pointer table indexed by the command number,
\texttt{handler = TABLE[cmd]; handler()}. The patched operand \emph{is} the
table entry.
\end{quote}

\subsection*{Patched operands as variables}

Many ``variables'' are stored \emph{inside an instruction}. A loop limit
lives in the immediate operand of a [[CPX]]/[[CPY]]; a moving source
pointer lives in the absolute operand of an [[LDA]]; a stream cursor is the
operand of a [[STA]] that is incremented in place. The annotations name
each such byte with a [[label = *+1]] (or [[*+2]]) convention so the
patched operand has a symbol.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} an ordinary variable. Where the assembly reads
``[[LDA SHAPE_PTR]]'' with [[SHAPE_PTR]] being the operand of the [[LDA]]
itself, the port has a pointer variable and an ordinary load through it.
\end{quote}

A subtle consequence for \emph{byte-exact} reproduction (not for porting):
the value sitting in a self-modified operand \emph{on disk} is whatever it
was last left as, often a stale or sentinel value (the recurring
[[STALE_FFFF]] is one) that the running code overwrites before first use.
The assembly chapters emit the stale disk value and note it; a port simply
initialises its variable.

\subsection*{Patched opcodes (toggling actors)}

Occasionally a whole \emph{opcode} byte is patched, not just an operand:
writing a [[JSR]] opcode where an [[RTS]] was (or vice versa) switches a
routine on or off --- a called subroutine becomes an immediate return.
This toggles optional per-frame actors without a flag test.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} a boolean (``is this actor active?'') checked before the
call.
\end{quote}

\section{Multi-entry routines}

Several routines have two entry points that differ only in a flag, packed
together with two tricks that exploit how the 6502 decodes the byte
\emph{after} an opcode.

\subsection*{The carry dual-entry (\texttt{CLC} / \texttt{.byte \$B0} / \texttt{SEC})}

A routine wants two entries that differ only in the carry flag. It writes:
[[CLC]] (the silent entry), then the byte [[$B0]] (a [[BCS]] opcode), then
[[SEC]] (the second entry). Entering at the top clears carry and then the
[[$B0]] consumes the following [[SEC]] byte as its branch \emph{operand} ---
the [[SEC]] never executes. Entering one byte later runs [[SEC]] normally.
Two entries, one body, distinguished by carry. (Used by [[TICK]]/%
[[TICK_SND]] and the disk-prompt routine.)

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} two functions, or one function with a boolean parameter.
\end{quote}

\subsection*{The \texttt{BIT}-absolute skip (\texttt{.byte \$2C})}

To give a routine a second entry that skips its first instruction (often
an [[LDA \#imm]]), a [[$2C]] byte (a [[BIT]]-absolute opcode) is placed
before it: falling in from above, the [[$2C]] turns the next two bytes
into a harmless [[BIT]] of some address; jumping past it runs them as the
real instruction. This is how one routine offers ``with this default
value'' and ``with the value already in A'' entries.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} an optional/defaulted parameter.
\end{quote}

\section{Inline-argument calling conventions}

Many routines take their arguments \emph{from the bytes following the
[[JSR]]}, not from registers or the stack. The file library's load/save
calls are followed by a path string; the text printer is followed by the
zero-terminated message; the menu picker is followed by several count and
pointer bytes. The routine reads the return address off the stack, consumes
the inline bytes, and adjusts the return address to land past them.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{Port as:} ordinary function arguments. ``[[JSR PRINT]] then the
text bytes'' becomes \texttt{print("text")}. (Recognising these sites
matters even for reading the disassembly: the bytes after such a call are
\emph{data}, and a disassembler that treats them as code produces garbage
--- a frequent trap noted throughout these chapters.)
\end{quote}

\section{Numbers and tables}

\textbf{Binary quantities, BCD displays.} As the data-structure chapter
notes, all quantities are 16-bit binary; only the two on-screen counters
are BCD. The decimal-display path runs a double-dabble binary-to-BCD
conversion. A port keeps integers and formats on output.

\textbf{Precomputed tables instead of arithmetic.} Costs are read from a
squares table rather than multiplied; multiplication itself is done by
repeated addition; perspective is a coordinate table, not a projection
calculation; the hi-res row address is sometimes a table. These are speed
tricks for a 1\,MHz 8-bit CPU. A port computes the value directly --- but
should preserve the \emph{table contents} where they encode tuning (the
monster tiers, the per-transport tick costs, the attribute bonuses), since
those are game-design data, not optimisations.

\textbf{16-bit values are little-endian pairs}, low byte first, and the
code addresses the high byte as [[label+1]]. Pointers in zero page follow
the same convention and are dereferenced with the indirect-indexed
addressing mode --- the portable reading is just ``a 16-bit pointer.''

\section{Machine and OS dependencies}

A few hooks into the Apple~II and ProDOS have no portable content beyond
their effect:

\begin{description}
\item[Soft switches] ([[$C0xx]]) toggle graphics modes, display pages, and
  read the keyboard; a port calls its own platform's equivalents.
\item[The vertical-blank interrupt] paces animation. Only the resulting
  frame counts are portable; one mode even borrows a mouse card purely as
  a VBL source on machines that lack a direct one.
\item[The file library] wraps ProDOS file calls (and a transparent
  \texttt{/RAM} cache); a port maps these to ordinary file or asset loads.
  The seven overlays and the data files become seven code modules and
  their bundled assets.
\item[The reset vector] is hooked at two points (the bootstrap and the
  victory screen) so a hardware reset re-enters the game rather than
  dropping to the monitor --- cosmetic on a port.
\end{description}

None of these change behaviour a player sees; they are the seams where the
1986 program meets its host, and a port re-cuts them against a different
host without touching the game above.

\part{Implementation: the annotated program}
\label{part:implementation}

\noindent
This second part is the evidence base for the first: the complete original
program as literate, annotated 6502 assembly. It proceeds in load order ---
the disk layout and boot chain, the launcher and title, the resident
library and engine, the seven mode overlays, and the bundled game data ---
and every chunk assembles to bytes identical to the original disk. Where a
routine realises a mechanism described abstractly in
Part~\ref{part:design}, the prose names it for cross-reference.

\chapter{Disk layout and boot chain}

\section{Disk image format}

The disk image is a 140K \texttt{.dsk} file: 35 tracks of 16 sectors
of 256 bytes, stored in DOS~3.3 logical order. The volume on it,
however, is a ProDOS volume, which addresses the disk in 512-byte
\emph{blocks} (two sectors each, 8 blocks per track, 280 blocks per
volume).

Three sector orderings are therefore in play, and all the extraction
tooling reduces to composing two fixed permutations:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Physical order} --- the order sectors pass under the
  drive head; the order in the sector address fields. The controller
  PROM and the boot code address physical sectors.
\item \textbf{DOS 3.3 logical order} --- the order sectors are stored
  in the \texttt{.dsk} file. Physical sector $P$ of track $T$ is at
  file offset $T \cdot 4096 + \mathit{DOS}[P] \cdot 256$ with
  $$\mathit{DOS} = [0,7,14,6,13,5,12,4,11,3,10,2,9,1,8,15].$$
\item \textbf{ProDOS block order} --- ProDOS block $B$ lives on track
  $\lfloor B/8 \rfloor$; its two halves are ProDOS logical sectors
  $2(B \bmod 8)$ and $2(B \bmod 8)+1$, which map to physical sectors
  through $$\mathit{PRO} = [0,2,4,6,8,10,12,14,1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15].$$
  Note the two halves of a block always sit two physical sectors
  apart --- a fact the boot block's sector reader exploits
  (section~\ref{sec:diskii-read-block}).
\end{itemize}

The script \texttt{.claude/scripts/prodos\_extract.py} implements this
mapping, walks the ProDOS volume directory, and extracts every file
into \texttt{reference/} as the flat reference binaries that all
assembly targets verify against.

