\section{Calibrated delays}

The game must run at the same speed on a 1\,MHz Apple ][+, an
accelerated machine, and a IIgs. [[VDELAY]] is the model for how the
library copes: on a IIgs it drops [[CYAREG]] to 1\,MHz around the
delay loop and restores it after; on anything else it reads
[[DRIVE_OFF]] first --- a classic trick, because Zip-Chip-style
accelerator boards drop to 1\,MHz for a while whenever a Disk II soft
switch is touched.

<<stuph delay>>=
        ORG $15E9
VDELAY  SUBROUTINE
        ; Delay roughly A*1.3ms at 1 MHz, on any machine.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A       -- delay count (outer iterations)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   IIgs: save CYAREG, force 1 MHz, delay, restore.
        ;   Otherwise: touch DRIVE_OFF so accelerator boards
        ;   self-slow, then delay.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A
        BIT GS_SPEED                    ; bit 6 set = not a IIgs
        BVS DELAY_SLOW
        STA .cnt                        ; patch the reload below
        LDA CYAREG
        AND #$9F
        PHA
        AND #$7F                        ; clear the fast bit
        STA CYAREG
.cnt = *+1
        LDA #$00                        ; (patched: the saved count)
        JSR DELAY_256
        PLA
        STA CYAREG                      ; back to the caller's speed
        LDA #$00
        RTS
DELAY_SLOW
        ; Nudge accelerators down to 1 MHz, then delay A units.
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
DELAY_256
        ; Busy-wait A*256 SBC loops (A=0 acts as 256).
        SEC
.outer  PHA
.inner  SBC #$01
        BNE .inner
        PLA
        SBC #$01
        BNE .outer
        RTS
@ %def VDELAY DELAY_SLOW DELAY_256

\section{Clearing, flipping and copying the hi-res pages}

[[VIEW_CLEAR]] blacks out scanlines 8--151 (the viewport area
between the border rows) on the \emph{draw} page, columns 1--38,
writing [[$80]] (black, palette bit set).

<<stuph view clear>>=
        ORG $1617
VIEW_CLEAR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Black out the map viewport on the draw page.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   For scanlines 8..$97, write $80 to screen bytes 1..$26
        ;   of the page selected by ZP_PAGE_XOR.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX #$08
.row    LDA HGR_ROW_LO,X
        STA .dstl
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI,X
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA .dsth
        LDY #$26
        LDA #$80
.dstl = *+1
.dsth = *+2
.col    STA HGR1,Y
        DEY
        BNE .col
        INX
        CPX #$98
        BCC .row
        RTS
@ %def VIEW_CLEAR

[[PAGE_FLIP]] is the frame boundary: wait for vertical blank, show
the page that was just drawn, retarget drawing at the other page,
and play out any sound effects the frame queued.

<<stuph page flip>>=
        ORG $1637
PAGE_FLIP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; End of frame: display the draw page, swap buffers,
        ; play queued sound effects.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   FRAME_SYNC; display page 1 or 2 per ZP_PAGE_XOR;
        ;   ZP_PAGE_XOR ^= ZP_PAGE_TGL; graphics on; drain the
        ;   effect queue until empty.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X
        JSR FRAME_SYNC
        LDX #$00
        LDA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        BEQ .show
        INX
.show   CMP TXTPAGE1,X                  ; soft switch: show drawn page
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        BIT TXTCLR
.drain  JSR SFX_DRAIN
        BNE .drain
        RTS
@ %def PAGE_FLIP

[[PAGE_COPY]] copies the \emph{displayed} page onto the \emph{draw}
page --- 8\,KB --- used when the engine wants to start a frame from
what the player currently sees rather than from a stale back buffer.

<<stuph page copy>>=
        ORG $1719
PAGE_COPY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Copy the displayed hi-res page onto the draw page.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   dst high byte = $20 EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR (the draw page);
        ;   src = dst EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL (the other page); copy
        ;   $20 pages of 256 bytes.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$20
        TAX                             ; 32 pages = 8 KB
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA .dsth
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA .srch
        LDY #$00
.srch = *+2
.cp     LDA HGR2,Y
.dsth = *+2
        STA HGR1,Y
        INY
        BNE .cp
        INC .srch
        INC .dsth
        DEX
        BNE .cp
        RTS
@ %def PAGE_COPY

\section{Sound switches and the accelerator nudge}

[[SOUND_SET]] records the master sound flag. On a IIgs it also picks
the system speed policy: sound on runs fast (effects slow the clock
themselves around playback); sound off parks the machine at 1\,MHz so
the busy-wait game pacing stays right. [[ACCEL_NUDGE]] gives
accelerator boards their Disk-II-soft-switch slowdown cue whenever
sound is \emph{off} --- when sound is on, the speaker timing loops
already do it.

<<stuph sound enable>>=
        ORG $1651
SOUND_SET
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Set the master sound flag and the IIgs speed policy.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A       -- 0 = sound off, nonzero = sound on
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   SOUND_ON <- #$00 or #$FF. On a IIgs, sound on restores
        ;   full speed (effects slow themselves around playback);
        ;   sound off parks the clock at 1 MHz so busy-wait pacing
        ;   stays right.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   SOUND_ON; CYAREG fast bit on a IIgs.
        CMP #$00
        BEQ .store
        LDA #$FF
.store  STA SOUND_ON
        PHA
        BIT GS_SPEED                    ; not a IIgs: done
        BVS .done
        CMP #$01                        ; C = sound on
        LDA CYAREG
        AND #$1F
        BCC .slow                       ; off -> stay at 1 MHz
        ORA #$80                        ; on -> full speed
.slow   STA CYAREG
.done   PLA
        RTS
@ %def SOUND_SET

<<stuph accel nudge>>=
        ORG $1670
ACCEL_NUDGE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Keep accelerator boards at 1 MHz when sound is off.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If SOUND_ON is clear, read DRIVE_OFF -- Zip-Chip-style
        ;   boards drop to 1 MHz after a Disk II soft switch access.
        ;   When sound is on the speaker loops do this themselves.
        BIT SOUND_ON
        BMI .done
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
.done   RTS
@ %def ACCEL_NUDGE

\section{File loading through the RAM-disk cache}

The library's file loader sits on top of the [[$B700]] file library
and adds one feature: on a 128K machine it shadows every file it
loads onto the \texttt{/RAM} volume, and tries \texttt{/RAM} first
the next time --- so revisiting a town or dungeon needs no disk
access at all. The caller parses the filename into [[MLIB_PATH]]
first (via [[MLIB_PARSE_PATH]]); [[FILE_LOAD]] loads at the file's
own aux-type address, [[FILE_LOAD_AT]] at the address in Y/A. The
error buzz is suppressed around the speculative \texttt{/RAM} read,
and a full RAM volume (translated error 9) silently falls back to
deleting the cached copy.

<<stuph file load>>=
        ORG $1679
FILE_LOAD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Load the file named in MLIB_PATH, through the /RAM cache.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   MLIB_PATH -- parsed pathname (length-prefixed)
        ;   FILE_LOAD_AT only: Y/A = load address lo/hi
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Build "/RAM/<name>" in RAM_NAME; on a 128K machine try
        ;   loading that (buzz suppressed). On a miss, BLOAD from
        ;   disk (at aux address or at Y/A per the entry point),
        ;   then BSAVE a copy to /RAM for next time.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C set on error, A = translated error code.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   LOAD_AUX_FLAG, RAM_NAME, MLIB_QUIET (restored)
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        JMP .load
FILE_LOAD_AT
        STA .addr+1
        STY .addr
        LDA #$00
        BEQ .mode
.load   LDA #$80
.mode   STA LOAD_AUX_FLAG               ; bit 7: load at aux address
        LDY MLIB_PATH                   ; pathname length
        LDA #$00
        STA RAM_NAME,Y                  ; zero-terminate the copy
        DEY
.copy   LDA MLIB_PATH+1,Y
        STA RAM_NAME,Y
        DEY
        BPL .copy
        LDA MLIB_QUIET
        PHA
        STY MLIB_QUIET                  ; Y=$FF: no buzz while we probe
        LDA GP_MACHID
        AND #$30
        CMP #$30                        ; 128K machine?
        BNE .disk
        JSR MLIB_BLOAD_P                ; try the /RAM shadow copy
        DC.W RAM_PATH
        BCC .exit                       ; cache hit
.disk   BIT LOAD_AUX_FLAG
        BPL .at
        JSR MLIB_BLOAD_P                ; load at the file's aux address
        DC.W RAM_NAME
        JMP .ckerr
.at     JSR MLIB_BLOAD_AT_P             ; load at the caller's address
.addr   DC.W $FFFF                      ; (patched per call)
        DC.W RAM_NAME
.ckerr  BCS .exit
        LDA GP_MACHID
        AND #$30
        CMP #$30
        BNE .exit
        LDY #$01                        ; shadow the load to /RAM:
.args   LDA PARM_RW+2,Y                 ; where the data landed
        STA .sva,Y
        LDA PARM_RW+6,Y                 ; how many bytes arrived
        STA .svl,Y
        DEY
        BPL .args
        JSR MLIB_BSAVE_P
.sva    DC.W $0000                      ; (patched: data address)
.svl    DC.W $0000                      ; (patched: data length)
        DC.W RAM_PATH
        BCC .exit
        CMP #$09                        ; /RAM full?
        BNE .fail
        JSR MLIB_DESTROY_P              ; drop the partial copy
        DC.W RAM_PATH
        CLC
        BCC .exit
.fail   SEC
.exit   TAX
        PLA
        STA MLIB_QUIET
        TXA
        RTS
LOAD_AUX_FLAG
        DC.B $00                        ; bit 7: FILE_LOAD entry used
RAM_PATH
        HEX 2f 52 41 4d 2f              ; "/RAM/" -- prefix of RAM_NAME
RAM_NAME
        DS.B 16,$00                     ; the bare name, copied per call
@ %def FILE_LOAD FILE_LOAD_AT LOAD_AUX_FLAG RAM_PATH RAM_NAME

\section{The pixel color}

[[COLOR_SET]] patches the two color-mask immediates inside [[PLOT]].
Hi-res color depends on byte parity, so each of the eight colors has
an even-column and an odd-column mask --- the same six non-monochrome
patterns every Apple II program uses ([[$2A]]/[[$55]] violet--green,
[[$AA]]/[[$D5]] blue--orange), plus black and white in both palettes.

<<stuph color set>>=
        ORG $173B
COLOR_SET
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Select the color that PLOT and LINE_TO will draw with.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A       -- color 0-7 (hi-res palette pairs)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Patch PLOT's two immediate operands with the color's
        ;   even-column and odd-column bit masks.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   PLOT_CEVEN, PLOT_CODD
        AND #$07
        TAX
        LDA COLOR_EVEN,X
        STA PLOT_CEVEN
        LDA COLOR_ODD,X
        STA PLOT_CODD
        RTS
COLOR_EVEN
        HEX 00 2a 55 7f 80 aa d5 ff     ; even screen byte
COLOR_ODD
        HEX 00 55 2a 7f 80 d5 aa ff     ; odd screen byte
@ %def COLOR_SET COLOR_EVEN COLOR_ODD

\section{Machine state and the interrupt handler}

The library's machine-detection state, the ProDOS interrupt
parameter block, and the interrupt handler itself. The remarkable
part: the game looks for an \textbf{AppleMouse card not to read the
mouse, but to use it as a VBL interrupt source} --- [[SETMOUSE]] mode
8 generates interrupts at vertical blank without tracking motion at
all, and the handler just calls \textsc{servemouse} and decrements
[[VBL_TICK]]. [[FRAME_SYNC]] then locks the frame rate to it.

<<stuph machine state>>=
        ORG $175B
GS_SPEED
        DC.B $FF                ; IIgs: saved CYAREG bit 7; $FF = not a
                                ;   IIgs (bit 6 set, tested with BIT/BVS)
HAS_VBL DC.B $00                ; $FF = RDVBL ($C019) is readable
VBL_TICK
        DC.B $00                ; decremented by each VBL interrupt
MOUSE_CN
        DC.B $C0                ; mouse slot firmware page ($Cn)
MOUSE_N0
        DC.B $00                ; mouse slot << 4; 0 = no mouse card
INT_PARM
        DC.B $02                ; ALLOC_INTERRUPT: 2 parameters
INT_NUM DC.B $00                ; -> interrupt number (for DEALLOC)
        DC.W INT_HANDLER
KEY_XSAV
        DC.B $00                ; caller's X across KEY_GET
KEY_YSAV
        DC.B $00                ; caller's Y across KEY_GET
ANIM_CNT1
        DC.B $01                ; frames until the water scrolls
ANIM_CNT2
        DC.B $03                ; frames until the castle flag waves
ANIM_CNT3
        DC.B $02                ; frames until the tower flag waves
DITHER_IX
        DC.B $01                ; walking index into MLIB_CODE noise
INT_HANDLER
        ; ProDOS interrupt handler: acknowledge the mouse card's
        ; VBL interrupt and count it. Claims every interrupt (CLC).
        CLD
INT_SRV = *+1
        JSR MOUSE_FW_DEF        ; (patched: the slot's SERVEMOUSE)
        DEC VBL_TICK
        CLC
        RTS
@ %def GS_SPEED HAS_VBL VBL_TICK MOUSE_CN MOUSE_N0 INT_PARM INT_NUM
@ %def KEY_XSAV KEY_YSAV ANIM_CNT1 ANIM_CNT2 ANIM_CNT3 DITHER_IX
@ %def INT_HANDLER INT_SRV

\section{Machine detection}

[[LIB_INIT]] runs once at game start. It scans slots 7 down to 1 for
the AppleMouse firmware signature (bytes [[$20]]/[[$00]]/[[$D6]] at
offsets [[$0C]]/[[$11]]/[[$FB]] of the slot ROM), hooks its VBL
interrupt if found, then identifies the machine from the ROM id
bytes: an enhanced-IIe-class ROM means [[RDVBL]] can be polled, and
a positive [[MON_IDROUTINE]] means a IIgs, whose speed register is
saved and forced fast. It ends by zeroing the queues and switching
on full-screen hi-res.

<<stuph firmware byte>>=
        ORG $1773
FW_BYTE SUBROUTINE
        ; Read a byte of the mouse slot's firmware page.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   Y       -- offset into the $Cn00 firmware page
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Point ZP_FW_PTR at MOUSE_CN's page and load its byte Y.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A = the firmware byte; X = $Cn; ZP_FW_PTR+1 = $Cn.
        LDX #$00
        STX ZP_FW_PTR
        LDX MOUSE_CN
        STX ZP_FW_PTR+1
        LDA (ZP_FW_PTR),Y
        RTS
@ %def FW_BYTE

<<stuph machine init>>=
        ORG $177F
LIB_INIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; One-time hardware setup: find a mouse card for VBL
        ; interrupts, classify the machine, enter hi-res.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Scan $C7xx..$C1xx for the AppleMouse signature; if
        ;   found, record the slot and call MOUSE_HOOK. Then read
        ;   ROM_MACHID/ROM_SUBID: enhanced-class ROMs set HAS_VBL;
        ;   a IIgs (MON_IDROUTINE clears carry) saves its speed bit
        ;   in GS_SPEED and switches to fast. Clear the queues and
        ;   page state; display hi-res page 2, full screen.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   HAS_VBL, MOUSE_CN, MOUSE_N0, GS_SPEED, ZP_INVERSE,
        ;   ZP_KEY_CNT, ZP_SFX_CNT, ZP_PAGE_XOR, ZP_PAGE_TGL
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        SEI
        JSR SPEED_RESTORE
        LDA #$00
        STA HAS_VBL
        STA ZP_FW_PTR
        STA ZP_INVERSE
        LDX #$C7                        ; scan slot 7 first
.slot   STX ZP_FW_PTR+1
        LDY #$0C                        ; mouse firmware signature
        LDA (ZP_FW_PTR),Y
        CMP #$20
        BNE .next
        LDY #$11
        LDA (ZP_FW_PTR),Y
        BNE .next
        LDY #$FB
        LDA (ZP_FW_PTR),Y
        CMP #$D6
        BNE .next
        TXA                             ; found one
        STA MOUSE_CN
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        STA MOUSE_N0                    ; $n0, the firmware's id reg
        JSR MOUSE_HOOK
        BNE .gs
.next   DEX
        CPX #$C1
        BCS .slot
.gs     LDX ROM_MACHID
        CPX #$06                        ; IIe or later?
        BNE .common
        LDX ROM_SUBID
        CPX #$F0
        BCS .common
        CPX #$E0                        ; $Ex = enhanced class
        BCC .common
        PHP
        DEC HAS_VBL                     ; RDVBL is pollable
        PLP
        BNE .common                     ; only $E0 can be a IIgs
        JSR MON_IDROUTINE
        BCS .common
        LDA CYAREG                      ; a IIgs: remember its speed,
        PHA                             ;   then run fast
        AND #$80
        STA GS_SPEED
        PLA
        AND #$9F
        ORA #$80
        STA CYAREG
.common LDA #$00
        STA ZP_KEY_CNT
        STA ZP_SFX_CNT
        STA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL
        CLI
        BIT HIRES
        BIT TXTPAGE2
        BIT MIXCLR
.rts    RTS
MOUSE_HOOK
        ; Allocate a ProDOS interrupt for the mouse card, point
        ; INT_HANDLER's SERVEMOUSE call at the slot firmware, then
        ; INITMOUSE and SETMOUSE mode 8 (VBL interrupts only --
        ; the card is used purely as a frame clock).
        LDA MOUSE_N0
        BEQ .rts                        ; no card: nothing to hook
        LDA #$02
        STA INT_PARM
        JSR MLI
        DC.B $40                        ; ALLOC_INTERRUPT
        DC.W INT_PARM
        LDY #$13                        ; firmware offset: SERVEMOUSE
        JSR FW_BYTE
        STA INT_SRV
        STX INT_SRV+1
        LDY #$19                        ; firmware offset: INITMOUSE
        JSR MOUSE_CALL
        LDA #$08                        ; mode 8: VBL interrupts only
MOUSE_SETMODE
        LDY #$12                        ; firmware offset: SETMOUSE
MOUSE_CALL
        ; Call mouse firmware routine Y (offset table entry) with
        ; the required X=$Cn / Y=$n0 register convention.
        SEI
        PHA
        JSR FW_BYTE                     ; A := entry low byte; X := $Cn
        STA ZP_FW_PTR                   ; ZP_FW_PTR+1 is already $Cn
        LDY MOUSE_N0
        PLA
        JMP (ZP_FW_PTR)
@ %def LIB_INIT MOUSE_HOOK MOUSE_SETMODE MOUSE_CALL

[[LIB_SHUTDOWN]] is the mirror image, called before the game quits
to ProDOS: back to text mode, mouse off, interrupt deallocated,
IIgs speed restored.

<<stuph shutdown>>=
        ORG $1831
LIB_SHUTDOWN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Undo LIB_INIT before returning to ProDOS.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Map ROM in; full text window, clear screen, text mode;
        ;   if a mouse was hooked, SETMOUSE off and DEALLOC its
        ;   interrupt; fall into SPEED_RESTORE.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   MOUSE_N0, INT_PARM; CYAREG on a IIgs.
        BIT ROMIN                       ; make sure ROM is mapped
        JSR WIN_FULL
        JSR MON_HOME
        JSR MON_INIT                    ; text mode, full window
        LDA MOUSE_N0
        BEQ SPEED_RESTORE
        LDA #$00
        JSR MOUSE_SETMODE               ; mouse off
        LDY #$00
        STY MOUSE_N0
        INY
        STY INT_PARM                    ; 1 parameter this time
        JSR MLI
        DC.B $41                        ; DEALLOC_INTERRUPT
        DC.W INT_PARM
SPEED_RESTORE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Put a IIgs back at the speed it had before LIB_INIT.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Not a IIgs (GS_SPEED bit 6 set): do nothing. Otherwise
        ;   restore the saved fast bit into CYAREG.
        BIT GS_SPEED
        BVS .rts                        ; not a IIgs
        LDA CYAREG
        AND #$1F
        ORA GS_SPEED
        STA CYAREG
.rts    RTS
@ %def LIB_SHUTDOWN SPEED_RESTORE

\section{Plot and line}

The dungeon overlay's wireframe view is drawn with these. [[PLOT]]
draws a \emph{pair} of adjacent dots (one color pixel) at column
[[ZP_PX]], row [[ZP_PY]] --- rows are offset 16 scanlines down into
the viewport, and a zero entry in [[XCOL_TBL]] rejects off-limits
columns. The masked read-modify-write ([[EOR]]/[[AND]]/[[EOR]])
replaces exactly the bits in [[XMASK_TBL]] with the color mask that
[[COLOR_SET]] patched in.

[[LINE_TO]] is integer Bresenham with separate steep and shallow
loops; it leaves ([[ZP_PX]],[[ZP_PY]]) at the destination, so chained
calls trace a polyline. The shallow loop caches the row pointer and
calls the inner pair-plot directly, only recomputing the row on a
vertical step.

<<stuph plot and line>>=
        ORG $1867
PLOT    SUBROUTINE
        ; Plot one color pixel (a dot pair) at (ZP_PX, ZP_PY).
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_PX, ZP_PY -- pixel coordinates (row + 16 = scanline)
        ;   PLOT_CEVEN/PLOT_CODD -- color masks (via COLOR_SET)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Row tables give the draw-page address; XCOL_TBL/
        ;   XMASK_TBL give byte and bit; masked write per dot.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDY ZP_PY
        BMI .rts
        LDX ZP_PX
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO+$10,Y
        STA ZP_HGR_PTR
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI+$10,Y
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA ZP_HGR_PTR+1
PLOT_PAIR
        ; Plot the dots at columns X and X+1 on the cached row.
        JSR .dot
        INX
.dot    LDY XCOL_TBL,X                  ; screen byte + 1; 0 = clipped
        BEQ .rts
        TYA
        LSR                             ; C = odd screen byte
PLOT_CEVEN = *+1
        LDA #$80                        ; (patched: even color mask)
        BCC .mix
PLOT_CODD = *+1
        LDA #$80                        ; (patched: odd color mask)
.mix    EOR (ZP_HGR_PTR),Y
        AND XMASK_TBL,X
        EOR (ZP_HGR_PTR),Y
        STA (ZP_HGR_PTR),Y
.rts    RTS
LINE_TO
        ; Bresenham line from (ZP_PX,ZP_PY) to (X,Y), leaving
        ; ZP_PX/ZP_PY at the destination.
        STX ZP_LX2
        STY ZP_LY2
LINE_AGAIN
        ; Line to the previously stored (ZP_LX2,ZP_LY2).
        JSR PLOT
        LDA ZP_LX2
        CMP ZP_PX
        BNE .go
        LDA ZP_LY2
        CMP ZP_PY
        BEQ .rts                        ; zero-length line
.go     LDA #$01
        STA ZP_XSTEP
        STA ZP_YSTEP
        LDX #$FF
        SEC
        LDA ZP_LX2
        SBC ZP_PX
        BCS .dxok
        SEC
        LDA ZP_PX
        SBC ZP_LX2
        STX ZP_XSTEP                    ; ZP_XSTEP <- #$FF (leftward)
.dxok   STA ZP_DX
        SEC
        LDA ZP_LY2
        SBC ZP_PY
        BCS .dyok
        SEC
        LDA ZP_PY
        SBC ZP_LY2
        STX ZP_YSTEP                    ; ZP_YSTEP <- #$FF (upward)
.dyok   STA ZP_DY
        CMP ZP_DX
        BCC .shallow
        ; --- steep: one y step per iteration, x on overflow ---
        STA ZP_CNT
        LSR
        STA ZP_ERR
.sloop  CLC
        LDA ZP_ERR
        ADC ZP_DX
        STA ZP_ERR
        SEC
        SBC ZP_DY
        BCC .nox
        STA ZP_ERR
        CLC
        LDA ZP_PX
        ADC ZP_XSTEP
        STA ZP_PX
.nox    CLC
        LDA ZP_PY
        ADC ZP_YSTEP
        STA ZP_PY
        JSR PLOT
        DEC ZP_CNT
        BNE .sloop
        RTS
        ; --- shallow: one x step per iteration, y on overflow ---
.shallow
        LDA ZP_DX
        STA ZP_CNT
        LSR
        STA ZP_ERR
.hloop  CLC
        LDA ZP_PX
        ADC ZP_XSTEP
        STA ZP_PX
        TAX
        CLC
        LDA ZP_ERR
        ADC ZP_DY
        STA ZP_ERR
        BCC .nc
        SBC ZP_DX                       ; (overflowed past 256)
        JMP .ystep
.nc     SEC
        SBC ZP_DX
        BCC .plot                       ; no row change this step
.ystep  STA ZP_ERR
        CLC
        LDA ZP_PY
        ADC ZP_YSTEP
        STA ZP_PY
        TAY
        BMI .skip
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO+$10,Y            ; re-cache the row pointer
        STA ZP_HGR_PTR
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI+$10,Y
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA ZP_HGR_PTR+1
.plot   JSR PLOT_PAIR
.skip   DEC ZP_CNT
        BNE .hloop
        RTS
@ %def PLOT PLOT_PAIR PLOT_CEVEN PLOT_CODD LINE_TO LINE_AGAIN

\section{The text window: scroll, clear, presets}

Text lives in the monitor's window variables ([[MON_WNDLFT]] and
friends), and every text write goes to \emph{both} hi-res pages so
the windows persist across page flips. [[TEXT_SCROLL]] moves each
window row up eight scanlines and falls through into [[CLR_ROW]] to
blank the newly exposed bottom row. [[CLR_EOL]] ends by polling the
keyboard --- a free type-ahead sample on every printed line.

<<stuph text scroll and clear>>=
        ORG $193E
TEXT_SCROLL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Scroll the text window up one character row (both pages),
        ; leave the cursor on the bottom row, and clear it.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   For each scanline of rows WNDTOP..WNDBTM-2, copy the
        ;   scanline 8 below it (read from page 1, written to both
        ;   pages), then fall into CLR_ROW for the last row.
        ;
        ; Modifies: MON_CV
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX MON_WNDBTM
        DEX
        TXA
        STA MON_CV                      ; cursor to the bottom row
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        STA ZP_ROWLIM                   ; last scanline to fill
        LDA MON_WNDTOP
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        TAX
.row    LDA HGR_ROW_LO,X
        ADC MON_WNDLFT
        STA .d1l
        STA .d2l
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI,X
        STA .d1h
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA .d2h
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO+8,X              ; the row 8 scanlines below
        ADC MON_WNDLFT
        STA .sl
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI+8,X
        STA .sh
        LDY MON_WNDWDTH
        DEY
.sl = *+1
.sh = *+2
.cp     LDA $2100,Y                     ; (patched: src, page 1)
.d1l = *+1
.d1h = *+2
        STA HGR1,Y
.d2l = *+1
.d2h = *+2
        STA HGR2,Y
        DEY
        BPL .cp
        INX
        CPX ZP_ROWLIM
        BCC .row
        ; falls into CLR_ROW for the exposed bottom row
CLR_ROW SUBROUTINE
        ; Clear the cursor row (CLR_ROW), row A (CLR_ROW_A), or
        ; from the cursor column to the row end (CLR_EOL), writing
        ; background ($80 EOR ZP_INVERSE) to both pages.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Compute the row's 8 scanline addresses from the tables;
        ;   fill columns MON_CH..MON_WNDWDTH-1. CLR_EOL exits (and
        ;   the others end) via KEY_POLL.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X
        LDA MON_CV
CLR_ROW_A
        LDX #$00
        STX MON_CH
        BEQ .calc
CLR_EOL LDX MON_CH
        CPX MON_WNDWDTH
        BCS .out
        LDA MON_CV
.calc   ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        TAX
        LDA #$08
        STA ZP_ROWLIM                   ; 8 scanlines per text row
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO,X
        ADC MON_WNDLFT
        STA .c1l
        STA .c2l
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI,X
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
.hibump STA .c1h
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA .c2h
        LDA #$80
        EOR ZP_INVERSE                  ; background byte
        LDX MON_CH
.c1l = *+1
.c1h = *+2
.col    STA HGR1,X
.c2l = *+1
.c2h = *+2
        STA HGR2,X
        INX
        CPX MON_WNDWDTH
        BCC .col
        LDA .c1h
        ADC #$03                        ; +4 with the loop's carry:
        DEC ZP_ROWLIM                   ;   next scanline of the row
        BNE .hibump
.out    JMP KEY_POLL                    ; free type-ahead sample
@ %def TEXT_SCROLL CLR_ROW CLR_ROW_A CLR_EOL

The four window presets correspond to the game screen's fixed
layout: the bordered \textbf{viewport} (text rows 1--18, columns
1--38) where the map or dungeon view is drawn, the \textbf{message
area} (rows 20--23, columns 0--29), and the \textbf{stats panel}
(rows 20--23, columns 31--39). [[WIN_FULL]] opens the whole screen.

<<stuph window presets>>=
        ORG $19D4
WIN_TEXT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Window := the message area (cols 0-29, rows 20-23).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The four entry points load the monitor window variables
        ;   with one of the screen's fixed regions and home the
        ;   cursor to its top-left. Shared tails set the common
        ;   rows and clear MON_CH.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   MON_WNDLFT, MON_WNDWDTH, MON_WNDTOP, MON_WNDBTM,
        ;   MON_CH, MON_CV
        LDA #$1E
        STA MON_WNDWDTH
        LDA #$00
        BEQ .left
WIN_STATS
        ; Window := the stats panel (cols 31-39, rows 20-23).
        LDA #$09
        STA MON_WNDWDTH
        LDA #$1F
.left   STA MON_WNDLFT
        LDA #$18
        STA MON_WNDBTM
        LDA #$14
.top    STA MON_WNDTOP
        STA MON_CV
        LDA #$00
        STA MON_CH
        RTS
WIN_FULL
        ; Window := the full 40x24 screen.
        LDA #$28
        STA MON_WNDWDTH
        LDA #$18
        STA MON_WNDBTM
        LDA #$00
        STA MON_WNDLFT
        BEQ .top
WIN_VIEW
        ; Window := the viewport interior (cols 1-38, rows 1-18).
        LDA #$26
        STA MON_WNDWDTH
        LDA #$13
        STA MON_WNDBTM
        LDA #$01
        STA MON_WNDLFT
        BNE .top
@ %def WIN_TEXT WIN_STATS WIN_FULL WIN_VIEW

<<stuph window clear>>=
        ORG $1A0F
CLR_WINDOW
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Clear every row of the current text window (both pages).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   For each row WNDTOP..WNDBTM-1, call CLR_ROW_A. Leaves
        ;   MON_CV at the top row.
        LDY MON_WNDTOP
        STY MON_CV
.row    TYA
        JSR CLR_ROW_A
        INY
        CPY MON_WNDBTM
        BCC .row
        RTS
@ %def CLR_WINDOW

\section{The font blitter}

[[FONT_DRAW]] paints glyph A at the cursor --- the primitive under
every character the game ever prints. The glyph index is taken mod
128; indexes below [[$1A]] (the terrain strips) are bumped to the
odd-column variant when the screen address is odd. The eight
scanlines come from [[FONT_BANK]]'s eight 128-byte planes --- the
plane address alternates its low byte between [[$00]] and [[$80]]
and increments its high byte every second plane, while the screen
address steps by [[$0400]] per scanline. Both pages are written.
The cursor does \emph{not} advance --- the engine's [[PUTCH]] does
that.

<<stuph glyph draw>>=
        ORG $1A1D
FONT_DRAW
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw glyph A & $7F at the text cursor, on both pages.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A -- character; MON_CH/MON_CV/MON_WNDLFT -- position
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Reject columns outside the window. Odd screen columns
        ;   use glyph+1 for codes < $1A (pre-shifted pairs). Copy
        ;   8 planes EORed with ZP_INVERSE to both pages.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: (A, X preserved; Y clobbered)
        PHA
        STX FONT_XSAV
        LDX MON_CH
        CPX MON_WNDWDTH
        BCS .out
        AND #$7F
        TAY
        LDA MON_CV
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        TAX
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO,X
        ADC MON_WNDLFT
        ADC MON_CH
        STA .d1l
        STA .d2l
        LSR                             ; odd screen byte?
        BCC .even
        CPY #$1A
        BCS .even
        INY                             ; terrain strip: odd variant
.even   LDA HGR_ROW_HI,X
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA .d1h
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA .d2h
        CLC
        LDX #$08                        ; plane high byte $08..$0B
.plane  STX .srch
.srcl = *+1
.srch = *+2
.half   LDA FONT_BANK,Y                 ; (patched: the 8 planes)
        EOR ZP_INVERSE
.d1l = *+1
.d1h = *+2
        STA HGR1
.d2l = *+1
.d2h = *+2
        STA HGR2
        LDA .d1h
        ADC #$04                        ; next scanline, both pages
        STA .d1h
        EOR ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA .d2h
        LDA .srcl
        EOR #$80                        ; second half of the page pair
        STA .srcl
        BMI .half
        INX
        CPX #$0C
        BCC .plane
.out    LDX FONT_XSAV
        PLA
        RTS
FONT_XSAV
        DC.B $00                        ; caller's X
@ %def FONT_DRAW FONT_XSAV

\section{Tile animation}

[[TILE_ROLL]] rotates one glyph column of [[TILE_BANK]] vertically
by one scanline (with wrap), by walking the sixteen 96-byte planes
and exchanging bytes; [[TILE_ROLL2]] does a glyph pair. [[DRAW_MAP]]
calls it on glyphs 0--1 every other frame --- that is the flowing
water --- and swaps a few fixed plane bytes of the castle, tower and
ship glyphs for their flag-wave and sparkle.

<<stuph tile roll>>=
        ORG $1A85
TILE_ROLL2
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Rotate a glyph pair of TILE_BANK down one scanline.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   Y       -- left glyph index (TILE_ROLL: single glyph)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Walk the sixteen 96-byte planes exchanging bytes, with
        ;   the plane-15 byte wrapping to plane 0 -- a vertical
        ;   rotation. This is the flowing-water animation.
        JSR TILE_ROLL
        INY
TILE_ROLL
        ; Rotate glyph column Y of TILE_BANK by one scanline.
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_TILE_PTR
        LDA #$0C
        STA ZP_TILE_PTR+1
        LDX TILE_BANK+$5A0,Y            ; plane 15: the wrap byte
        CLC                             ; (the loop re-enters via BCC)
.swap   LDA (ZP_TILE_PTR),Y
        PHA
        TXA
        STA (ZP_TILE_PTR),Y
        PLA
        TAX
        LDA ZP_TILE_PTR
        ADC #$60                        ; next plane
        STA ZP_TILE_PTR
        BCC .swap
        INC ZP_TILE_PTR+1
        LDA ZP_TILE_PTR+1
        CMP #$12
        BCC .swap
        TXA
        STA TILE_BANK,Y
        RTS
@ %def TILE_ROLL2 TILE_ROLL

\section{Sound effects}

Nine effects, dispatched by even codes 0--[[$10]] through an
address-minus-one table and an RTS jump. [[SFX_PLAY]] ignores odd or
out-of-range codes and anything while [[SFX_ON]] is clear; on a IIgs
with sound enabled it wraps playback at 1\,MHz. Interrupts are masked
during an effect so the mouse VBL cannot warp the pitch.

Effects are usually not played directly: the engine \emph{queues}
them ([[SFX_QUEUE]] into [[ZP_SFX_Q]]) and [[PAGE_FLIP]] plays the
queue back at the frame boundary ([[SFX_DRAIN]]). Names follow
their observed use: code 0 is the per-turn move thump (every
outdoor turn queues it through [[TICK_SND]]), 2 plays twice at
death, [[$10]] is the ``Huh?'' error blat, 8 the command beep.

<<stuph sfx dispatch>>=
        ORG $1AB2
SFX_TBL ; RTS-dispatch addresses (minus one), codes 0,2,..,$10
        DC.W SFX_THUD-1
        DC.W SFX_RUMBLE-1
        DC.W SFX_NOISE-1
        DC.W SFX_BUZZ-1
        DC.W SFX_TONE-1
        DC.W SFX_SIREN-1
        DC.W SFX_FADE-1
        DC.W SFX_TICK-1
        DC.W SFX_BLAT-1
SFX_PLAY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Play sound effect A (even, 0..$10), if effects are on.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Validate the code; honor SFX_ON; on a IIgs with sound
        ;   on, drop to 1 MHz around playback; dispatch through
        ;   SFX_TBL with interrupts masked. X is preserved.
        STX ZP_XSAV
        TAX
        LSR
        BCS .out                        ; odd codes are not effects
        CPX #$12
        BCS .out
        LDA SFX_ON
        BEQ .out
        LDA SOUND_ON
        BEQ SFX_RAW
        BIT GS_SPEED
        BVS SFX_RAW                     ; not a IIgs
        LDA CYAREG
        AND #$1F
        PHA
        STA CYAREG                      ; 1 MHz for true pitch
        JSR SFX_RAW
        PLA
        ORA #$80
        STA CYAREG
        RTS
SFX_RAW PHP
        SEI                             ; no VBL ticks mid-effect
        JSR .disp
        PLP
        RTS
.disp   LDA SFX_TBL+1,X
        PHA
        LDA SFX_TBL,X
        PHA                             ; RTS-dispatch below
.out    LDX ZP_XSAV
        RTS
@ %def SFX_TBL SFX_PLAY SFX_RAW

<<stuph sfx queue>>=
        ORG $1B02
SFX_DRAIN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Play and remove the oldest queued effect, if any.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If ZP_SFX_CNT is zero, return. Otherwise shift the
        ;   queue down, SFX_PLAY the popped code, and decrement
        ;   the count.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   Z clear while effects remain queued (loop on BNE).
        LDA ZP_SFX_CNT
        BEQ .rts
        LDA ZP_SFX_Q                    ; oldest entry
        LDX #$01
.shift  LDY ZP_SFX_Q,X
        STY ZP_SFX_Q-1,X
        INX
        CPX #$04
        BCC .shift
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        DEC ZP_SFX_CNT
.rts    RTS
SFX_QUEUE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Append effect A to the queue for the next PAGE_FLIP.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A       -- effect code (even, 0..$10)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Store at the tail (collapsing onto a trailing zero
        ;   entry); if the 4-byte queue is full, SFX_DRAIN one
        ;   effect first to make room.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SFX_Q, ZP_SFX_CNT
        LDX ZP_SFX_CNT
        BEQ .store
        LDY ZP_SFX_Q-1,X                ; collapse a trailing zero
        BNE .full
        DEX
.full   CPX #$04
        BCC .store
        PHA
        JSR SFX_DRAIN
        PLA
        LDX ZP_SFX_CNT
.store  STA ZP_SFX_Q,X
        INC ZP_SFX_CNT
        RTS
@ %def SFX_DRAIN SFX_QUEUE

The effects themselves are conventional Apple II speaker loops ---
toggle [[SPKR]], burn cycles, vary the period. Each speaker touch is
paired with a [[DRIVE_OFF]] read to keep accelerator boards at
1\,MHz. The noise-based effects get their randomness from [[RND]].

<<stuph sfx effects>>=
        ORG $1B32
SFX_TICK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Code $0E: 16 evenly spaced clicks (a soft tick/whirr).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Each effect below toggles SPKR with cycle-burning loops
        ;   (paired with DRIVE_OFF reads for accelerators); they
        ;   differ only in period schedule and envelope. Reached by
        ;   SFX_PLAY's RTS dispatch; interrupts are masked.
        LDY #$10
        LDA #$30
.click  PHA
        JSR DELAY_SLOW
        BIT SPKR
        PLA
        DEY
        BNE .click
        RTS
SFX_BLAT
        ; Code $10: 50 fast clicks -- the "Huh?" error blat.
        LDY #$32
        LDA #$17
        BNE .click
SFX_SIREN
        ; Code $0A: two interleaved voices sweeping toward each
        ; other and back -- the siren/alarm.
        LDX #$40
        LDY #$40
        BNE .voices
SFX_BUZZ
        ; Code $06: the same engine with a long/short period pair:
        ; a low buzz.
        LDX #$E0
        LDY #$06
.voices STX ZP_CNT
        STX ZP_SFX_P1
        STY ZP_SFX_PER
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SFX_P2
        ; --- sweep P1 down / P2 up ---
.sweep1 LDA ZP_SFX_PER
        STA ZP_ROWLIM
.s1     LDX ZP_SFX_P1
.d1     DEX
        BNE .d1
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        LDX ZP_SFX_P2
.d2     DEX
        BNE .d2
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        DEC ZP_ROWLIM
        BNE .s1
        DEC ZP_SFX_P1
        INC ZP_SFX_P2
        LDA ZP_SFX_P2
        CMP #$1B
        BNE .sweep1
        ; --- and back ---
.sweep2 LDA ZP_SFX_PER
        STA ZP_ROWLIM
.s2     LDX ZP_SFX_P1
.d3     DEX
        BNE .d3
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        LDX ZP_SFX_P2
.d4     DEX
        BNE .d4
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        DEC ZP_ROWLIM
        BNE .s2
        INC ZP_SFX_P1
        DEC ZP_SFX_P2
        BNE .sweep2
        RTS
SFX_FADE
        ; Code $0C: a long single tone that fades out as its
        ; period counter runs down.
        LDA #$FB
        STA ZP_CNT
.cycle  INX
        BNE .cycle
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        DEC ZP_CNT
        LDX ZP_CNT
        BNE .cycle
        RTS
SFX_TONE
        ; Code $08: a steady mid tone -- the command beep.
        LDY #$A0
.period TYA
        TAX
.dly    DEX
        BNE .dly
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        DEY
        BNE .period
        RTS
SFX_NOISE
        ; Code $04: white noise with a rising envelope (period
        ; sweeps $E0 down to $40) -- an explosion.
        LDA #$40
        STA ZP_CNT
        LDA #$E0
        STA ZP_SFX_PER
.hiss   JSR RND
        ORA ZP_SFX_PER
        TAX
.dlyn   DEX
        BNE .dlyn
        BIT SPKR
        BIT DRIVE_OFF
        DEC ZP_SFX_PER
        LDA ZP_SFX_PER
        CMP ZP_CNT
        BCS .hiss
        RTS
SFX_RUMBLE
        ; Code $02: long random rumble (death knell, played twice).
        LDA #$E8
        LDX #$FF
        BNE .noise
SFX_THUD
        ; Code $00: short noise burst -- the damage thud.
        LDA #$00
        LDX #$08
.noise  STX ZP_CNT
        STA .acc                        ; $E8 keeps the accelerator
        LDA #$00                        ;   nudge; $00 disables it
        STA ZP_SFX_PER
.hiss2  JSR RND
        ORA ZP_SFX_PER
        TAX
.dly2   DEX
        BNE .dly2
        BIT SPKR
.acc = *+1
        BIT DRIVE_OFF                   ; (operand low byte patched)
        DEC ZP_CNT
        BNE .hiss2
        RTS
@ %def SFX_TICK SFX_BLAT SFX_SIREN SFX_BUZZ SFX_FADE SFX_TONE
@ %def SFX_NOISE SFX_RUMBLE SFX_THUD

\section{Frame synchronization}

[[FRAME_SYNC]] paces the game to the display. With a mouse card it
waits for the next two VBL interrupt ticks (a full frame); on an
enhanced IIe/IIc/IIgs without one it polls [[RDVBL]] for an edge; on
an older machine it returns immediately and the game free-runs at
whatever the busy-wait delays allow. Either way it samples the
keyboard first, so type-ahead never drops keys.

<<stuph frame sync>>=
        ORG $1C15
FRAME_SYNC
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Wait for the vertical blank, by the best available means.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Sample the keyboard; then with a mouse card wait for
        ;   two VBL_TICK changes (a full frame); else on an
        ;   enhanced machine wait for an RDVBL edge; else return
        ;   immediately (free-run).
        JSR KEY_POLL
        LDA MOUSE_N0
        BEQ .novbl
        LDY VBL_TICK                    ; mouse card: wait 2 ticks
.tick   JSR KEY_POLL
        CPY VBL_TICK
        BEQ .tick
        RTS
.novbl  LDA HAS_VBL
        BEQ .rts                        ; old machine: free-run
.hi     LDA RDVBL                       ; wait for a VBL edge
        BPL .hi
.lo     LDA RDVBL
        BMI .lo
.rts    RTS
@ %def FRAME_SYNC

\section{The map renderer}

[[DRAW_MAP]] paints the whole 19$\times$9-tile viewport from the
64$\times$64 map at [[MAP_BASE]] --- the game's single most
important graphics routine, called every frame of every outdoor,
town and castle turn (the main loop's [[KEY_GET_ANIM]] calls it
while waiting for input, which is what keeps the world animated).

The view is centered on the player at ([[ZP_PLR_X]],[[ZP_PLR_Y]]):
tile columns [[ZP_PLR_X]]$-9$ through $+9$, rows [[ZP_PLR_Y]]$-4$
through $+4$. For each map row it builds a 38-glyph code string in
[[MAPROW_BUF]]: each cell byte is masked with [[$7E]] and becomes
the glyph pair $(c, c{+}1)$. Cells outside the 0--63 map range
become water --- the seas at the edge of the world are an
\emph{artifact of the clipping}, not map data. Codes
[[$20]]--[[$58]] are creatures, and get $+2$ added pseudo-randomly
--- creature tiles come in two-frame pairs, and the renderer picks a
frame per cell per band by reading bit 1 of an arbitrary byte of the
file library's code at [[MLIB_CODE]] (a free, if cheeky, noise
source). The player's own cells (buffer columns 18--19) are
overwritten with [[PLAYER_TILE]], which the engine sets to the
on-foot/horse/cart/raft/frigate tile as transport changes.

Then sixteen scanlines are blitted per band: for each, one byte per
buffer column, read from [[TILE_BANK]] plane by plane and stored
through a patched address into screen bytes 1--38 of the draw page.
After the last band comes [[PAGE_FLIP]], then the tile-bank
animations (water roll, flag waves, ship sparkle), and a final fall
through into [[KEY_POLL]]. Mid-draw, the keyboard is sampled once
per band so fast typists never outrun the renderer.

<<stuph map renderer>>=
        ORG $1C39
DRAW_MAP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Render the tile viewport centered on the player, flip
        ; pages, animate the tile bank, and poll the keyboard.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_PLR_X/ZP_PLR_Y -- player map position
        ;   MAP_BASE -- 64x64 cell map, one byte per cell
        ;   PLAYER_TILE -- glyph code for the player's tile
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   9 bands of 16 scanlines; per band, decode 19 cells
        ;   into 38 glyph codes in MAPROW_BUF (clipping to water,
        ;   randomizing creature frames), insert the player tile
        ;   on the player's row, then blit 16 glyph scanlines.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$08
        STA ZP_SCANROW                  ; first scanline row
        SEC
        LDA ZP_PLR_X
        SBC #$09
        STA ZP_MAP_X0                   ; leftmost visible column
        SEC
        LDA ZP_PLR_Y
        SBC #$04
        STA ZP_MAP_Y0                   ; topmost visible row
.band   LDA #$10
        STA ZP_ROWLIM                   ; 16 scanlines per band
        LDA #$00
        STA .tsl
        LDA #$0C
        STA .tsh                        ; tile source := TILE_BANK
        LDA KBD                         ; sample the keyboard
        BPL .nokey
        JSR KEY_STASH
.nokey  LDA ZP_MAP_Y0
        CMP #$40
        BCS .fill                       ; off the map: a water band
        LSR                             ; map row pointer =
        STA ZP_MAP_PTR+1                ;   MAP_BASE + row*64
        LDA #$00
        ROR
        LSR ZP_MAP_PTR+1
        ROR
        STA ZP_MAP_PTR
        LDA ZP_MAP_PTR+1
        ADC #$60
        STA ZP_MAP_PTR+1
        LDX #$00
        LDY ZP_MAP_X0
.cell   CPY #$40
        BCC .incell
        LDA #$00                        ; off the edge: water
        BEQ .pair
.fill   LDX #$25                        ; fill the whole band
.fl     LDA #$01
        STA MAPROW_BUF,X
        DEX
        LDA #$00
        STA MAPROW_BUF,X
        DEX
        BPL .fl
        BMI .player
.incell LDA (ZP_MAP_PTR),Y
        AND #$7E
        CMP #$20
        BCC .pair                       ; terrain: as stored
        CMP #$59
        BCS .pair
        STX ZP_CELLX                    ; creature: pick a frame
        STA ZP_CELLA
        INC DITHER_IX
        LDX DITHER_IX
        LDA MLIB_CODE,X                 ; cheap noise: library code
        AND #$02
        ADC ZP_CELLA                    ; +0 or +2: frame A or B
        LDX ZP_CELLX
.pair   STA MAPROW_BUF,X                ; left glyph
        INX
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        STA MAPROW_BUF,X                ; right glyph
        INX
        INY
        CPX #$26
        BCC .cell
.player LDA ZP_MAP_Y0
        INC ZP_MAP_Y0
        CMP ZP_PLR_Y                    ; the player's row?
        BNE .scan
        LDY PLAYER_TILE
        STY MAPROW_BUF+$12              ; center cell of the view
        INY
        STY MAPROW_BUF+$13
.scan   LDY ZP_SCANROW
        INC ZP_SCANROW
        CLC
        LDA HGR_ROW_LO,Y
        ADC #$01                        ; viewport starts at byte 1
        STA .dl
        LDA HGR_ROW_HI,Y
        EOR ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA .dh
        LDX #$25
.cp     LDY MAPROW_BUF,X
.tsl = *+1
.tsh = *+2
        LDA TILE_BANK,Y                 ; (patched: plane by plane)
.dl = *+1
.dh = *+2
        STA HGR1,X                      ; (patched: each scanline)
        DEX
        BPL .cp
        CLC
        LDA .tsl
        ADC #$60                        ; next tile plane
        STA .tsl
        BCC .noc
        INC .tsh
.noc    DEC ZP_ROWLIM
        BNE .scan
        LDA ZP_SCANROW
        CMP #$98                        ; 9 bands done?
        BCS .anim
        JMP .band
        ; --- end of frame: flip, then animate the tile bank ---
.anim   JSR PAGE_FLIP
        DEC ANIM_CNT1
        BNE .wave
        LDA #$02
        STA ANIM_CNT1
        LDY #$00
        JSR TILE_ROLL2                  ; the water flows
.wave   DEC ANIM_CNT2
        BNE .wave2
        LDA #$03
        STA ANIM_CNT2
        LDX TILE_BANK+$69               ; castle flag: swap two
        LDY TILE_BANK+$C9               ;   scanlines of glyph 9
        STY TILE_BANK+$69
        STX TILE_BANK+$C9
.wave2  DEC ANIM_CNT3
        BNE .spark
        LDA #$02
        STA ANIM_CNT3
        LDX TILE_BANK+$12C              ; tower flag: glyph $0C
        LDY TILE_BANK+$18C
        STY TILE_BANK+$12C
        STX TILE_BANK+$18C
.spark  LDX TILE_BANK+$D9               ; ship sparkle: glyphs
        LDY TILE_BANK+$139              ;   $18/$19, every frame
        STY TILE_BANK+$D9
        STX TILE_BANK+$139
        LDX TILE_BANK+$D8
        LDY TILE_BANK+$138
        STY TILE_BANK+$D8
        STX TILE_BANK+$138
        ; falls into KEY_POLL
@ %def DRAW_MAP

\section{The keyboard}

A four-key type-ahead queue in zero page. [[KEY_POLL]] samples the
hardware register --- it is called from every clear, every frame
sync, and twice per map band, so the queue fills no matter what the
game is busy doing. Pressing \emph{space} flushes the queue first:
space is the ``stop everything'' key. [[KEY_GET]] pops a key,
erasing the flashing cursor behind it, translating Delete to
backspace and folding lowercase to uppercase; [[KEY_GET_ANIM]] is
the main loop's variant that keeps the world animated while it
waits. The cursor itself is [[CURSOR_FLASH]]: glyphs [[$7F]] down to
[[$7C]] drawn in rotation, falling through into [[RND]] --- so every
caller gets a fresh random number as a side effect, and the RNG
state advances with every flash of the cursor.

<<stuph keyboard>>=
        ORG $1D64
KEY_POLL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Sample the keyboard into the type-ahead queue.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If a key is down: space flushes the queue first; then
        ;   the key (high bit set) is appended if room, and the
        ;   strobe is cleared.
        LDA KBD
        BPL .rts
KEY_STASH
        ; (entry with the key already in A, from DRAW_MAP)
        CMP #$A0                        ; space: flush type-ahead
        BNE .store
        LDX #$00
        STX ZP_KEY_CNT
.store  LDX ZP_KEY_CNT
        CPX #$04
        BCS .rts                        ; queue full: drop the key
        STA ZP_KEY_BUF,X
        INC ZP_KEY_CNT
        BIT KBDSTRB
.rts    RTS
KEY_DELAY
        ; A short delay (7 x $4F units), cut short by a waiting
        ; key -- the pacing primitive for message display.
        LDY #$07
.poll   JSR KEY_POLL
        LDA ZP_KEY_CNT
        BNE .rts
        LDA #$4F
        JSR DELAY_256
        DEY
        BNE .poll
        RTS
KEY_WAIT
        ; Block until a key arrives; A := the key (see KEY_GET).
        JSR KEY_GET
        BEQ KEY_WAIT
        RTS
KEY_GET
        ; Poll once (with cursor flash and delay); A := key or 0.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A = ASCII key (Delete -> $08+$80, lowercase folded to
        ;   upper, high bit stripped), or 0 if none. X/Y preserved.
        JSR KEY_CTX
        JSR KEY_DELAY
        LDA ZP_KEY_CNT
        BNE .pop
        BEQ .none
KEY_GET_ANIM
        ; As KEY_GET, but the wait redraws the animated map view.
        JSR KEY_CTX
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        LDA ZP_KEY_CNT
        BEQ .none
.pop    LDA #$20
        JSR FONT_DRAW                   ; erase the cursor glyph
        LDA ZP_KEY_BUF                  ; the oldest key
        DEC ZP_KEY_CNT
        LDX #$01
        CMP #$FF
        BNE .nodel
        LDA #$88                        ; Delete -> backspace
.nodel  CMP #$E0
        BCC .shift
        EOR #$20                        ; fold lowercase to upper
.shift  LDY ZP_KEY_BUF,X
        STY ZP_KEY_BUF-1,X
        INX
        CPX #$04
        BCC .shift
.none   LDX KEY_XSAV
        LDY KEY_YSAV
        AND #$7F
        RTS
KEY_CTX ; Save X/Y, nudge accelerators, and fall into the cursor.
        STX KEY_XSAV
        STY KEY_YSAV
        JSR ACCEL_NUDGE
CURSOR_FLASH
        ; Draw the next cursor frame (glyphs $7F down to $7C, in
        ; rotation) at the text cursor, then fall into RND -- the
        ; cursor's flicker doubles as entropy for the RNG.
        LDX .frame
        DEX
        CPX #$7C
        BCS .keep
        LDX #$7F
.keep   STX .frame
.frame = *+1
        LDA #$7C                        ; (operand: the frame glyph)
        JSR FONT_DRAW
        ; falls into RND
@ %def KEY_POLL KEY_STASH KEY_DELAY KEY_WAIT KEY_GET KEY_GET_ANIM
@ %def KEY_CTX CURSOR_FLASH

\section{The random number generator}

A 16-byte lagged additive generator. Each call sweeps the last
state byte through the first fifteen as a running sum (a chain of
additions whose carries interact chaotically), adds it into byte 0
again, then increments the state as a little-endian 16-byte counter
to guarantee the sequence never locks up at zero. Byte 0 is the
result. Combined with the cursor-flash coupling above, the stream
is effectively seeded by player timing.

<<stuph rng>>=
        ORG $1DF1
RND     SUBROUTINE
        ; A := next pseudo-random byte. Preserves X, Y.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Sweep the last state byte through the first fifteen as
        ;   a carry-chained running sum, fold it into byte 0, then
        ;   increment the state as a 16-byte counter so the
        ;   sequence has no fixed point. Returns byte 0.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   RND_STATE
        CLC
        LDA RND_STATE+$0F
        LDX #$0E
.mix    ADC RND_STATE,X                 ; running chaotic sum
        STA RND_STATE,X
        DEX
        BPL .mix
        LDA RND_STATE+$0F
        CLC
        ADC RND_STATE
        STA RND_STATE
        LDX #$0F
.count  INC RND_STATE,X                 ; 16-byte counter: never
        BNE .done                       ;   a fixed point
        DEX
        BPL .count
.done   LDA RND_STATE
        RTS
RND_STATE
        HEX 64 76 85 54 f6 5c 76 1f     ; state as shipped on disk
        HEX e7 12 a7 6b 93 c4 6e 1b
RND_SPARE
        ; 18 further seed bytes, never referenced by code.
        HEX e7 12 a7 6b 93 c4 6e 1b
        HEX 76 1f e7 12 a7 6b 93 c4
        HEX 6e 1b
STUPH_FILL
        DS.B 454,$00                    ; zero fill to $1FFF
@ %def RND RND_STATE RND_SPARE STUPH_FILL

