\chapter{The resident engine: MI.U1}
\label{ch:engine}

\texttt{MI.U1} (``machine interface'') is the game's memory-resident
core, occupying [[$7000]]--[[$89BC]] --- everything below the overlay
region at [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]]. It supplies the services every mode
overlay shares: the status panel, text output, the player-disk save
files (\texttt{/U1.PLAYER}, \texttt{/U1.VARS} --- their pathnames are
in the string region), name tables for items, monsters, and places,
and assorted drawing helpers. Its first instruction simply jumps to
the overlay entry point: running \texttt{MI.U1} \emph{is} running
whichever overlay is currently loaded at [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]].

The whole file is now decomposed: the death-skull image at
[[DEATH_IMG]], the string region's name tables ([[STR_RACES]]
through [[STR_PLACES]]), the player state block ([[LOC_NAME]]
onward), and the engine code ([[$8037]]--[[$89BC]]).

<<miu1 defines>>=
RESET_VEC       EQU $03F2       ; ProDOS soft-reset vector (+2: check)
MON_HOME        EQU $FC58       ; monitor: clear the text screen
MON_RESET       EQU $FF59       ; monitor cold entry (placeholder)
@

<<miu1 entry>>=
        ORG $7000
MIU1_ENTRY
        ; the resident engine starts whatever overlay is loaded
        JMP OVERLAY_ENTRY
@ %def MIU1_ENTRY

\section{The death image}

The 940 bytes between the entry jump and the string region are not
``mask tables'' at all --- they are exactly one picture: the 10-byte
by 94-scanline skull that [[DEATH]] blits over the viewport when
the player dies (bytes with the high bit set overwrite the screen;
the rest are ORed in, which feathers the skull's edges into the
scene behind it).

