\section{The string region}

All of the game's nouns live in one 2.6\,KB region of packed string
tables: each entry's final character has its high bit set, and the
readers ([[STR_NTH]] and friends) count entries from a table's
start, so the tables need no pointers or lengths. The contents are
a complete census of the game world --- and they pin down meanings
that the code alone left open: the four \emph{continent} names, the
46 monsters, and all 84 named places (castles, towns, dungeons,
pillars and signposts; index order will matter to the overlays'
location tables).

A few non-string stretches are embedded among the tables, and the
OUT overlay (chapter~\ref{ch:overlays}) identified both:
[[MON_TIER]] is the per-monster difficulty tier (one byte per
monster, parallel to [[STR_MONSTERS]]; the tier indexes the
overlays' hit-point/experience scale tables), and the 168 bytes
between the continent and place names are two parallel 84-entry
coordinate tables, [[PLACE_Y]] and [[PLACE_X]] --- the world
position of every named place, in the same index order as
[[STR_PLACES]].

