\section{Text output}

The engine's text system, the most-called code in the game (the
overlays invoke [[MSG_PRINT]] alone some 349 times). Text renders on
the hi-res screen through the resident library's font blitter
([[FONT_DRAW]], documented in the \texttt{STUPH} chapter), with the
monitor's window and cursor zero-page variables
([[MON_WNDLFT]]\dots[[MON_CV]]) defining the text region. The
[[$15xx]] addresses below are \texttt{STUPH}'s public jump vectors;
the engine assembles against them as EQUs.

Three printing interfaces, all using the same inline-argument
convention as the file library:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[MSG_PRINT]] --- zero-terminated text follows the [[JSR]];
  [[MSG_AT]] first sets the cursor from X/Y.
\item [[STR_NTH]] --- an inline \emph{pointer} to a string table
  follows the [[JSR]]; X picks the string. Table strings are packed
  with no separators: the last character of each has its high bit
  set. [[STR_FIRST]] prints entry 0; [[STR_NTH_CAP]] capitalizes the
  first letter (for sentence-initial item names --- the flag byte
  [[CAP_FLAG]] doubles as ``seen the first letter'' state).
\item [[PRINT_HEX]] --- A as two hex digits.
\end{itemize}

Characters pass through [[PUTCH]], which treats the four codes from
[[$7C]] up specially: [[$7C]] (\texttt{|}) is a newline, [[$7E]]
(\texttt{\~{}}) newline-then-column-1, [[$7D]] (\texttt{\}})
newline-only-if-needed-then-column-1, and [[$7F]] (in the string
readers) adds the following byte to the column --- a tab. This is why
the game's strings are full of \texttt{|}, \texttt{\}}, and
\texttt{\~{}} characters. The newline path scrolls the text window
via [[TEXT_SCROLL]] when the cursor passes [[MON_WNDBTM]].

<<miu1 text defines>>=
; --- Monitor text window and cursor (shared with STUPH) ---
MON_WNDLFT      EQU $20         ; text window: left column
MON_WNDWDTH     EQU $21         ; text window: width
MON_WNDTOP      EQU $22         ; text window: top row
MON_WNDBTM      EQU $23         ; text window: bottom row + 1
MON_CH          EQU $24         ; cursor column
MON_CV          EQU $25         ; cursor row
; --- The resident library's jump vectors (see the STUPH chapter) ---
LIB_INIT        EQU $1583       ; detect mouse/IIgs, hi-res on
LIB_SHUTDOWN    EQU $1586       ; text mode, unhook, restore speed
FILE_LOAD       EQU $1589       ; load MLIB_PATH file (RAM cache)
FILE_LOAD_AT    EQU $158C       ; same, at address Y/A
PAGE_COPY       EQU $158F       ; copy shown page onto draw page
TEXT_SCROLL     EQU $1592       ; scroll the text window up a row
CLR_ROW         EQU $1595       ; clear the cursor row
CLR_EOL         EQU $1598       ; clear cursor to end of row
CLR_WINDOW      EQU $159B       ; clear the whole text window
WIN_FULL        EQU $159E       ; window := full screen
WIN_STATS       EQU $15A1       ; window := stats panel
WIN_TEXT        EQU $15A4       ; window := message area
WIN_VIEW        EQU $15A7       ; window := viewport interior
VIEW_CLEAR      EQU $15AA       ; black out the viewport
PAGE_FLIP       EQU $15AD       ; show drawn page, toggle, drain sfx
FONT_DRAW       EQU $15B0       ; draw glyph A at the cursor
DRAW_MAP        EQU $15B3       ; render the tile viewport
KEY_DELAY       EQU $15B6       ; short delay, cut by a keypress
RND             EQU $15B9       ; A := pseudo-random byte
KEY_POLL        EQU $15BC       ; sample keyboard into type-ahead
KEY_WAIT        EQU $15BF       ; block for a key
KEY_GET         EQU $15C2       ; poll once; A := key or 0
KEY_GET_ANIM    EQU $15C5       ; poll with animated map redraw
CURSOR_FLASH    EQU $15C8       ; flash the cursor; A := random
SFX_PLAY        EQU $15CB       ; play effect A now
SFX_QUEUE       EQU $15CE       ; queue effect for next PAGE_FLIP
SFX_DRAIN       EQU $15D1       ; play one queued effect
