\chapter{Mode overlays}
\label{ch:overlays}

The seven play-mode overlays all load at [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]] and are
entered at their first byte. They share the engine API, the player
state block, and (visibly, from common code shapes and even
unreferenced leftover routines) a common ancestral source file.
\texttt{OUT} is fully decomposed below and serves as the reference
for the conventions; \texttt{DNG} follows it (all but its
wireframe renderer, which has its own round); the remaining five
are stub regions pending their own rounds.

\section{OUT: the outdoors overlay}

\texttt{OUT} is the overworld: the player walks one of four $64
\times 64$ continents, monsters spawn and hunt, and every other game
mode is entered from here --- towns, castles, dungeons and landmarks
through the \emph{Enter} command, space by boarding the shuttle, the
endgame by boarding a time machine. It is the smallest overlay
(5230 bytes at [[$8956]]--[[$9DC3]]) and the template for reading
the other six: a screenful of command handlers in front, the world
machinery behind them, and packed message text at the end.

The overlay's working vocabulary, recovered in this chapter:

\begin{itemize}
\item A map \emph{cell} is one byte at [[MAP_BASE]] +
row$\times$64 + column. The byte is twice the \emph{cell code}; [[DRAW_MAP]] masks
it with \texttt{\$7E} to pick a glyph pair, and the low bit is free
for tile animation. Codes 0--7 are terrain: 0 water, 1 grass, 2
forest, 3 mountains, 4 castle, 5 landmark, 6 town, 7 dungeon
entrance. Codes 8--15 are parked transports (8 $+$ transport
index, 15 = a time machine). Codes 16--44 (cell bytes
[[$20]]--[[$58]]) are monsters: monster index = cell byte / 4 $-$ 2,
giving the outdoor range 6--20 of [[STR_MONSTERS]].
\item Everything that sits \emph{on top of} terrain --- monsters
and parked transports --- is an \emph{object record}: five parallel
80-entry arrays ([[OBJ_X]], [[OBJ_YC]], [[OBJ_TILE]],
[[OBJ_UNDER]] in the saved player block; hit points in
[[OBJ_HP]], up in unsaved RAM). [[OBJ_YC]] carries the continent in its top two
bits, so records from all four continents coexist; a map rebuild
only paints the records whose tag matches [[PLR_CONT_BITS]].
\item The world map itself is read-only: the four continents live
RLE-compressed above the overlay at [[MAP_PACKED]] and are
decompressed into [[$6000]] on every continent change. Nothing the
player does alters the stored map --- all world state is the
object-record arrays, which travel inside the saved player block.
\end{itemize}

The overlay calls the resident library through the [[$15xx]]
vectors and the engine API directly; everything external is
declared here. The five working bytes past the end of the file
([[$9DC4]]--[[$9DC8]]) are the overlay's only BSS.

<<out defines>>=
