\section{OUT: arrival and the main loop}

The engine's [[GAME_LOAD]] BLOADs the overlay and jumps to its
first byte. Entry restores the player's outdoor position, turns
double-buffering back on (popups and other overlays leave the game
locked to page 1), and \emph{stashes the packed world map}: when
the loader brought the game up, \texttt{/U1.VARS} put the four
RLE-compressed continents at [[MAP_BASE]], and OUT immediately
copies those 14 pages up to [[MAP_PACKED]] so the same region can
hold the decompressed current continent. (Leaving outdoors copies
them back --- see [[EXIT_TO]] --- so the next entry finds them at
[[MAP_BASE]] again.)

[[OBJ_HP]]+0 is the world-state sentinel: zero means no object
records exist yet (a fresh boot or a new game), in which case
[[MON_CLEAR]] primes it. Then the map is decompressed and, if the
player arrived dead (hit points zero --- the engine's [[DEATH]]
respawns by reloading OUT), control falls straight into
resurrection.

<<out entry>>=
        ORG $8956
OUT_ENTRY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Restore position, stash the packed map, build the
        ; continent, and decide: main loop or resurrection.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Restore ZP_PLR_X/Y from the save, enable page flips,
        ;   copy the 14 packed-map pages to MAP_PACKED, prime the
        ;   world on first entry, decompress the continent, then
        ;   fall into OUT_MAIN -- or RESURRECT if hits are zero.
        LDA PLR_OUT_X
        STA ZP_PLR_X
        LDA PLR_OUT_Y
        STA ZP_PLR_Y
        LDA #$60                        ; double-buffering on:
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL                 ;   draw on page 2 first
        STA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        JSR PAGE_COPY
        LDX #$0E                        ; 14 pages
        LDY #$00
.stash
STASH_SRC = *+2
        LDA MAP_BASE,Y
STASH_DST = *+2
        STA MAP_PACKED,Y
        INY
        BNE .stash
        INC STASH_SRC                   ; next page (self-modified)
        INC STASH_DST
        DEX
        BNE .stash
        STX DIR_STR_PTR+1               ; default direction names
        LDA OBJ_HP                      ; world not initialized?
        BNE .world
        JSR MON_CLEAR                   ;   prime the sentinel
.world  JSR MAP_REFRESH
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; dead on arrival? (DEATH
        ORA PLR_HITS+1                  ;   reloads OUT to respawn)
        BEQ RESURRECT
@ %def OUT_ENTRY STASH_SRC STASH_DST

The main loop is four steps: print the prompt, wait for a key
(idle turns happen by themselves), dispatch the command, then let
the world act. Dispatch is a self-modified [[JSR]]:
[[GET_COMMAND]] returns X = twice the command index, the handler's
address is copied from [[CMD_TBL]] into [[DISPATCH_VEC]], and the
patched [[JSR]] calls it. (On disk the operand rests at
[[RTS_HOOK]], an engine [[RTS]].) The stack pointer is reset every
lap, so handlers are free to bail out with [[JMP OUT_MAIN]] from
any depth.

An idle turn --- 128 polls of [[KEY_GET_ANIM]] with no key ---
costs $0.05$ food and $0.50$ time and still gives the monsters
their turn, so standing still is never safe. Death is checked at
the top of every turn for both hit points and food; either reaching
zero ends the game ([[DEATH]] paints the skull, then reloads OUT,
which lands in [[RESURRECT]]).

<<out main loop>>=
        ORG $8995
OUT_MAIN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The turn loop. No return; every path comes back here.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Reset the stack, prompt, poll. No key: charge an idle
        ;   tick and run the world. A key: GET_COMMAND, patch
        ;   DISPATCH_VEC from CMD_TBL, call the handler, run the
        ;   world, repeat. Zero hits or food fall into DEATH.
        LDX #$FF                        ; reset the stack: command
        TXS                             ;   handlers JMP back here
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "|",$0E,$00                ; the prompt glyph
        JSR PLAYER_TILE_SET
.turn   JSR STATS_VALUES
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; dead?
        ORA PLR_HITS+1
        BEQ .dead
        LDA PLR_FOOD                    ; starved?
        ORA PLR_FOOD+1
        BEQ .dead
        JSR KEY_OR_IDLE
        BNE .cmd
        LDY #$05                        ; idle: food -= 0.05,
        LDA #$50                        ;   time += 0.50
        JSR TICK_SND
        JSR TURN_PASS
        LDA MON_CH                      ; quiet turn: skip the
        CMP #$02                        ;   prompt reprint
        BCC .turn
        BCS OUT_MAIN
.cmd    JSR GET_COMMAND
        BCS .world                      ; "Huh?" still costs a turn
        LDA CMD_TBL,X                   ; patch the JSR below with
        STA DISPATCH_VEC                ;   the handler's address
        LDA CMD_TBL+1,X
        STA DISPATCH_VEC+1
DISPATCH_VEC = *+1
        JSR RTS_HOOK                    ; (self-modified)
.world  JSR TURN_PASS
        JMP OUT_MAIN
.dead   JSR DEATH
@ %def OUT_MAIN DISPATCH_VEC

\section{OUT: death and resurrection}

[[DEATH]] never returns --- it reloads OUT --- so the fall-through
from [[.dead]] above is really the entry path arriving with zero
hit points. The price of dying outdoors: the transport being
ridden is gone, every weapon but bare hands is gone, and the
readied weapon, armour and spell are cleared. The player is set
down on a random patch of open land on the current continent with
hit points and food wound up to 99 each, one heartbeat at a time,
on screen --- the famous slow ``Attempting resurrection!''

<<out resurrection>>=
        ORG $89E8
RESURRECT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Respawn after death: pay the penalty, find land, and
        ; crank vitals back to 99.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Strip the ride and weapons 1-15, clear the readied
        ;   slots, despawn monsters, place the player on random
        ;   land, then visibly count hits and food up to 99 and
        ;   rejoin the main loop.
        LDX #$0A                        ; let the death knell ring
.wait   JSR VDELAY
        DEX
        BPL .wait
        JSR FIND_LAND
        STX ZP_PLR_X                    ; respawn position
        STY ZP_PLR_Y
        JSR MON_CLEAR
        LDA #$00
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT             ; the ride is lost
        BEQ .nomount
        STA READY_TRANSPORT
        LDY OWNED_TRANSPORT,X
        BEQ .nomount
        DEC OWNED_TRANSPORT,X
.nomount
        LDX #$0F                        ; weapons 1-15 are lost
.strip  STA OWNED_WEAPONS,X             ;   (bare hands remain)
        DEX
        BNE .strip
        STA READY_ARMOUR
        STA READY_WEAPON
        STA READY_SPELL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Attempting resurrection!",$00
.hits   INC PLR_HITS                    ; wind hits up to 99,
        JSR .beat                       ;   visibly
        LDA PLR_HITS
        CMP #$63
        BCC .hits
.food   INC PLR_FOOD                    ; then food
        JSR .beat
        LDA PLR_FOOD
        CMP #$63
        BCC .food
        JSR KBD_CLEAR
        LDA #$0A                        ; the triumphant ding
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        JMP OUT_MAIN
.beat   JSR STATS_VALUES                ; one tick of the crank
        LDA #$68
        JSR VDELAY
        JMP FRAME_SYNC
@ %def RESURRECT

\section{OUT: reading the player}

[[KEY_OR_IDLE]] is the turn timer: up to 128 animated polls
(cursor flash, tile wobble) waiting for a keypress. Zero in A and
X means the player let the turn pass.

<<out key or idle>>=
        ORG $8A6A
KEY_OR_IDLE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Poll for a key through one idle period.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   KEY_GET_ANIM up to 128 times (cursor flash and tile
        ;   wobble run in the poll); stop at the first key.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A, X -- the key, or 0 if the turn timed out
        LDX #$80
.poll   JSR KEY_GET_ANIM
        BNE .got
        DEX
        BNE .poll
.got    TAX                             ; Z reflects the key
        RTS
@ %def KEY_OR_IDLE

\emph{Pass} (the space bar) is an idle turn by request, at the
same price; the dispatcher returns to [[OUT_MAIN]], which runs the
world. (This handler is reached only through [[CMD_TBL]].)

<<out cmd pass>>=
        ORG $8A76
CMD_PASS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Pass: food -= 0.05, time += 0.50, monsters move.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Tail-call TICK with the idle fare; the dispatcher's
        ;   return path runs the monsters.
        LDY #$05
        LDA #$50
        JMP TICK
@ %def CMD_PASS

A small orphan follows: a pointer builder for the target cell,
referenced by nothing in this overlay. (The seven overlays were
clearly built from one shared source; expect a sibling to use it
--- noted to verify in the later overlay rounds.)

<<out target row pointer>>=
        ORG $8A7D
TGT_CELL_PTR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; ZP_CELL_PTR := row ZP_TGT_Y of the map; Y := ZP_TGT_X.
        ; Not referenced by OUT itself.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Shift ZP_TGT_Y into a row offset (row * 64), add the
        ;   MAP_BASE page, load Y with the column.
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR
        LDA ZP_TGT_Y
        LSR                             ; row * 64 + MAP_BASE
        ROR ZP_CELL_PTR
        LSR
        ROR ZP_CELL_PTR
        ADC #$60
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        LDY ZP_TGT_X
        RTS
@ %def TGT_CELL_PTR

Attack, Cast and Fire all aim the same way: [[DIR_PROMPT]] prints
\texttt{": "}, takes one key, and accepts only the four direction
keys (after [[KEY_ALIAS]] folds in the one-handed aliases). The
chosen direction is echoed by name from [[STR_COMMANDS]], the
target cursor [[ZP_TGT_X]]/[[ZP_TGT_Y]] starts on the player, and
the signed step vector goes in [[ZP_STEP_X]]/[[ZP_STEP_Y]].
Anything else prints ``nothing'' (the first entry of the engine's
[[READY_CLASSES]] table) and returns carry set.

<<out direction prompt>>=
        ORG $8A90
DIR_PROMPT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Aim: read a direction key.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Print ": ", read one key through KEY_ALIAS, match it
        ;   against the four arrow entries of CMD_KEYS. On a match
        ;   echo the direction name and build the step vector;
        ;   otherwise print "nothing" and fail.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C clear -- ZP_STEP_X/Y = the step (-1/0/+1 each),
        ;     ZP_TGT_X/Y = the player's position
        ;   C set -- not a direction; "nothing" printed
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B ": ",$00
        JSR KEY_OR_IDLE
        JSR KEY_ALIAS
        LDX #$03
.find   CMP CMD_KEYS,X                  ; one of the 4 arrows?
        BNE .next
        STX ZP_STEP_X                   ; (borrowed as scratch)
        JSR STR_NTH                     ; echo "North".."West"
        DC.W STR_COMMANDS
        LDX ZP_PLR_X                    ; target := the player
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        STX ZP_TGT_X
        STY ZP_TGT_Y
        LDX #$00                        ; step := (0,0), then
        LDY #$00                        ;   bend per direction
        DEC ZP_STEP_X
        BMI .north
        DEC ZP_STEP_X
        BMI .south
        DEC ZP_STEP_X
        BMI .east
        DEX                             ; west: dx = -1
.done   STX ZP_STEP_X
        STY ZP_STEP_Y
        CLC
        RTS
.north  DEY
        BNE .done                       ; (always)
.south  INY
        BNE .done
.east   INX
        BNE .done
.next   DEX
        BPL .find
        JSR STR_FIRST                   ; "nothing"
        DC.W READY_CLASSES
        SEC
        RTS
@ %def DIR_PROMPT

\section{OUT: aiming and hitting things}

[[PROJ_WALK]] walks the target cursor along the aimed direction,
[[RANGE_CNT]] cells at most --- range 1 for melee weapons, 3 for
bows and firearms (see [[WEAP_RANGE]]), 3 for ship weapons. Each
cell is tested twice: mountains stop the shot dead, and
[[MON_FIND]] checks the object records for a monster to hit.

<<out projectile walk>>=
        ORG $8ADC
PROJ_WALK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Walk the target cursor along the aim, RANGE_CNT cells.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_TGT_X/Y, ZP_STEP_X/Y -- from DIR_PROMPT
        ;   RANGE_CNT -- cells of reach
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Add the step to the target cursor; stop on mountains
        ;   (CELL_TYPE 3), a monster (MON_FIND), or when RANGE_CNT
        ;   runs out.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C clear -- monster found: ZP_REC/TGT_REC/CUR_MON set,
        ;     ZP_CELL_PTR/Y point at its cell
        ;   C set -- nothing in range (or a mountain in the way)
        LDA ZP_TGT_X
        CLC
        ADC ZP_STEP_X
        STA ZP_TGT_X
        TAX
        LDA ZP_TGT_Y
        CLC
        ADC ZP_STEP_Y
        STA ZP_TGT_Y
        TAY
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        CMP #$03                        ; mountains block it
        BEQ .out
        JSR MON_FIND
        BCC .out                        ; hit something
        DEC RANGE_CNT
        BNE PROJ_WALK
        SEC
.out    RTS
@ %def PROJ_WALK

The monster lookup translates a cell byte back to a monster index
(cell bytes [[$20]]--[[$59]]; index = byte/4 $-$ 2) and locks the
record as the current target.

<<out monster at cell>>=
        ORG $8AFF
MON_FIND
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Find a monster record at cell (ZP_TGT_X, ZP_TGT_Y).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Scan the record arrays for matching coordinates with a
        ;   monster cell byte ($20-$59); decode the byte to a
        ;   monster index and lock the target.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C clear -- found: ZP_REC and TGT_REC = the record,
        ;     CUR_MON = the monster index, ZP_CELL_PTR/Y = cell
        ;   C set -- no monster there
        LDX OBJ_COUNT
        BEQ .none
.scan   DEX
        LDA OBJ_X,X
        CMP ZP_TGT_X
        BNE .next
        LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$3F
        CMP ZP_TGT_Y
        BNE .next
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        CMP #$20                        ; monsters only
        BCC .next
        CMP #$5A
        BCS .next
        LSR                             ; cell byte -> monster
        LSR                             ;   index (byte/4 - 2)
        ADC #$FE
        STA CUR_MON
        STX ZP_REC
        STX TGT_REC
        JSR OBJ_PTR_X
        CLC
        RTS
.next   TXA
        BNE .scan
.none   SEC
        RTS
@ %def MON_FIND

\section{OUT: the Attack command}

\emph{Attack} fights with the readied weapon. Its reach comes from
[[WEAP_RANGE]] --- 1 for most arms, 3 for bows and the
Space-Age guns, 0 for things that cannot swing at all (rope \&
spikes, and the magic weapons, which fight through \emph{Cast}
instead). The to-hit roll is agility-based: hit if
$\mathrm{rnd} < \mathrm{agility} + 128$. Damage is a random pick
from $8\times\mathrm{weapon} + \mathrm{strength}$, halved, plus
one.

The little tile dance around [[DRAW_MAP]] is the attack flash: the
target's cell is overwritten with the splash tile (cell byte
[[$5E]]), one frame is drawn, and the monster's own tile is put
back.

<<out cmd attack>>=
        ORG $8B36
CMD_ATTACK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Attack with the readied weapon.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Print the weapon, fetch its reach from WEAP_RANGE (zero
        ;   cannot attack), aim via DIR_PROMPT, walk the shot, flash
        ;   the splash tile, roll rnd < agility + 128 to hit, and
        ;   fall into MON_HIT with rnd(8*weapon + strength)/2 + 1.
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "with ",$00
        LDX READY_WEAPON
        JSR STR_NTH                     ; short weapon name
        DC.W STR_WEAPONS_S
        LDX READY_WEAPON
        LDA WEAP_RANGE,X
        BNE .armed
        JMP QUERY_MARK                  ; can't attack with that
.armed  STA RANGE_CNT
        JSR DIR_PROMPT
        BCC .aimed
        RTS
MISS_MSG
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Miss!",$00
        RTS
.aimed  LDA #$06                        ; the swing sound
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        JSR PROJ_WALK
        BCS MISS_MSG
        LDA #$5E                        ; flash the splash tile
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y             ;   over the target
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        JSR OBJ_PTR
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X                  ; put the monster back
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        LDA PLR_AGI                     ; hit if rnd < agi + 128
        CLC
        ADC #$80
        STA ZP_CHANCE
        JSR RND
        CMP ZP_CHANCE
        BCC .hit
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Missed",$00
        JMP PRINT_THE_MON
.hit    LDA READY_WEAPON                ; damage: rnd(8*weapon
        ASL                             ;   + strength)/2 + 1
        ASL
        ASL
        ADC PLR_STR
        JSR RND_MOD
        LSR
        CLC
        ADC #$01
@ %def CMD_ATTACK MISS_MSG

\section{OUT: damage, loot and experience}

All three player attacks --- weapon, Magic Missile, ship guns ---
funnel into [[MON_HIT]] with the damage in A. A monster that
survives reports the number; one that dies pays out experience and
coin on the spot.

The payouts both scale from the monster's tier:
experience += $\mathrm{TIER\_HP}[\mathrm{tier}]/2$ (randomized
once it is 2 or more), and the coin purse gains
$\mathrm{rnd}(4\times\mathrm{tier}) + 10$, announced in the
period flavor --- the binary amount is converted with [[BIN2BCD]]
and read out digit by digit as \emph{copper}, \emph{silver} and
\emph{gold} pieces (ones, tens, hundreds).

<<out monster damage>>=
        ORG $8BAC
MON_HIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Apply A damage to the target monster.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A -- damage; ZP_REC/CUR_MON -- the target
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Subtract from OBJ_HP. Survives: print "Hit <n>
        ;   damage". Dies: print "Killed", remove the record,
        ;   award experience and coin, clamp both at 9999.
        STA DMG_AMT
        LDA #$00
        STA NUM_PAD
        LDX ZP_REC
        LDA OBJ_HP,X
        SEC
        SBC DMG_AMT
        BEQ .killed
        BCC .killed
        STA OBJ_HP,X
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Hit",$00
        JSR PRINT_THE_MON
        LDA MON_CH                      ; keep the number on the
        CMP #$15                        ;   line
        BCC .num
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.num    LDA DMG_AMT
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " damage",$00
.sfx    LDA #$02                        ; the hit crunch
        JMP SFX_PLAY
.killed JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Killed",$00
        JSR PRINT_THE_MON
        JSR .sfx
        LDX CUR_MON                     ; exp += TIER_HP[tier]/2,
        LDY MON_TIER,X                  ;   randomized when >= 2
        LDA TIER_HP,Y
        LSR
        CMP #$02
        BCC .exp
        JSR RND_MOD
.exp    ADC PLR_EXP
        STA PLR_EXP
        BCC .coin
        INC PLR_EXP+1
.coin   TYA                             ; coin: rnd(4*tier) + 10
        ASL
        ASL
        JSR RND_MOD
        CLC
        ADC #$0A
        PHA
        TAX
        LDA #$00
        JSR BIN2BCD
        LDA ZP_BCD                      ; ones -> "copper!"
        AND #$0F
        BEQ .silver
        JSR COIN_DIGIT
        DC.B "copper! ",$00
.silver LDA ZP_BCD                      ; tens -> "silver!"
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        BEQ .gold
        JSR COIN_DIGIT
        DC.B "silver! ",$00
.gold   LDA ZP_BCD+1                    ; hundreds -> "gold!"
        BEQ .add
        JSR COIN_DIGIT
        DC.B "gold!",$00
.add    PLA
        CLC
        ADC PLR_COIN
        STA PLR_COIN
        BCC .clamp
        INC PLR_COIN+1
.clamp  JSR SCORE_CLAMP
        JMP TGT_REMOVE
COIN_DIGIT
        ; Print the digit in A, then the caller's inline text.
        PHA
        LDA MON_CH
        CMP #$15
        BCC .col
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.col    PLA
        JSR PRINT_DIGIT
        INC MON_CH
        JMP MSG_PRINT
PRINT_THE_MON
        ; Print " the <monster>! " for the current fight.
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " the ",$00
        LDX CUR_MON
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "! ",$00
        RTS
@ %def MON_HIT COIN_DIGIT PRINT_THE_MON

[[TGT_REMOVE]] retires the target record --- after a kill, and
also for Prayer's ``Monster removed!'' miracle. [[SCORE_CLAMP]]
caps experience and coin at 9999 so the four-digit stats panel
never overflows.

<<out loot bookkeeping>>=
        ORG $8C9C
TGT_REMOVE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Remove the locked target record, if it is a monster.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If TGT_REC still indexes a live monster record, remove
        ;   it and clear the lock.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C clear -- removed (TGT_REC cleared to FF)
        ;   C set -- no valid monster target
        LDX TGT_REC
        CPX OBJ_COUNT
        BCS .no
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        CMP #$20
        BCC .no
        CMP #$5A
        BCS .no
        JSR OBJ_REMOVE
        LDX #$00
        STX CUR_MON
        STX ZP_REC
        DEX
        STX TGT_REC                     ; TGT_REC <- #$FF
        CLC
        RTS
.no     SEC
        RTS
SCORE_CLAMP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Clamp PLR_EXP and PLR_COIN to 9999; repaint the stats.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Two 16-bit compares against 10000; anything over is
        ;   rewritten as 9999. Tail-calls STATS_VALUES.
        LDA PLR_EXP                     ; 16-bit compare vs 10000
        CMP #$10
        LDA PLR_EXP+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .coin
        LDA #$0F                        ; exp <- #$270F (9999)
        STA PLR_EXP
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_EXP+1
.coin   LDA PLR_COIN
        CMP #$10
        LDA PLR_COIN+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .done
        LDA #$0F                        ; coin <- #$270F
        STA PLR_COIN
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_COIN+1
.done   JMP STATS_VALUES
@ %def TGT_REMOVE SCORE_CLAMP

\section{OUT: the Board command and the time machine}

\emph{Board} mounts whatever transport is parked underfoot (cell
codes 8--15). The parked object record is removed from the world,
[[READY_TRANSPORT]] takes its index, and the player tile changes.
Code 15 is special twice over: it boards as transport 10 --- the
\emph{time machine} --- and launches the endgame sequence, but
only for a player holding all four gems. Boarding the shuttle
(transport 6) switches to the space overlay immediately.

<<out cmd board>>=
        ORG $8CF0
CMD_BOARD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Board the transport parked under the player.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Refuse if already riding or nothing parked here. Take
        ;   the cell code as the transport (15 boards as the time
        ;   machine), remove the parked record, retile the player.
        ;   The shuttle exits to SPA; the time machine to TM_BOARD.
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        BEQ .afoot
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "X-it thy craft first!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.afoot  JSR CELL_HERE
        CMP #$10                        ; parked craft here?
        BCS .none                       ;   (codes 8-15)
        CMP #$08
        BCS .board
.none   JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "nothing to Board!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.board  AND #$07
        CMP #$07                        ; code 15: the time
        BCC .mount                      ;   machine is index 10
        LDA #$0A
.mount  STA READY_TRANSPORT
        PHA
        JSR OBJ_FIND_REMOVE             ; unpark the record
        JSR PLAYER_TILE_SET
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        PLA
        CMP #$03
        BCS .name                       ; animals get "Mount"
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Mount ",$00
.name   JSR TRANSPORT_NAME
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        CMP #$06                        ; the shuttle: to space
        BEQ .space
        BCS TM_BOARD                    ; 7+: the time machine
        RTS
.space  LDA #$14                        ; LOC_NAME offset of SPA
TM_GO   JMP EXIT_TO
@ %def CMD_BOARD TM_GO

Boarding a time machine is the endgame gate. With all four gems
in hand it simply jumps to the \texttt{TM} overlay (offset
[[$18]]). Otherwise the game opens a popup sketching the four
gem holes --- \texttt{R G B W} --- and lights a colored marker
over each gem the player owns, so the craft itself reports the
quest progress. The marker colors are hi-res palette indexes:
orange, green, blue, white.

<<out time machine check>>=
        ORG $8D73
TM_BOARD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The time machine: all four gems, or a hint popup.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   All four gems: EXIT_TO the TM overlay. Otherwise draw
        ;   the four-holes popup, mark each owned gem with a colored
        ;   dash, explain what is missing, and put the screen back.
        LDA OWNED_GEMS
        BEQ .show
        LDA OWNED_GEMS+1
        BEQ .show
        LDA OWNED_GEMS+2
        BEQ .show
        LDA OWNED_GEMS+3
        BEQ .show
        LDA #$18                        ; LOC_NAME offset of TM
        BNE TM_GO                       ; (always)
.show   JSR WIN_SAVE                    ; popup over the viewport
        JSR VIEW_CLEAR
        JSR WIN_VIEW
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL                 ; page flips off
        JSR WIN_SHRINK
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "||||",$7F,$03,"Entering the craft, thou dost|",$7F
        DC.B $03,"remark upon four holes marked:||",$7F,$0D
        DC.B "o  o  o  o|",$7F,$0D,"R  G  B  W||",$00
        LDA OWNED_GEMS                  ; any gem at all?
        ORA OWNED_GEMS+1
        ORA OWNED_GEMS+2
        ORA OWNED_GEMS+3
        BNE .marks
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B $7F,$02,"Thou canst not determine how to|",$7F,$02
        DC.B "operate the craft at this time.",$00
.close  LDA #$60                        ; page flips back on
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL
        JSR PAGE_FLIP
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JSR PAUSE_ABORTABLE
        JMP PAUSE_ABORTABLE+3           ; skip its KBD_CLEAR: any
                                        ;   key already buffered
                                        ;   cuts the pause short
.marks  LDA OWNED_GEMS                  ; red gem: orange mark
        BEQ .green
        LDX #$5E
        LDA #$05
        JSR GEM_MARK
.green  LDA OWNED_GEMS+1
        BEQ .blue
        LDX #$73
        LDA #$01                        ; (hi-res green)
        JSR GEM_MARK
.blue   LDA OWNED_GEMS+2
        BEQ .white
        LDX #$88
        LDA #$06
        JSR GEM_MARK
.white  LDA OWNED_GEMS+3
        BEQ .msg
        LDX #$9D
        LDA #$07
        JSR GEM_MARK
.msg    JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B $7F,$05,"Thou hast not all the gems|",$7F,$04
        DC.B "needed to operate thy craft!",$00
        JMP .close
@ %def TM_BOARD

Each marker is six short strokes: three double-width horizontal
lines drawn twice ([[GEM_MARK]] recurses into its own tail to
repeat the row pattern), making a chunky colored dash above the
gem hole.

<<out gem indicator>>=
        ORG $8ED5
GEM_MARK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw one gem marker.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   X -- left pixel column; A -- hi-res color index
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Set the color, then draw six 4-pixel horizontal strokes
        ;   on consecutive rows from row 58 down (the JSR ladder
        ;   runs the tail 2+2+2 times).
        STX ZP_TMP
        INX
        INX
        INX
        INX
        STX ZP_TMP2                     ; right edge = left + 4
        LDY #$39
        STY ZP_BOX_T                    ; ZP_PY <- #$39 (row 57)
        JSR COLOR_SET
        JSR .two                        ; 2 + 2 + 2 rows of dash
.two    JSR .one
        JSR .one
.one    LDX ZP_TMP
        STX ZP_BOX_L                    ; ZP_PX <- left edge
        LDX ZP_TMP2
        INC ZP_BOX_T                    ; next row down
        LDY ZP_BOX_T
        JMP LINE_TO
@ %def GEM_MARK

\section{OUT: leaving the map}

Every exit from the outdoors funnels through [[EXIT_TO]]: store
the position for the next visit, put the packed world map back at
[[MAP_BASE]] (undoing the entry stash, so the next overlay --- or
the next OUT entry --- finds it where \texttt{/U1.VARS} loaded
it), and hand the [[LOC_NAME]] offset to [[GAME_LOAD]].

<<out exit to>>=
        ORG $8EFA
EXIT_TO
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Leave OUT for the overlay at LOC_NAME offset A.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Save the position, copy the 14 packed-map pages from
        ;   MAP_PACKED back to MAP_BASE (self-modified page bytes),
        ;   and tail-call GAME_LOAD.
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        STX PLR_OUT_X
        STY PLR_OUT_Y
        PHA
        LDX #$0E                        ; the packed map goes
        LDY #$00                        ;   back to MAP_BASE
.unstash
UNSTASH_SRC = *+2
        LDA MAP_PACKED,Y
UNSTASH_DST = *+2
        STA MAP_BASE,Y
        INY
        BNE .unstash
        INC UNSTASH_SRC                 ; (self-modified)
        INC UNSTASH_DST
        DEX
        BNE .unstash
        PLA
        JMP GAME_LOAD
@ %def EXIT_TO UNSTASH_SRC UNSTASH_DST

\section{OUT: the Cast command and Prayer}

Outdoors, magic is thin: only \emph{Magic Missile} (spell 3) and
\emph{Kill} (spell 10) may be cast, and trying anything else
wastes the scroll --- ``Failed, dungeon spell only!'' decrements
the count all the same. With no spell readied, the character
falls back on \emph{Prayer} (spell 0), which is free.

A cast shouts its incantation (the [[INCANT]] table), then runs
like a ranged attack with reach 3. Non-wizards fail outright when
$\mathrm{rnd} \geq \mathrm{wisdom} + 128$ (class 2 never rolls).
Magic Missile's damage is $\mathrm{rnd}(\mathrm{intelligence})+1$,
multiplied by the readied \emph{magic} weapon: $\times1.5$ holding
the amulet, $\times2$ the wand, $\times3$ the staff or triangle.
Kill does flat 255 damage --- sudden death to anything outdoors.

<<out cmd cast>>=
        ORG $8F1F
CMD_CAST
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Cast the readied spell (outdoors: 3, 10, or Prayer).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Filter: Prayer when nothing readied; only spells 3 and
        ;   10 work outdoors (others are consumed for nothing). Aim,
        ;   shout the incantation, roll wisdom to cast, walk the
        ;   shot, and hand MON_HIT the damage.
        JSR PRINT_SPELL
        LDX READY_SPELL
        BNE .have
        JMP PRAYER                      ; spell 0: Prayer
.have   LDA OWNED_SPELLS,X
        BNE .stocked
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~You've used up that spell!",$00
        JMP BEEP_CMD
.stocked
        CPX #$03                        ; Magic Missile
        BEQ .castable
        CPX #$0A                        ; Kill
        BEQ .castable
        DEC OWNED_SPELLS,X              ; wasted anyway!
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Failed, dungeon spell only!",$00
        JMP BEEP_CMD
.castable
        JSR DIR_PROMPT
        BCC .aimed
        JMP OUT_MAIN
.aimed  LDA #$0A
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDX READY_SPELL
        DEC OWNED_SPELLS,X
        CPX #$0A                        ; pick the incantation:
        LDX #$00                        ;   0 = Missile, 1 = Kill
        BCC .shout
        INX
.shout  JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W INCANT
        LDX #$03                        ; reach 3
        STX RANGE_CNT
        DEX
        CPX PLR_CLASS                   ; class 2 cannot fail
        BEQ .sure
        LDA #$80                        ; else rnd < wis + 128
        CLC
        ADC PLR_WIS
        STA ZP_CHANCE
        JSR RND
        CMP ZP_CHANCE
        BCC .sure
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Failed!",$00
.bail   JSR BEEP_CMD
        JMP OUT_MAIN
.miss   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Miss!",$00
        JMP .bail
.sure   JSR PROJ_WALK
        BCS .miss
        LDA #$5C                        ; the missile splash
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        JSR OBJ_PTR
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        LDA READY_SPELL
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .missile
        LDA #$FF                        ; Kill: flat 255
        JMP MON_HIT
.missile
        LDA PLR_INT                     ; rnd(int) + 1 ...
        JSR RND_MOD
        INC ZP_CHANCE
        LDA ZP_CHANCE
        LDX READY_WEAPON                ; ... scaled by the magic
        CPX #$08                        ;   weapon in hand
        BCC .deal
        CPX #$0C
        BCS .deal
        ASL                             ; x2
        CPX #$09                        ; the wand stops here
        BEQ .deal
        CLC
        ADC ZP_CHANCE                   ; x3: staff, triangle
        CPX #$08
        BNE .deal
        LSR                             ; the amulet: x1.5
.deal   JMP MON_HIT
@ %def CMD_CAST

The incantations are pure flavor --- dog-Latin shouted before the
bolt flies.

<<out incantations>>=
        ORG $901A
INCANT  ; the spoken spells: Magic Missile, then Kill
        DC.B "~",$22,"DELCIO-ERE-UI!",$22,$A0
        DC.B "~",$22,"INTERFICIO-NUNC!",$22,$A0
@ %def INCANT

Prayer is the catch-all miracle for a character with nothing
readied: it tops up whichever vital is desperate (hit points
below 15, then food below 15, each restored \emph{to} 15 with a
``Shazam!''), and failing that, one time in four it spirits away
the monster last fought. Otherwise --- ``Hmmmm... no effect?''

<<out prayer>>=
        ORG $9040
PRAYER
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Spell 0: free, feeble, occasionally a miracle.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Shout, then: hits below 15 are raised to 15; else food
        ;   likewise; else 1 chance in 4 to TGT_REMOVE the current
        ;   monster; else no effect.
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~",$22,"POTENTIS-LAUDIS!",$22,$00
        LDA #$0A
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDY #$0F
        LDA PLR_HITS+1                  ; hits below 15?
        BNE .food
        CPY PLR_HITS
        BCC .food
        BEQ .food
        STY PLR_HITS                    ; PLR_HITS <- #$0F
.shazam JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " Shazam!",$00
        RTS
.food   LDA PLR_FOOD+1                  ; food below 15?
        BNE .banish
        CPY PLR_FOOD
        BCC .banish
        BEQ .banish
        STY PLR_FOOD                    ; PLR_FOOD <- #$0F
        BNE .shazam                     ; (always)
.banish JSR RND                         ; 1 in 4: banish the
        AND #$03                        ;   current target
        BNE .nope
        JSR TGT_REMOVE
        BCS .nope
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Monster removed!",$00
        RTS
.nope   JMP NO_EFFECT_MSG
@ %def PRAYER

\section{OUT: the Enter command}

[[CELL_PROBE]] is Enter's little scout, used when walking into a
town or castle: it reports whether a neighboring cell could hold
a parked transport. The answer is the cell's terrain code (0--2)
if it is open ground and the world's parking lot is not full, or
[[$FF]]. The town/castle overlay later writes a transport cell
code over the answer for every craft the player should find
waiting on the way out --- which [[MAP_REFRESH]] then turns back
into object records. (How the in-town side fills these slots is
confirmed in the TWN/CAS rounds.)

<<out cell probe>>=
        ORG $90B0
CELL_PROBE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Can cell (X, Y) hold a parked craft?
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Refuse when PARK_CNT has hit 53 or the cell is not
        ;   open terrain; otherwise count it and return its code.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A -- the terrain code (0-2), or FF if blocked/full
        LDA PARK_CNT
        CMP #$35                        ; 53 craft world-wide max
        BCS .no
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        CMP #$03                        ; open terrain only
        BCS .no
        INC PARK_CNT
        RTS
.no     LDA #$FF
        RTS
@ %def CELL_PROBE

\emph{Enter} works on the four enterable terrain codes. Towns
(code 6) and castles (code 4) switch overlays after some
bookkeeping: the transport census refreshes [[OWNED_TRANSPORT]]
so shops and kings know what the player has, and the four cells
around a town are probed into [[COURT_CELLS]]. Dungeon mouths
(code 7) just load \texttt{DNG}. Code 5 is a \emph{landmark} ---
the per-continent pair of special sites handled below. Everything
else gets a ``?''.

<<out cmd enter>>=
        ORG $90C5
ENTER_HUH
        ; Enter: nothing enterable underfoot.
        JMP QUERY_MARK
CMD_ENTER
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Enter the place under the player.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Save the position. Landmarks (code 5) match PLR_PLACE
        ;   against LM_PLACE and run LANDMARK. Castles load CAS;
        ;   towns run the census, probe the four COURT_CELLS, and
        ;   load TWN; dungeon mouths load DNG.
        LDX ZP_PLR_X                    ; remember where, for the
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y                    ;   return trip
        STX PLR_OUT_X
        STY PLR_OUT_Y
        JSR CELL_HERE
        CMP #$04                        ; enterable: codes 4-7
        BCC ENTER_HUH
        CMP #$08
        BCS ENTER_HUH
        JSR MSG_PRINT                   ; complete the echo:
        DC.B "ing...",$00               ;   "Entering..."
        JSR CMD_INFORM                  ; name the place
        LDA UNDER_TYPE
        CMP #$05                        ; a landmark?
        BNE .place
        LDA PLR_PLACE                   ; only the 8 known sites
        LDX #$07                        ;   respond
.known  CMP LM_PLACE,X
        BEQ LANDMARK
        DEX
        BPL .known
        RTS
.place  CMP #$04
        BNE .town
        LDA #$10                        ; a castle: load CAS
        BNE .exit                       ; (always)
.town   CMP #$06
        BNE .dungeon
        JSR CENSUS                      ; count the fleet for the
        LDX ZP_PLR_X                    ;   shops, and probe the
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y                    ;   courtyard for parking
        DEY
        JSR CELL_PROBE
        STA COURT_CELLS                 ; north
        INY
        DEX
        JSR CELL_PROBE
        STA COURT_CELLS+1               ; west
        INX
        INX
        JSR CELL_PROBE
        STA COURT_CELLS+2               ; east
        DEX
        INY
        JSR CELL_PROBE
        STA COURT_CELLS+3               ; south
        LDA #$0C                        ; a town: load TWN
        BNE .exit                       ; (always)
.dungeon
        LDA #$08                        ; load DNG
.exit   JMP EXIT_TO
@ %def ENTER_HUH CMD_ENTER

\section{OUT: landmarks and their boons}

Each continent hides two landmarks (local places 2 and 3 --- see
[[LM_PLACE]]): a signpost, a grave, a pillar, the Ozymandias
pedestal, the Tower of Knowledge. Entering one opens a popup with
its inscription from [[STR_SIGNS]] --- Sosaria's epigraphy runs
from Shelley to schoolboy Latin --- and then grants the boon:

\begin{itemize}
\item If the site closes one of the even-numbered [[QUEST_FLAGS]]
slots and that quest is active (the flag is 1), it completes ---
``A Quest is completed!'' with a border flash. (The kings assign
these quests in the castle overlay.)
\item Sites with a stat index in [[LM_STAT]] raise that attribute
toward its cap: gain $\lceil(99-\mathrm{stat})/10\rceil$, to a
maximum of 99. The Tower of Knowledge raises intelligence, the
pedestal wisdom, the grave stamina.
\item The Signpost (site 4) hands over the first weapon the
player lacks --- ``You find a great sword!''.
\end{itemize}

A landmark goes dormant after a visit ([[PLR_LASTMARK]]) until
some other landmark is used, so the boons cannot be farmed by
standing in place.

<<out landmarks>>=
        ORG $913A
LANDMARK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Show landmark X's inscription and grant its boon.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Popup the inscription. Complete the LM_QUEST slot if
        ;   that quest is active. Then the boon: raise the LM_STAT
        ;   attribute by a tenth of what is missing to 99, or (the
        ;   Signpost) grant the first unowned weapon. PLR_LASTMARK
        ;   blocks repeat visits.
        STX LM_SAVE
        JSR POPUP_FRAME
        LDX LM_SAVE
        JSR STR_NTH                     ; the inscription
        DC.W STR_SIGNS
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JSR KBD_CLEAR
        LDX LM_SAVE
        LDY LM_QUEST,X                  ; closes a quest slot?
        BMI .boon
        LDA QUEST_FLAGS,Y               ; active quests only
        BEQ .boon
        BMI .boon
        LDA #$FF                        ; QUEST_FLAGS[Y] <- done
        STA QUEST_FLAGS,Y
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "}A Quest is completed!",$00
        JSR LM_JINGLE
.boon   LDX LM_SAVE
        LDA LM_STAT,X
        BNE .stat
        CPX #$04                        ; only the Signpost has
        BNE .done                       ;   a non-stat boon
        CPX PLR_LASTMARK                ; not twice in a row
        BEQ .dud
        LDX #$00
.scan   INX                             ; first weapon not owned
        LDA OWNED_WEAPONS,X
        BEQ .give
        CPX #$0F
        BCC .scan
.dud    JSR NO_EFFECT_MSG
        JMP .done
.give   LDA #$01
        STA OWNED_WEAPONS,X
        STX ZP_TMP
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~You find a",$00
        LDX ZP_TMP
        CPX #$03                        ; "an" axe / amulet
        BEQ .an
        CPX #$08
        BNE .name
.an     LDA #$6E                        ; 'n'
        JSR CHAR_OUT
.name   INC MON_CH
        LDX ZP_TMP
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_WEAPONS
        LDA #$21                        ; '!'
        JSR CHAR_OUT
.ding   JSR LM_JINGLE
.done   LDA LM_SAVE                     ; the site goes dormant
        STA PLR_LASTMARK
        JMP PAUSE_ABORTABLE
.dud2   JMP .dud
.stat   CPX PLR_LASTMARK                ; not twice in a row
        BEQ .dud2
        STA ZP_TMP                      ; the stat index
        ASL
        TAX
        LDA PLR_HITS,X                  ; (stats are word pairs
        STA ZP_TMP2                     ;   from PLR_HITS)
        SEC
        LDA #$63
        SBC PLR_HITS,X
        BCC .dud2                       ; already past 99
        ADC #$08                        ; gain (99-stat+9)/10
        JSR DIV10
        ADC PLR_HITS,X
        CMP #$63
        BCC .raise
        LDA #$63                        ; cap at 99
.raise  STA PLR_HITS,X
        SEC
        SBC ZP_TMP2
        BEQ .dud2                       ; nothing gained
        PHA
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "}Thou dost gain ",$00
        PLA
        JSR PRINT_DIGIT
        INC MON_CH
        LDX ZP_TMP
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_STATS
        JMP .ding
LM_JINGLE
        ; Flash the popup border white and ring the ding.
        LDA #$07                        ; white
        JSR POPUP_BORDER_A
        LDA #$0A
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        JSR .pause
        JSR POPUP_BORDER                ; back to blue
.pause  LDA #$E6
        JMP VDELAY
@ %def LANDMARK LM_JINGLE

\section{OUT: the Fire command}

\emph{Fire} is the mounted weapon: cannons from a frigate, lasers
from an aircar, ``what?'' from anything else. The shot aims like
an attack with reach 3, misses flat one time in five, and deals
$\mathrm{rnd}(\mathrm{TIER\_HP}[\mathrm{transport}]) + 30$ ---
the same 0--100 scale table doing double duty, giving cannons
rnd(40) and lasers rnd(50).

<<out cmd fire>>=
        ORG $924A
CMD_FIRE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Fire the transport's weapon.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Cannons from a frigate, lasers from an aircar. Aim and
        ;   walk the shot 3 cells; miss flat 51/256; damage is
        ;   rnd(TIER_HP[transport]) + 30 into MON_HIT.
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        CPX #$04                        ; frigate?
        BNE .notship
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "cannons",$00
        JMP .aim
.notship
        CPX #$05                        ; aircar?
        BEQ .lasers
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "what",$00
        JMP QUERY_MARK
.lasers JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "lasers",$00
.aim    JSR DIR_PROMPT
        BCC .aimed
        RTS
.miss   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Miss!",$00
        RTS
.aimed  LDA #$0C                        ; the report
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDA #$03                        ; reach 3
        STA RANGE_CNT
        JSR PROJ_WALK
        BCS .miss
        LDA #$5E                        ; splash the target
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        JSR OBJ_PTR
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        JSR RND
        CMP #$33                        ; flat 20% miss
        BCS .hit
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Missed",$00
        JMP PRINT_THE_MON
.hit    LDX READY_TRANSPORT             ; rnd(TIER_HP[transport])
        LDA TIER_HP,X                   ;   + 30 damage
        JSR RND_MOD
        ADC #$1E
        JMP MON_HIT
@ %def CMD_FIRE

\section{OUT: saving, readying, dismounting}

\emph{Quit} is a misnomer kept from the command list: it saves
the game and plays on. The whole player block --- vitals,
inventory, position, quest flags \emph{and} the object records
--- is one [[MLIB_BSAVE_P]] of 458 bytes to \texttt{/U1.PLAYER}.
Nothing else needs saving: the world map proper is immutable ---
the packed continents are loaded read-only from \texttt{/U1.VARS}
and never written back (and \texttt{/U1.VARS} is absent from this
crack disk; \texttt{MAKE.INDATA}, now fully decompiled in
section~\ref{sec:makeindata}, builds only the title screens, not
this file) --- so the records are the entire mutable world.

<<out cmd quit>>=
        ORG $92CA
CMD_QUIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Quit-(saving game...): write /U1.PLAYER, keep playing.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Store the position and MLIB_BSAVE_P the 458-byte block
        ;   at PLR_SAVE to /U1.PLAYER, retrying through the disk
        ;   prompt; report "saved."
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        STX PLR_OUT_X
        STY PLR_OUT_Y
        JSR WIN_SAVE
.retry  JSR MLIB_BSAVE_P
        DC.W PLR_SAVE                   ; the saved block,
        DC.W $01CA                      ;   458 bytes
        DC.W PATH_PLAYER
        JSR DISK_PROMPT_P               ; wrong disk? ask, retry
        BCS .retry
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "saved.",$00
        JMP CLR_EOL
@ %def CMD_QUIT

\emph{Ready} just forwards to the engine: wait for the
W/A/S selector key, then [[READY_CMD]] runs its menus.

<<out cmd ready>>=
        ORG $92F2
CMD_READY
        ; Ready Weapon/Armour/Spell: the engine does the work.
        JSR KEY_OR_IDLE
        JMP READY_CMD
@ %def CMD_READY

\emph{X-it} parks the current transport on the spot as a fresh
object record --- which is exactly how it will be found again,
by Board, by the census, by anyone. Dismounting is only allowed
on open terrain (codes 0--2; a frigate is left \emph{on} its
water cell, with the player standing on the same cell until the
next move). Transports 7 and up park as cell code 15, a time
machine.

<<out cmd exit transport>>=
        ORG $92F8
CMD_XIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; X-it: park the transport here.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Allowed on open terrain only: spawn a record with cell
        ;   code transport + 8 (15 for index 7 and up) and go on
        ;   foot.
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        BNE .have
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " what",$00
        JMP QUERY_MARK
.have   JSR CELL_HERE
        CMP #$03                        ; open terrain only
        BCC .park
.cant   JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Thou canst not leave it here!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.park   LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        CMP #$07                        ; 7+ parks as a time
        BCC .code                       ;   machine (code 15)
        LDA #$07
.code   ORA #$08                        ; transport cell code
        JSR OBJ_SPAWN
        BCS .cant                       ; record table full
        LDA #$00
        STA READY_TRANSPORT
        RTS
@ %def CMD_XIT

\section{OUT: moving across the world}

The four direction commands share one tiny prologue --- fetch the
position, clear carry --- and bend one coordinate each before
falling into the shared mover. (The [[BCC]]s are branch-always:
nothing between [[POS_LOAD]]'s [[CLC]] and the branch touches
carry.)

<<out direction commands>>=
        ORG $9351
POS_LOAD
        ; X/Y := the player's position; C clear.
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        CLC
        RTS
CMD_NORTH
        ; the four movement commands
        JSR POS_LOAD
        DEY
        BCC MOVE_STEP                   ; (always)
CMD_SOUTH
        JSR POS_LOAD
        INY
        BCC MOVE_STEP
CMD_EAST
        JSR POS_LOAD
        INX
        BCC MOVE_STEP
CMD_WEST
        JSR POS_LOAD
        DEX
@ %def POS_LOAD CMD_NORTH CMD_SOUTH CMD_EAST CMD_WEST

The mover is the terrain rulebook. Water needs a raft or frigate;
mountains stop everyone; aircars cannot put down in forest; rafts
and frigates beach on any land (``Frigates like water!''); cell
codes 16 and up are something alive --- ``Blocked by an orc!''.
A craft of index 6 or more (the shuttle, a boarded time machine)
does not surface-travel at all.

<<out move step>>=
        ORG $936D
MOVE_STEP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Try to step the player to (X, Y).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Read the destination cell and apply the rulebook; legal
        ;   steps branch to MOVE_DO, refusals print their string
        ;   from STR_BLOCKED (or name the blocking monster) and
        ;   play the bump.
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        STX ZP_DST_X
        STY ZP_DST_Y
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        CMP #$06
        BCC .terrain
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Can't travel on land!",$00
        JMP .blat
.terrain
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        TAX
        BNE .notwater
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT             ; water: raft or frigate
        CMP #$03
        BCS MOVE_DO
        BCC .say                        ; (X=0: the water string)
.notwater
        LDX #$01
        CMP #$03                        ; mountains
        BEQ .say
        CMP #$10                        ; someone in the way
        BCS .blocked
        INX
        CMP #$02                        ; forest:
        BNE .craft
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT             ;   no aircar landings
        CMP #$05
        BEQ .say
.craft  LDX READY_TRANSPORT             ; water craft beach on
        CPX #$03                        ;   any land
        BEQ .beach
        CPX #$04
        BNE MOVE_DO
.beach  JSR STR_NTH_CAP                 ; "Raft"/"Frigate"
        DC.W STR_TRANSPORT
        LDX #$03                        ;   + "s like water!"
.say    JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_BLOCKED
.blat   LDA #$0E                        ; the bump sound
        JMP SFX_PLAY_FLUSH
.blocked
        PHA
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Blocked by a",$00
        PLA
        SEC                             ; cell code -> monster
        SBC #$04                        ;   index
        LSR
        TAX
        CPX #$0E                        ; "an": evil trent,
        BEQ .an                         ;   orc, evil ranger
        CPX #$10
        BEQ .an
        CPX #$13
        BNE .mname
.an     LDA #$6E                        ; 'n'
        JSR CHAR_OUT
.mname  INC MON_CH
        CPX #$14                        ; the warlock's name
        BNE .pr                         ;   needs its own line
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.pr     JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        LDA #$21                        ; '!'
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        JMP .blat
@ %def MOVE_STEP

A legal step commits the position, lets [[EDGE_CROSS]] handle
walking off the continent, and charges the fare from the
per-transport tables: faster mounts eat less food \emph{and} less
time per step. A step on foot is exactly $1.00$ on the move
counter (via [[MOVE_CNT_INC]]) and half a ration of food; a
shuttle step is $0.14$ time and nothing to eat. Land transports
thump ([[TICK_SND]]); boats and aircraft glide silently.

<<out move commit>>=
        ORG $9416
MOVE_DO
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Commit the step to (ZP_DST_X, ZP_DST_Y); charge fare.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Store the new position, let EDGE_CROSS handle leaving
        ;   the continent, then TICK the per-transport food and time
        ;   fare (a foot step adds its 1.00 via MOVE_CNT_INC).
        LDX ZP_DST_X
        LDY ZP_DST_Y
        STX ZP_PLR_X
        STY ZP_PLR_Y
        JSR EDGE_CROSS
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        BNE .fare
        JSR MOVE_CNT_INC                ; on foot: a whole move
        LDX #$00
.fare   LDY FOOD_TBL,X
        LDA TIME_TBL,X
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        CPX #$03
        BCS .quiet                      ; craft glide silently
        JMP TICK_SND
.quiet  JMP TICK
@ %def MOVE_DO

<<out tick tables>>=
        ORG $943E
FOOD_TBL ; food per step, BCD hundredths, by transport
        HEX 50 43 36 29 21 14 07 00
        HEX 00 00
TIME_TBL ; time per step, BCD hundredths (foot adds its whole
         ; 1.00 through MOVE_CNT_INC instead)
        HEX 00 86 71 57 43 29 14 00
        HEX 00 00 00
@ %def FOOD_TBL TIME_TBL

\section{OUT: continent edges}

Two terrain scouts pick random cells until they find the right
kind (or give up after 256 draws): open water for spawning craft,
open land for respawning the dead. ``Land'' is anything except
water, mountains, and occupied cells --- a resurrection can
deposit the player on a town's doorstep.

<<out random terrain finders>>=
        ORG $9453
FIND_WATER
        SUBROUTINE
        ; X/Y := a random water cell.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Draw random cells until CELL_TYPE returns water, up to
        ;   256 times.
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_TRIES
.try    JSR CELL_RAND
        BEQ .got
        DEC ZP_TRIES
        BNE .try
.got    RTS
FIND_LAND
        SUBROUTINE
        ; X/Y := a random open land cell.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Draw random cells until one is neither water, nor
        ;   mountains, nor occupied (code 8+), up to 256 times.
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_TRIES
.try    JSR CELL_RAND
        BEQ .next                       ; water
        CMP #$08                        ; occupied
        BCS .next
        CMP #$03                        ; mountains
        BNE .got
.next   DEC ZP_TRIES
        BNE .try
.got    RTS
@ %def FIND_WATER FIND_LAND

Each continent floats in a 10-cell ocean margin: coordinates run
$-10\dots73$ around the $0\dots63$ map, and anything off the map
proper reads as water (see [[CELL_TYPE]]). Sailing past the
margin switches continents --- east/west neighbors differ in bit
0 of [[PLR_CONT]], north/south in bit 1, a $2\times2$ torus ---
and re-enters from the opposite margin, monsters cleared, map
rebuilt.

<<out edge crossing>>=
        ORG $9477
EDGE_CROSS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Cross to the neighbor continent past the ocean margin.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Coordinates inside -10..73 return. Beyond that: adjust
        ;   PLR_CONT (x: +/-1, y: +/-2), re-enter from the opposite
        ;   margin, clear the monsters, and fall into MAP_REFRESH.
        LDA ZP_PLR_X
        BMI .xneg
        CMP #$4A
        BCC .ycheck
        BCS .east
.xneg   CMP #$F6
        BCS .ycheck
        BCC .west                       ; (always)
.ycheck LDA ZP_PLR_Y
        BMI .yneg
        CMP #$4A
        BCC .in
        BCS .south
.yneg   CMP #$F6
        BCC .north
.in     RTS
.east   INC PLR_CONT
        LDA #$F6                        ; enter at west margin
        STA ZP_PLR_X
        BNE .reload                     ; (always)
.west   DEC PLR_CONT
        LDA #$48
        STA ZP_PLR_X
        BNE .reload
.south  DEC PLR_CONT
        DEC PLR_CONT
        LDA #$FB
        STA ZP_PLR_Y
        BNE .reload
.north  INC PLR_CONT
        INC PLR_CONT
        LDA #$43
        STA ZP_PLR_Y
.reload JSR MON_CLEAR
        ; falls into MAP_REFRESH
@ %def EDGE_CROSS

\section{OUT: rebuilding the map}

[[MAP_REFRESH]] turns the stored world into the live one. The
packed map opens with four pointer words (offsets relative to
[[MAP_PACKED]] itself); each continent is a run-length stream of
\emph{count$\times$8 $+$ terrain-code} bytes, zero-terminated,
expanding to exactly 4096 cells. On top of the fresh terrain go,
in order: every object record tagged for this continent, any
transports owed to the player from the last town visit
([[COURT_CELLS]]), and --- once the endgame flag [[TM_REVEAL]] is
raised and while fewer than 7 exist --- a time machine, tucked
into forest near the continent's northwest corner.

<<out map refresh>>=
        ORG $94C1
MAP_REFRESH
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Decompress continent PLR_CONT to MAP_BASE and restock.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Expand the continent's RLE stream to MAP_BASE, derive
        ;   PLR_CONT_BITS, paint this continent's records, respawn
        ;   COURT_CELLS craft, recount the census, and scatter a
        ;   time machine when TM_REVEAL is up.
        LDA PLR_CONT
        AND #$03                        ; the world is a 2x2
        STA PLR_CONT                    ;   torus of continents
        ASL
        TAX
        LDA MAP_PACKED,X                ; src := MAP_PACKED +
        ADC #$00                        ;   table[continent]
        STA ZP_RLE_SRC
        LDA MAP_PACKED+1,X
        ADC #$A9
        STA ZP_RLE_SRC+1
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_RLE_DST
        LDA #$60                        ; dst := MAP_BASE
        STA ZP_RLE_DST+1
        LDY #$00
.unit   LDA (ZP_RLE_SRC),Y              ; run byte: length*8 +
        BEQ .objects                    ;   terrain code; 0 ends
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        TAX
        LDA (ZP_RLE_SRC),Y
        AND #$07
        ASL                             ; cell byte = code * 2
.fill   STA (ZP_RLE_DST),Y
        INC ZP_RLE_DST
        BNE .nc
        INC ZP_RLE_DST+1
.nc     DEX
        BNE .fill
        INC ZP_RLE_SRC
        BNE .unit
        INC ZP_RLE_SRC+1
        BNE .unit                       ; (always)
.objects
        LDA PLR_CONT
        LSR                             ; continent index into
        ROR                             ;   the top two bits
        ROR
        STA PLR_CONT_BITS
        LDX OBJ_COUNT                   ; paint this continent's
        BEQ .court                      ;   records onto the map
.rec    DEX
        LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$C0
        CMP PLR_CONT_BITS
        BNE .skip
        JSR OBJ_PTR_X
        LDA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y             ; remember the terrain,
        STA OBJ_UNDER,X
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X                  ;   show the object
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
.skip   TXA
        BNE .rec
.court  STX ZP_TRIES                    ; 0: 256 tries below
        LDX ZP_PLR_X                    ; respawn craft parked
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y                    ;   around the courtyard
        DEY
        LDA COURT_CELLS
        JSR OBJ_PLACE_T                 ; north
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        DEX
        LDA COURT_CELLS+1
        JSR OBJ_PLACE_T                 ; west
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        INX
        LDA COURT_CELLS+2
        JSR OBJ_PLACE_T                 ; east
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        INY
        LDA COURT_CELLS+3
        JSR OBJ_PLACE_T                 ; south
        LDX #$03
        LDA #$FF
.clr    STA COURT_CELLS,X               ; consume the slots
        DEX
        BPL .clr
        JSR CENSUS
        LDA TM_REVEAL                   ; scatter a time machine?
        BEQ .done
        LDA OWNED_TRANSPORT+10          ; at most 7 in the world
        CMP #$07
        BCS .done
.seek   JSR RND                         ; in the northwest
        AND #$07                        ;   corner, in forest
        TAY
        INY
        JSR RND
        AND #$07
        TAX
        INX
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        CMP #$02
        BEQ .drop
        DEC ZP_TRIES
        BNE .seek
.drop   LDA #$0F                        ; park a time machine
        JSR OBJ_SPAWN
.done   LDA #$00
        STA TM_REVEAL
        RTS
@ %def MAP_REFRESH

\section{OUT: the transport census}

[[OWNED_TRANSPORT]] is never edited piecemeal: whenever it
matters (entering a town, after a map rebuild), the census
recounts slots 1--10 from the ground truth --- the transport
being ridden plus every parked record. [[PARK_CNT]] tallies the
world-wide fleet for [[CELL_PROBE]]'s 53-craft cap.

<<out transport census>>=
        ORG $9597
CENSUS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Recount OWNED_TRANSPORT 1-10 and PARK_CNT.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Clear slots 1-10, count the ridden transport, then scan
        ;   the records for parked-craft bytes ($12-$1E) and bump
        ;   the matching slot (15 counts as a time machine).
        LDA #$00
        LDX #$0A
.clr    STA OWNED_TRANSPORT,X
        DEX
        BNE .clr
        STA PARK_CNT
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        BEQ .world
        INC OWNED_TRANSPORT,X
        INC PARK_CNT
.world  LDY OBJ_COUNT
        BEQ .done
.scan   DEY
        LDA OBJ_TILE,Y
        CMP #$20
        BCS .next
        CMP #$12                        ; parked craft: cell
        BCC .next                       ;   bytes $12-$1E
        INC PARK_CNT
        LSR                             ; byte -> cell code;
        CMP #$0F                        ;   code 15 counts as a
        BCC .own                        ;   time machine
        LDA #$12
.own    TAX
        INC OWNED_TRANSPORT-8,X         ; code - 8 = transport
.next   TYA
        BNE .scan
.done   RTS
@ %def CENSUS

\section{OUT: monster spawning}

Each world turn may add one monster. The gate is tuned to the
player: a flat 12-in-256 floor, plus a roll that passes more
often at higher experience. The \emph{kind} is drawn against a
difficulty bar of $2\times\mathrm{rnd}(1..7)$: a candidate among
the fifteen outdoor monsters is accepted only if its
[[MON_TIER]] is under the bar, so balrons stay rare while orcs
are everywhere. Sea monsters (relative 0--3) spawn on water,
the forest dwellers (4--8) in woods, the rest on grass ---
always outside the visible viewport, never on the player.

Hit points scale with both the player and the kind:
$(\mathrm{exp}_{hi} + \mathrm{TIER\_HP}[\mathrm{tier}])/2$,
randomized above 4. [[TIER_HP]] is just $10\times$tier --- the
same scale the kill code pays out as experience.

<<out monster spawner>>=
        ORG $95D2
MON_SPAWN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Maybe spawn one monster, off-screen, on its terrain.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Gate the turn's spawn roll, draw a kind under the
        ;   difficulty bar, pick a matching-terrain cell outside
        ;   the viewport box, OBJ_SPAWN it, and give it
        ;   (exp-high + TIER_HP[tier])/2 hit points.
        LDA OBJ_COUNT
        CMP #$41                        ; keep slots for craft
        BCS .rts
        JSR RND
        CMP #$0C                        ; 12/256: spawn for sure
        BCC .roll
        AND #$3F                        ; otherwise gate on the
        CMP PLR_EXP+1                   ;   player's progress
        BCS .rts
        AND #$07
        BNE .rts
.roll   STA ZP_RLE_SRC                  ; (scratch) retry count
        JSR RND
        AND #$07
        BEQ .rts
        ASL
        STA ZP_TGT_X                    ; difficulty bar: 2..14
.pick   LDA #$0F                        ; draw one of the 15
        JSR RND_MOD                     ;   outdoor monsters
        TAX
        LDA MON_TIER+6,X
        CMP ZP_TGT_X                    ; tier under the bar?
        BCC .kind
        DEC ZP_RLE_SRC
        BNE .pick
.rts    RTS
.kind   LDY #$00                        ; terrain class by kind:
        CPX #$04                        ;   0-3 sea monsters,
        BCC .cls                        ;   4-8 forest dwellers,
        LDY #$02                        ;   9-14 grass roamers
        CPX #$09
        BCC .cls
        LDY #$01
.cls    STY ZP_TGT_Y                    ; the required terrain
        STX CUR_MON                     ; (relative index, only
        TXA                             ;   while spawning)
        ASL
        ADC #$10
        STA ZP_TGT_X                    ; cell code = 16 + 2*kind
        LDA ZP_PLR_X                    ; exclusion box around
        SBC #$09                        ;   the visible viewport
        BPL .l
        LDA #$00
.l      STA ZP_BOX_L
        LDA ZP_PLR_X
        ADC #$09
        STA ZP_BOX_R
        LDA ZP_PLR_Y
        SBC #$04
        BPL .t
        LDA #$00
.t      STA ZP_BOX_T
        LDA ZP_PLR_Y
        ADC #$04
        STA ZP_BOX_B
.find   JSR CELL_RAND                   ; a random cell of the
        CMP ZP_TGT_Y                    ;   right terrain,
        BNE .find
        CPX ZP_BOX_L                    ;   outside the box
        BCC .ok
        CPX ZP_BOX_R
        BCS .ok
        CPY ZP_BOX_T
        BCC .ok
        CPY ZP_BOX_B
        BCS .ok
        DEC ZP_TILE_TMP                 ; (free-running counter)
        BNE .find
        RTS
.ok     LDA ZP_TGT_X
        JSR OBJ_SPAWN
        BCS .full
        LDA PLR_EXP+1                   ; hit points scale with
        LDX CUR_MON                     ;   progress and tier
        LDY MON_TIER+6,X
        ADC TIER_HP,Y
        LSR
        CMP #$05
        BCC .weak
        PHA                             ; randomize: (hp +
        JSR RND_MOD                     ;   rnd(hp) + 1) / 2
        PLA
        SEC
        ADC ZP_CHANCE
        ROR
.weak   LDX OBJ_COUNT
        STA OBJ_HP-1,X
.full   RTS
TIER_HP ; the 0-100 scale: TIER_HP[tier] = 10 * tier
        HEX 00 0a 14 1e 28 32 3c 46
        HEX 50 5a 64
@ %def MON_SPAWN TIER_HP

\section{OUT: the monsters' turn}

[[MON_CLEAR]] sweeps every monster record away --- crossing a
continent edge, respawning, or initializing a fresh world ---
while parked transports persist. Its parting [[DEX]] writes
[[$FF]] into [[OBJ_HP]]+0, the sentinel [[OUT_ENTRY]] checks to
know the world has been set up at least once.

<<out monster despawn>>=
        ORG $9691
MON_CLEAR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Remove all monster records; prime the world sentinel.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   OBJ_REMOVE every record with a monster cell byte;
        ;   leave craft. CUR_MON <- 0 and the sentinel <- $FF.
        LDX OBJ_COUNT
        BEQ .prime
.scan   DEX
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        CMP #$20
        BCC .skip
        CMP #$5A
        BCS .skip
        JSR OBJ_REMOVE
.skip   TXA
        BNE .scan
.prime  STX CUR_MON                     ; CUR_MON <- #$00
        DEX
        STX OBJ_HP                      ; sentinel <- #$FF
        RTS
@ %def MON_CLEAR

After every player action --- including idle and failed ones ---
each monster record gets to act.

<<out monsters turn>>=
        ORG $96B0
TURN_PASS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The world's half of the turn: maybe spawn, then every
        ; monster acts once.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   MON_SPAWN once, then MON_ACT for each record holding
        ;   a monster, last to first.
        JSR MON_SPAWN
        LDX OBJ_COUNT
        BEQ MON_DONE
.each   DEX
        STX ZP_REC
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        CMP #$20
        BCC .skip
        CMP #$5A
        BCS .skip
        JSR MON_ACT
.skip   LDX ZP_REC
        BNE .each
MON_DONE
        RTS
@ %def TURN_PASS MON_DONE

A monster on the move first rolls against [[AGGR_TBL]], indexed
by the \emph{player's} transport: on foot the world is calm (any
roll acts... downward --- entry 0 means monsters always move),
while a frigate or aircar stirs up almost everything. Then it
classifies itself (sea / land / forest-capable), takes one step
toward the player --- preferring a random axis so pursuit
wiggles --- and walks only on terrain its class allows: sea
monsters stay wet, land monsters may slip into forest, the two
forest natives roam both.

<<out monster roam>>=
        ORG $96CE
AGGR_TBL ; act threshold (rnd >= this) per player transport
        HEX 00 80 aa 00 80 c0 e6 e6
        HEX e6 e6 e6
MON_ROAM
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Step monster ZP_REC toward the player, terrain rules
        ; permitting.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Roll AGGR_TBL[player transport] to act at all; classify
        ;   the monster from its cell byte; build the signed step
        ;   toward the player; try a random-first axis order; legal
        ;   cells move the record and repaint both map cells.
        JSR RND
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        CMP AGGR_TBL,X
        BCC MON_DONE                    ; sitting this one out
        LDX ZP_REC
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        LDY #$00                        ; class 0: sea
        CMP #$30
        BCC .cls
        LDY #$01                        ; class 1: land
        CMP #$38                        ; the archer and the
        BEQ .wood                       ;   trent: forest too
        CMP #$40
        BNE .cls
.wood   LDY #$02
.cls    STY MON_TCLASS
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_STEP_X
        STA ZP_STEP_Y
        LDA OBJ_X,X
        STA ZP_TGT_X
        LDA ZP_PLR_X                    ; x step: toward the
        BMI .xless                      ;   player (negative =
        CMP ZP_TGT_X                    ;   margin = far west)
        BCC .xless
        BEQ .ystep
        INC ZP_STEP_X
        BCS .ystep                      ; (always)
.xless  DEC ZP_STEP_X
.ystep  LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$3F
        STA ZP_TGT_Y
        LDA ZP_PLR_Y
        BMI .yless
        CMP ZP_TGT_Y
        BCC .yless
        BEQ .go
        INC ZP_STEP_Y
        BCS .go                         ; (always)
.yless  DEC ZP_STEP_Y
.go     JSR RND                         ; prefer a random axis,
        BMI .ymajor                     ;   so pursuit wiggles
        JSR .tryx
        BCC .commit
.ymajor LDX ZP_TGT_X
        LDA ZP_TGT_Y
        CLC
        ADC ZP_STEP_Y
        TAY
        JSR .check
        BCC .commit
        JSR .tryx
        BCS .stay
.commit JSR OBJ_PTR                     ; lift the tile, put the
        LDA OBJ_UNDER,X                 ;   terrain back ...
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
        LDA ZP_DST_X
        STA OBJ_X,X
        LDA ZP_DST_Y
        ORA PLR_CONT_BITS
        STA OBJ_YC,X
        JSR OBJ_PTR_X                   ; ... and set it down on
        LDA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y             ;   the new cell
        STA OBJ_UNDER,X
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
.stay   RTS
.tryx   LDY ZP_TGT_Y
        LDA ZP_TGT_X
        CLC
        ADC ZP_STEP_X
        TAX
.check  CPX #$40                        ; a legal cell?
        BCS .no
        CPY #$40
        BCS .no
        CPX ZP_PLR_X                    ; not onto the player
        BNE .cell
        CPY ZP_PLR_Y
        BEQ .no
.cell   JSR CELL_TYPE
        CMP #$08                        ; (8+: an object; never
        BCS .terr                       ;   matches a class)
        CMP #$04
        BCC .terr
        LDA #$01                        ; places read as grass
.terr   CMP MON_TCLASS
        BEQ .yes
        CMP #$02                        ; land monsters may
        BNE .no                         ;   slip into forest
        LDA MON_TCLASS
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .yes
.no     SEC
        RTS
.yes    STX ZP_DST_X
        STY ZP_DST_Y
        CLC
        RTS
@ %def AGGR_TBL MON_ROAM

\section{OUT: monster attacks}

A sign/magnitude helper for the pursuit geometry; the negation
runs through a self-modified subtrahend.

<<out sign helper>>=
        ORG $97AC
SIGN_ABS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A (signed) -> Y := sign (FF/0/1), A := |A|.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Positive: Y=1. Zero: Y=0. Negative: Y=$FF and A is
        ;   negated through the self-modified SBC immediate.
        TAY
        BEQ .zero
        BMI .neg
        LDY #$01
        RTS
.neg    LDY #$FF
        STA SGN_NEG                     ; negate: 0 - A through
        LDA #$00                        ;   the immediate below
        SEC
SGN_NEG = *+1
        SBC #$00
.zero   RTS
@ %def SIGN_ABS SGN_NEG

The decision tree for one monster: orthogonally adjacent ---
strike. At distance 2--3 (along an axis or the diagonal), the
four \emph{shooters} --- dragon turtle, pirate ship, hidden
archer, wandering warlock --- trace a line of sight toward the
player (mountains block it) and strike from afar. Anything else
walks. The distance lives in Y; note the [[DC.B $C9]] trick
hiding a [[TAY]] inside a dummy [[CMP]] for the
\emph{dy${}={}$0} case.

<<out monster action>>=
        ORG $97BF
MON_ACT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Monster ZP_REC acts: melee, ranged attack, or walk.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Distance along the pursuit axis in Y (diagonals count
        ;   +1). Under 2: melee. 2-3: the four shooter kinds trace
        ;   line-of-sight (mountains block) and strike from afar.
        ;   Anything else: MON_ROAM.
        LDX ZP_REC
        LDA OBJ_X,X
        STA ZP_TGT_X
        SEC
        SBC ZP_PLR_X
        JSR SIGN_ABS
        STY ZP_SGN_X
        STA ZP_STEP_X                   ; here: |dx|
        LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$3F
        STA ZP_TGT_Y
        SEC
        SBC ZP_PLR_Y
        JSR SIGN_ABS
        STY ZP_SGN_Y
        STA ZP_STEP_Y                   ; here: |dy|
        TAY
        LDA ZP_STEP_X
        BEQ .dist                       ; dx=0: distance = |dy|
        CPY #$00
        BEQ .takex                      ; dy=0: distance = |dx|
        CPY ZP_STEP_X
        BNE .walk                       ; off-diagonal: walk
        INY                             ; diagonal: |dy| + 1
        DC.B $C9                        ; CMP #imm hides the TAY
.takex  TAY
.dist   CPY #$02
        BCC MON_MELEE                   ; adjacent: strike
        CPY #$04
        BCS .walk                       ; too far: walk
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X                  ; 2-3 away: the four
        CMP #$28                        ;   shooters fire --
        BEQ .ranged                     ;   dragon turtle,
        CMP #$2C                        ;   pirate ship,
        BEQ .ranged                     ;   hidden archer,
        CMP #$38                        ;   wandering warlock
        BEQ .ranged
        CMP #$58
        BEQ .ranged
.walk   JMP MON_ROAM
.ranged LDA #$02
        STA RANGE_CNT
.los    SEC                             ; trace the shot toward
        LDA ZP_TGT_X                    ;   the player
        SBC ZP_SGN_X
        TAX
        SEC
        LDA ZP_TGT_Y
        SBC ZP_SGN_Y
        TAY
        STX ZP_TGT_X
        STY ZP_TGT_Y
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        CMP #$03                        ; mountains block it
        BEQ .walk
        DEC RANGE_CNT
        BNE .los
        ; in range: falls into MON_MELEE
@ %def MON_ACT

The strike itself: the player's tile flashes to the splash
glyph for a frame, defense is $8\times\mathrm{armour} +
\mathrm{stamina}/2$ subtracted from a flat 200-in-256 chance,
and damage is $\mathrm{rnd}(2\times\mathrm{tier})+1$ off the
16-bit hit points, floor zero (the main loop notices the death).
The attacker also locks itself in as [[TGT_REC]], so a bare
\emph{Attack} answers back.

<<out monster melee>>=
        ORG $9830
MON_MELEE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Monster ZP_REC strikes the player.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Announce, rattle, flash the player tile; hit when
        ;   rnd < 200 - 8*armour - stamina/2; subtract
        ;   rnd(2*tier) + 1 from the 16-bit hits, floored at 0.
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COND
        LDX ZP_REC
        STX TGT_REC                     ; auto-target the attacker
        LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        LSR                             ; cell byte -> monster
        LSR
        ADC #$FE
        STA CUR_MON
        TAX
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " attacks! ",$00
        LDA #$04                        ; the menace rattle
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDA #$5E                        ; flash the player tile
        STA PLAYER_TILE
        JSR DRAW_MAP
        LDA PLR_STA                     ; defense: stamina/2
        LSR                             ;   + 8 * armour
        STA ZP_CHANCE
        LDA READY_ARMOUR
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ADC ZP_CHANCE
        STA ZP_CHANCE
        SEC
        LDA #$C8                        ; hit if rnd < 200 -
        SBC ZP_CHANCE                   ;   defense
        STA ZP_CHANCE
        JSR RND
        CMP ZP_CHANCE
        BCC .hit
        LDA MON_CH
        CMP #$17
        BCC .miss
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.miss   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Missed!",$00
        JMP .redraw
.hit    LDA MON_CH
        CMP #$1A
        BCC .say
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.say    JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Hit! ",$00
        LDA MON_CH
        CMP #$15
        BCC .num
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.num    LDX CUR_MON                     ; damage: rnd(2*tier)+1
        LDA MON_TIER,X
        ASL
        JSR RND_MOD
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        STA DMG_AMT
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " damage",$00
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; hits -= damage,
        SEC                             ;   floor at zero
        SBC DMG_AMT
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC #$00
        BPL .ok
        LDA #$00
        STA PLR_HITS
.ok     STA PLR_HITS+1
        JSR STATS_VALUES
        LDA #$02
        JSR SFX_PLAY
.redraw JSR PLAYER_TILE_SET
        JMP DRAW_MAP
@ %def MON_MELEE

\section{OUT: the object records}

The address arithmetic for a record's map cell:

<<out object cell pointer>>=
        ORG $98F8
OBJ_PTR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; ZP_CELL_PTR/Y := record ZP_REC's map cell.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Shift the masked row into row * 64, add the MAP_BASE
        ;   page, load Y with the record's column.
        LDX ZP_REC
OBJ_PTR_X
        ; (entry: record X's cell)
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR
        LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$3F
        LSR                             ; row * 64 + MAP_BASE
        ROR ZP_CELL_PTR
        LSR
        ROR ZP_CELL_PTR
        ADC #$60
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        LDY OBJ_X,X
        RTS
@ %def OBJ_PTR OBJ_PTR_X

Creation and removal keep the five arrays dense and the map in
sync: a spawn saves the terrain it covers and paints itself; a
removal restores the terrain (only if its continent is the live
one) and shifts everything above it down one slot.

<<out object records>>=
        ORG $9911
OBJ_PLACE_T
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Spawn A at (X, Y) only if A is a parked-craft code.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   A dispatcher fan-in: craft codes (8-15) fall through
        ;   to OBJ_SPAWN; everything else returns.
        CMP #$08
        BCC .rts2                       ; (the shared RTS below)
        CMP #$10
        BCC OBJ_SPAWN
        RTS
SPAWN_AT_WATER
        ; Spawn code A at a random water cell. (This and the
        ; land variant are unreferenced in OUT -- shared source
        ; with the sibling overlays; verify there.)
        PHA
        JSR FIND_WATER
        PLA
        JMP OBJ_SPAWN
SPAWN_AT_LAND
        ; Spawn code A at a random open land cell.
        PHA
        JSR FIND_LAND
        PLA
OBJ_SPAWN
        ; Create an object record: cell code A at (X, Y).
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   C clear -- spawned (terrain saved, map painted)
        ;   C set -- off-map or the record table is full
        CPX #$40
        BCS .rts2
        CPY #$40
        BCS .rts2
        STX ZP_TMP
        LDX OBJ_COUNT
        CPX #$50
        BCS .rts2
        ASL                             ; cell byte = code * 2
        STA OBJ_TILE,X
        PHA
        TYA
        ORA PLR_CONT_BITS
        STA OBJ_YC,X
        LDA ZP_TMP
        STA OBJ_X,X
        JSR OBJ_PTR_X
        LDA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y             ; remember the terrain,
        STA OBJ_UNDER,X
        PLA
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y             ;   paint the object
        INC OBJ_COUNT
        CLC
.rts2   RTS
OBJ_FIND_REMOVE
        ; Remove the record at the player's position.
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        CPX #$40
        BCS .rts2
        CPY #$40
        BCS .rts2
        STX ZP_TMP
        TYA
        ORA PLR_CONT_BITS
        LDX OBJ_COUNT
.scan   DEX
        BMI .rts2
        CMP OBJ_YC,X
        BNE .scan
        LDY OBJ_X,X
        CPY ZP_TMP
        BNE .scan
        ; found: falls into OBJ_REMOVE
OBJ_REMOVE
        ; Remove record X: restore its terrain (if on the live
        ; continent) and close the gap in all five arrays.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A -- the removed cell byte; X preserved
        LDA OBJ_YC,X
        AND #$C0
        CMP PLR_CONT_BITS
        BNE .gone
        JSR OBJ_PTR_X
        LDA OBJ_UNDER,X
        STA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
.gone   LDA OBJ_TILE,X
        STA ZP_TILE_TMP
        STX ZP_TMP
        DEC OBJ_COUNT
        BNE .test
        RTS
.shift  LDA OBJ_X+1,X                   ; compact all five
        STA OBJ_X,X                     ;   arrays down a slot
        LDA OBJ_YC+1,X
        STA OBJ_YC,X
        LDA OBJ_TILE+1,X
        STA OBJ_TILE,X
        LDA OBJ_UNDER+1,X
        STA OBJ_UNDER,X
        LDA OBJ_HP+1,X
        STA OBJ_HP,X
        INX
.test   CPX OBJ_COUNT
        BCC .shift
        LDX ZP_TMP
        LDA ZP_TILE_TMP
        RTS
@ %def OBJ_PLACE_T SPAWN_AT_WATER SPAWN_AT_LAND OBJ_SPAWN
@ %def OBJ_FIND_REMOVE OBJ_REMOVE

\section{OUT: reading the map}

The cell reader is the one place that knows the map's address
math (row${}\times{}$64, the 10-cell margin reading as water).
The row coordinate survives in Y by way of a self-modified
[[LDY]] immediate.

<<out cell helpers>>=
        ORG $99C5
CELL_RAND
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := cell code of a random cell; X/Y say where.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Two random draws masked to 0-63, then CELL_TYPE.
        JSR RND
        AND #$3F
        TAY
        JSR RND
        AND #$3F
        TAX
CELL_TYPE
        ; A := cell code at (X, Y); off-map reads as water (0).
        ; Leaves ZP_CELL_PTR on the row, X/Y untouched.
        LDA #$00
        CPY #$40
        BCS .half
        CPX #$40
        BCS .half
        TYA
        STA CT_ROW                      ; park the row in the
        LSR                             ;   LDY immediate below
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        LDA #$00
        ROR
        LSR ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        ROR
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR
        LDA ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        ADC #$60                        ; + MAP_BASE
        STA ZP_CELL_PTR+1
        TXA
        TAY
        LDA (ZP_CELL_PTR),Y
CT_ROW = *+1
        LDY #$00                        ; (self-modified)
.half   LSR                             ; cell byte -> code
        RTS
CELL_HERE
        ; A := cell code under the player; also in UNDER_TYPE.
        LDX ZP_PLR_X
        LDY ZP_PLR_Y
        JSR CELL_TYPE
        STA UNDER_TYPE
        RTS
@ %def CELL_RAND CELL_TYPE CT_ROW CELL_HERE

\section{OUT: the Inform command}

\emph{Inform and search} names the ground underfoot: the sea,
the woods, ``the lands of'' with the continent's name, or ---
standing on a place --- the place itself, found by matching the
player's coordinates against [[PLACE_X]]/[[PLACE_Y]]. The match
also sets [[PLR_PLACE]], which is how \emph{Enter} knows which
landmark responds. Standing on one's own parked craft, the
terrain \emph{under} the record is reported instead.

<<out cmd inform>>=
        ORG $9A03
CMD_INFORM
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Say where the player stands; track PLR_PLACE.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Map the cell underfoot to a report: terrain strings
        ;   (with the continent name for open land), or match the
        ;   position against PLACE_X/PLACE_Y and print the place
        ;   name, updating PLR_PLACE.
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COND
        JSR CELL_HERE
        CMP #$03                        ; mountains read as
        BEQ .lands                      ;   "the lands of"
        CMP #$08
        BCC .basic
        LDA ZP_PLR_Y                    ; on an object: report
        ORA PLR_CONT_BITS               ;   the terrain under
        LDX OBJ_COUNT                   ;   its record
.scan   CMP OBJ_YC-1,X
        BNE .next
        LDY OBJ_X-1,X
        CPY ZP_PLR_X
        BNE .next
        LDA OBJ_UNDER-1,X
        LSR
        BPL .basic                      ; (always)
.next   DEX
        BNE .scan
.lands  LDA #$01
.basic  STA UNDER_TYPE
        CMP #$04
        BCS .place
        TAX                             ; 0-2: sea/lands/woods
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_YOUARE
        LDX UNDER_TYPE
        DEX
        BNE .rts
        LDX PLR_CONT                    ; "the lands of" takes
        JSR STR_NTH                     ;   the continent name
        DC.W STR_CONTINENTS
.rts    RTS
.place  CMP #$06
        BNE .lookup
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "the city of ",$00
.lookup LDA PLR_CONT_BITS               ; find the place at
        ORA ZP_PLR_Y                    ;   this position
        LDX #$53
.match  CMP PLACE_Y,X
        BNE .miss
        LDY PLACE_X,X
        CPY ZP_PLR_X
        BEQ .found
.miss   DEX
        BPL .match
        STX PLR_PLACE                   ; PLR_PLACE <- #$FF
        RTS
.found  STX PLR_PLACE
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_PLACES
        RTS
@ %def CMD_INFORM

\section{OUT: transport names and the player tile}

<<out transport names>>=
        ORG $9A83
TRANSPORT_NAME
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Print the current transport's name.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   STR_NTH into the transport name table.
        LDX READY_TRANSPORT
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_TRANSPORT
        RTS
PLAYER_TILE_SET
        ; Player tile := (transport | 8) * 2; 7+ rides (and
        ; shows as) a time machine; out-of-range means on foot.
        LDA READY_TRANSPORT
        CMP #$0B
        BCC .seven
        LDA #$00                        ; sanity fallback
        STA READY_TRANSPORT
.seven  CMP #$07
        BCC .tile
        LDA #$0A                        ; READY_TRANSPORT <- #$0A
        STA READY_TRANSPORT
        LDA #$07
.tile   ORA #$08
        ASL
        STA PLAYER_TILE
        RTS
@ %def TRANSPORT_NAME PLAYER_TILE_SET

