\section{CAS}

\texttt{CAS} --- the castle overlay, 5524 bytes at [[$8956]]. It is
the near-twin of \texttt{TWN}: the player enters it on stepping onto
any of the game's eight castles, and it shares \texttt{TWN}'s loader,
its live-map buffer, its dispatch skeleton, and --- byte for byte ---
its map/NPC drawing and distance helpers. What a castle adds over a
town is \emph{the King}: an audience that hands out quests, a
storeroom the King's permission opens, the four quest gems with their
prophecies, and --- in the one castle that holds her --- the Princess
whose rescue reveals the time machine. \texttt{CAS} is where the
game's win condition is set in motion.

Because so much of \texttt{CAS} is the same engine as \texttt{TWN},
this section concentrates on what differs: the castle-index
arithmetic at entry, the King-audience command ([[CMD_TRANSACT]]),
the quest assignment and completion machinery, the gem prophecies,
the storeroom (Get and Unlock), and the Princess rescue folded into
the move handler. The shared drawing and helper routines at the file
tail are presented for completeness but described briefly, with
references back to their \texttt{TWN} cousins.

\subsection{The castle index}

A castle, like a town, is one record in \texttt{TCMAPS} --- the same
$38\times18$ grid of [[MAPCHARS]] glyph codes followed by the
80-byte NPC table. \texttt{TWN} turned [[PLR_PLACE]] into a record
number by reducing it mod~$\$15$ and subtracting $\$0D$ (towns are
places $13$--$20$ of each continent's local numbering). \texttt{CAS}
reduces mod~$\$15$ the same way, but the castles are the
\emph{low} local places, so it folds the continent in instead:
the index is $(\text{place} \bmod \$15) + 2c$ where $c$ is the
continent [[PLR_CONT]], then an even/odd parity flip is applied
($\$06 - \text{idx}$ when the index is even). That value,
[[CASTLE_IDX]], indexes the [[TCMAPS]]
directory (at [[TCMAPS_DIR]], the start of the ten-word pointer
table) and also keys the per-castle quest state: [[QUEST_FLAGS]]
slot, princess name, and the [[CASTLE_COL]] display column.

\subsection{The live map buffer}

As in \texttt{TWN}, the chosen record is copied to a 768-byte buffer
at [[CASTLE_MAP]]; its first $684$ bytes are the displayed cells and
the rest holds the five parallel 16-entry NPC arrays [[NPC_TYPE]],
[[NPC_X]], [[NPC_Y]], and the 16-bit [[NPC_HP]]. The eighteen
[[MAP_ROW_LO]]/[[MAP_ROW_HI]] pointers give each row's start within
the buffer. The castle's NPC types run a little higher than a
town's: the King is type [[$6C]], the storeroom doors are [[$6A]]
and [[$6B]], and the Princess and guards take the low slots.

\subsection{Engine and state symbols}

\texttt{CAS} reuses the resident-library and \texttt{MI.U1} engine
API and the shared player-state block exactly as \texttt{TWN} does.
Only the castle-specific zero-page scratch, the \texttt{CAS} BSS
state band, and the in-file tables are new.

