\texttt{CAS} enters at [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]], exactly where every overlay
is loaded. It zeroes the King-reject and storeroom-permission flags,
clears [[DIR_STR_PTR]] (so movement keys echo the default
North/South/East/West names), computes [[CASTLE_IDX]], then
[[BLOAD]]s \texttt{TCMAPS} and \texttt{MAPCHARS}, copies the chosen
record into [[CASTLE_MAP]] through the self-modified pointer
[[MAP_SRC]], draws the map ([[MAP_DRAW]]), and falls into the
dispatch loop. As in \texttt{TWN}, [[KEY_IDLE]] polls the keyboard
with a timeout so the castle animates ([[CASTLE_TICK]]) between
keystrokes.

<<cas entry>>=
        ORG $8956
OVERLAY_ENTRY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Overlay entry: load the castle map and run the castle loop.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Set the player position from zero page, clear the King-reject
        ;   and storeroom flags, fold PLR_PLACE and PLR_CONT into CASTLE_IDX
        ;   (with a parity flip), BLOAD TCMAPS and MAPCHARS, copy the chosen
        ;   3-page record into CASTLE_MAP, draw it, then fall into the
        ;   dispatch loop.  KEY_IDLE polls with a timeout so the castle
        ;   animates (CASTLE_TICK) while waiting for a key.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$09
        STA ZP_Y
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_X
        STA KING_REJECT
        STA DIR_STR_PTR+1
        STA KEY_KIND
        STA STORE_PERMIT
        LDA PLR_PLACE
.L896D
        CMP #$15
        BCC .L8975
        SBC #$15
        BNE .L896D
.L8975
        PHA
        CLC
        ADC PLR_CONT
        ADC PLR_CONT
        STA CASTLE_IDX
        AND #$01
        BNE .L898D
        LDA #$06
        SEC
        SBC CASTLE_IDX
        STA CASTLE_IDX
.L898D
        JSR MLIB_SET_PREFIX
        DC.B "TCMAPS",0
        LDA #$40
        LDY #$00
        JSR FILE_LOAD_AT
        JSR DISK_PROMPT
        BCS .L898D
.L89A3
        JSR MLIB_SET_PREFIX
        DC.B "MAPCHARS",0
        LDA #$B0
        LDY #$00
        JSR FILE_LOAD_AT
        JSR DISK_PROMPT
        BCS .L89A3
        PLA
        ASL
        TAX
        LDA TCMAPS_DIR,X
        STA MAP_SRC
        LDA TCMAPS_DIR+1,X
        STA MAP_SRC+1
        LDY #$03
        LDX #$00
.L89CE
MAP_SRC = *+1
        LDA STALE_FFFF,X
MAP_DST = *+1
        STA CASTLE_MAP,X
        DEX
        BNE .L89CE
        INC MAP_SRC+1
        INC MAP_DST+1
        DEY
        BNE .L89CE
        JSR MAP_DRAW
        JMP CAS_DISPATCH
MAP_PROMPT
        JSR TEXT_SCROLL
        LDA #$0E
        JSR CHAR_OUT
CAS_LOOP
        JSR STATS_VALUES
        JSR KEY_IDLE
        BNE CAS_GETCMD
        LDA #$00
        STA IDLE_MSG
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        LDA #$20
        JSR FONT_DRAW
        JSR CASTLE_TICK
        LDY #$01
        LDA #$10
        JSR TICK_SND
        JSR SFX_DRAIN
        LDA IDLE_MSG
        BNE MAP_PROMPT
        LDA #$17
        STA MON_CV
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JMP CAS_LOOP
CAS_GETCMD
        JSR GET_COMMAND
        BCS MAP_PROMPT
        RTS
KEY_IDLE
        LDX #$80
.L8A27
        JSR KEY_GET
        BNE .L8A2F
        DEX
        BNE .L8A27
.L8A2F
        TAX
        RTS
CAS_DISPATCH
        LDA PLR_HITS
        ORA PLR_HITS+1
        BEQ CAS_DEATH
        LDA PLR_FOOD
        ORA PLR_FOOD+1
        BNE .L8A47
CAS_DEATH
        JSR TEXT_SCROLL
        JMP RESPAWN
.L8A47
        JSR MAP_PROMPT
        LDA CMD_TBL,X
        STA DISP_OP
        LDA CMD_TBL+1,X
        STA DISP_OP+1
DISP_OP = *+1
        JSR STALE_FFFF
        JSR CASTLE_TICK
        JMP CAS_DISPATCH
@

\subsection{The command table and dispatch}

\texttt{CAS} dispatches commands exactly as \texttt{TWN} does: the
engine [[GET_COMMAND]] returns $X = 2\times\text{index}$, and the
loop self-modifies the operand of a [[JSR]] from the word table
[[CMD_TBL]]. Most of the 26 commands are no-ops in a castle and
point at the engine [[QUERY_MARK]]; the castle-mode handlers are the
rest. Accelerator and Noise reuse the engine sound toggles
[[SOUND_TOGGLE]] and [[SFX_TOGGLE]]. The four movement entries point
into [[CMD_MOVE]] (its three trailing entry points have no separate
label).

<<cas command table>>=
        ORG $8A5F
CMD_TBL
        HEX 938a9a8aa18aa88a
        HEX 4c8c4588568c0784
        HEX 3c8e5b8e07840784
        HEX d4900784fa9a0784
        HEX 5b88078434915991
        HEX 6f917c925e970784
        HEX 0784fe97
@

\subsection{Movement and the Princess rescue}

The four arrow commands enter [[CMD_MOVE]] with the step delta in
$(X,Y)$. An ordinary step runs [[MOVE_STEP]]: it probes the target
cell with [[CELL_PROBE]], prints ``Blocked'' on a wall, and otherwise
erases the player glyph, writes it at the new cell, and ticks a turn.

The interesting case is the wall at column~0. One castle on each
continent holds a captive Princess on her dais behind that wall;
stepping west into it with the King's NPC slot nearby triggers
[[PRINCESS_RESCUE]]. The rescue greets her by name from
[[STR_PRINCESS]] (indexed by [[CASTLE_IDX]]), awards 500 hit points,
pence, and experience through the capped adder [[ADD_CAP]], and ---
if the player is a \emph{space ace} (at least [[$14]] captured
vessels in [[PLR_VESSELS]] and enough experience) --- announces the
time machine ``far to the northwest'' and sets [[TM_REVEAL]], the
flag \texttt{OUT} reads to scatter time machines onto the overworld.
The rescue then exits to the overworld via [[EXIT_TO_OUT]].

<<cas move>>=
        ORG $8A93
CMD_MOVE
