\subsection{The item picker}

[[DROP_PICK]] is the generic popup picker, byte-for-byte the same
idiom \texttt{TWN} uses: five inline argument bytes (an item count and
two pointers) are pulled off the return address, the owned items are
listed lettered in a window, and the chosen index comes back in $X$.
[[PICK_CNT]] and [[PICK_TBL]] are self-modified bytes in the code
stream past the routine's [[RTS]].

<<cas drop pick>>=
        ORG $900D
DROP_PICK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Popup item picker (5 inline argument bytes).
        ;
        ; Inputs (inline after the JSR):
        ;   count byte, owned-array pointer (word), name-table pointer (word)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   List every owned item lettered a), b), ... in a popup window,
        ;   wait for a letter, and return its index in X (or $FF/"none").
        ;   PICK_CNT and PICK_TBL are self-modified storage cells.
        ;
        ; Outputs:  X = chosen item index, or $FF if none
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        PLA
        STA MSG_PTR
        PLA
        STA MSG_PTR+1
        JSR MSG_GETC
        STA PICK_CNT
        JSR MSG_GETC
        STA ZP_PICK_PTR
        JSR MSG_GETC
        STA ZP_PICK_PTR+1
        JSR MSG_GETC
        STA PICK_TBL
        JSR MSG_GETC
        STA PICK_TBL+1
        LDA MSG_PTR+1
        PHA
        LDA MSG_PTR
        PHA
        LDY PICK_CNT
        LDX #$00
.L903E
        LDA (ZP_PICK_PTR),Y
        BEQ .L9043
        INX
.L9043
        DEY
        BNE .L903E
        STX ZP_PICK_CNT
        CPX #$00
        BNE .L9051
        PLA
        PLA
        JMP .L90BC
.L9051
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        JSR WIN_VIEW
        LDX #$0F
        LDY #$00
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $0E," Drop ",$18,0
        JSR CLR_WINDOW
        SEC
        LDA #$14
        SBC ZP_PICK_CNT
        LSR
        STA MON_CV
        LDA #$61
        STA PICK_ALPHA
        LDY #$00
        BEQ .L908F
.L907B
        TYA
        PHA
        LDA #$0D
        STA MON_CH
PICK_ALPHA = *+3
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "a) ",0
        PLA
        JSR .L90CA
        TAY
        INC MON_CV
.L908F
        CPY PICK_CNT
        BCS .L909E
        INC PICK_ALPHA
        INY
        LDA (ZP_PICK_PTR),Y
        BNE .L907B
        BEQ .L908F
.L909E
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JSR KEY_WAIT
        PHA
        JSR POPUP_CLOSE
        SEC
        PLA
        SBC #$41
        BEQ .L90BC
        BMI .L90BC
        CMP PICK_CNT
        BCC .L90B7
        BNE .L90BC
.L90B7
        TAY
        LDA (ZP_PICK_PTR),Y
        BNE .L90C9
.L90BC
        LDY #$FF
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "none",0
        TYA
        TAX
        RTS
.L90C9
        TYA
.L90CA
        TAX
        PHA
PICK_TBL = *+3
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W ZP_X
        PLA
        RTS
PICK_CNT
        ASL
@

\subsection{Get from the storeroom}

The castle storerooms are the white gem's prize. [[CMD_GET]] requires
the player to face a storeroom cell --- armour ([[$65]]), food
([[$67]]), or a weapon ([[$69]]) --- and to hold the King's
permission in [[STORE_PERMIT]]. That counter starts at nine when the
white gem is awarded (the King's ``nine items, but only nine'' from
[[HINT_CONT3]]); each Get decrements it and drops into
[[STOREROOM_FIND]] (in the steal section, which both commands share)
to hand over a random item of the faced kind.

<<cas get>>=
        ORG $90D4
CMD_GET
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Get: take an item from a storeroom (needs the King's permission).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The player must face a storeroom cell ($65 armour / $67 food /
        ;   $69 weapon) and hold permission (STORE_PERMIT > 0, granted with
        ;   the white gem).  Each Get decrements STORE_PERMIT and falls into
        ;   STOREROOM_FIND to award a random item of that kind.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX ZP_X
        LDY ZP_Y
        JSR CELL_AT
        CMP #$65
        BEQ .L90FB
        CMP #$67
        BEQ .L90FB
        CMP #$69
        BEQ .L90FB
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Nothing here",0
        JMP QUERY_MARK
.L90FB
        STA ZP_T0
        LDA STORE_PERMIT
        BNE .L912E
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou hast not the king's~permission!",0
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.L912E
        DEC STORE_PERMIT
        JMP STOREROOM_FIND
@

\subsection{Quit and Ready}

Saving is an overworld-only action, so [[CMD_QUIT]] just prints
``only allowed outdoors''. [[CMD_READY]] accepts S, W, or A and
forwards to the engine [[READY_CMD]] (the shared spell/weapon/armour
selector), then redraws.

<<cas quit ready>>=
        ORG $9134
CMD_QUIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Quit (refused) and Ready (forward to the engine).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   CMD_QUIT prints "only allowed outdoors" and beeps -- the game
        ;   can only be saved on the overworld.  CMD_READY reads S/W/A and
        ;   forwards to the engine READY_CMD, then redraws.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$12
        STA MON_CH
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " is~only allowed outdoors!",0
        JMP BEEP_HUH
CMD_READY
        JSR KEY_IDLE
        CMP #$53
        BEQ .L9169
        CMP #$57
        BEQ .L9169
        CMP #$41
        BEQ .L9169
        RTS
.L9169
        JSR READY_CMD
        JMP MAP_DRAW
@

\subsection{Steal and the storeroom award}

[[CMD_STEAL]] is the unsanctioned path into the same storerooms. It
rolls to avoid detection --- the thief class ([[PLR_CLASS]]~$=4$)
always succeeds, others risk it; getting caught prints ``Thou wert
caught'' and sets [[KING_REJECT]]. On success it falls into the
award code [[STOREROOM_FIND]], which both Steal and Get reach: it
reads the faced cell kind and gives a random piece of armour (cell
[[$65]]), a number of bags of food (cell [[$67]]), or a random
weapon (cell [[$69]]), updating the matching owned-item array.

