\section{DNG: the dungeon overlay}

\texttt{DNG} is the first-person dungeon: ten levels of wireframe
corridors under every dungeon entrance on the world map. It is the
largest overlay (10051 bytes at [[$8956]]--[[$B098]]) and the most
self-contained --- it never touches the object-record arrays or the
outdoor map. Its world is an 11$\times$11 byte grid per level,
living in BSS just past the end of the file at [[DNG_MAP]], and
that grid is \emph{procedurally generated}: nothing about any
dungeon's layout is stored on disk.

The headline discovery, confirmed in this chapter: every dungeon in
the game is generated, deterministically, from four bytes of player
state --- the place index, the outdoor position, the continent, and
the level number ([[DNG_GEN]]). Walk into the same dungeon twice
and the same maze comes back; walk one level down and a different
but equally reproducible maze is laid out. Only the perishables
differ from visit to visit: which lattice cells hold a chest versus
a coffin is rolled on the real random generator, and monsters are
placed fresh each time.

A map cell is one byte: low nibble = \emph{feature}, high nibble =
\emph{monster slot}. The features:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{cll}
code & feature & notes \\
\hline
0 & open floor & \\
1 & wall & blocks walking and sight \\
2 & hidden trapdoor & walk on it and fall (see [[MOVE_FWD]]) \\
3 & hidden secret door & drawn as wall; Inform reveals it \\
4 & door & passable; drawn with a frame \\
5 & chest & opened by Unlock (trapped!) \\
6 & coffin & opened by Open (occupied!) \\
7 & ladder down & K-limb descends \\
8 & ladder up & K-limb ascends \\
9 & revealed trapdoor & K-limb descends \\
\texttt{\$C} & force field & blocks everything; Create/Destroy \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Movement treats codes 1 and 3 and everything at or above
[[$A]] as solid; everything else can be walked onto ---
including chests, coffins and ladders, which is why the Open,
Unlock and K-limb commands act on the cell the player is
\emph{standing on}.

Monsters use a completely different scheme from the outdoors: there
are exactly \emph{five} of them per level, in fixed slots 1--5 of
six parallel arrays ([[MON_FREE]], [[MON_X]], [[MON_Y]],
[[MON_HP]]). The slot number doubles as the monster's \emph{kind}:
name index = slot $+$ [[MON_BASE]], where [[LEVEL_INIT]] sets
[[MON_BASE]] $= 5\lfloor(\mathrm{level}-1)/2\rfloor + 20$. So
levels 1--2 field monsters 21--25 of [[STR_MONSTERS]] (ranger,
skeleton, thief, giant rat, bat), levels 3--4 field 26--30 (giant
spider, viper, orc, cyclops, gelatinous cube), and so on down to
the level 9--10 roster of 41--45 (invisible seeker, mind whipper,
zorn, daemon, balron). A cell's high nibble holds the slot of the
monster standing there; slot 0 means none.

Four of the kinds are special-cased by name index in the code: the
\emph{thief} of levels 1--2 ($21+2$, index 23) steals weapons, the
\emph{gelatinous cube} (30) destroys armour and is transparent to
the renderer, the \emph{gremlin} (37) halves the food supply, the
\emph{invisible seeker} (41) is never drawn at all, and the
\emph{mind whipper} (42) attacks the intelligence stat. The
slot-5 monster of each pair of levels (gelatinous cube, carrion
creeper, lich, balron) is quest material --- see [[MON_KILLED]].

The overlay shares the engine API and player state with
\texttt{OUT}; everything external is declared here, exactly as in
the previous chapter.

