\section{DNG: arrival}

The engine's [[GAME_LOAD]] jumps to the overlay's first byte with
nothing set up. Entry points the command echo's movement names at
[[DIR_STRS]] --- in the dungeon the four arrows read
\emph{Forward}, \emph{Turn around}, \emph{Turn right}, \emph{Turn
left} --- then plants the player at cell $(1,1)$ of level 1,
facing $+y$ (south), generates the level, and turns
double-buffering on for the wireframe animation.

There is no saved dungeon position: leaving and re-entering a
dungeon always starts back at $(1,1)$, level 1, and dying inside
one respawns outdoors. The position pair [[DNG_X]]/[[DNG_Y]] and
facing vector [[DNG_DX]]/[[DNG_DY]] live in the overlay's own BSS
([[DNG_X]] is a column 0--10, [[DNG_Y]] a row; the facing vector
is one of $(0,\pm1)$/$(\pm1,0)$).

<<dng entry>>=
        ORG $8956
DNG_ENTRY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Overlay entry: dungeon mode from square one.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Movement names := DIR_STRS, position := (1,1) facing
        ;   south, level := 1, generate the level, enable double
        ;   buffering, enter the main loop.
        LDA #<DIR_STRS                  ; arrows echo as Forward /
        STA DIR_STR_PTR                 ;   Turn around / right /
        LDA #>DIR_STRS                  ;   left
        STA DIR_STR_PTR+1
        LDA #$01
        STA DNG_X                       ; DNG_X <- #$01
        STA DNG_Y                       ; DNG_Y <- #$01
        STA DNG_DY                      ; facing south (+y)
        STA DNG_LEVEL                   ; topmost level
        LDA #$00
        STA DNG_DX
        JSR DNG_GEN                     ; lay out level 1
        LDA #$60                        ; double-buffering on
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL
        STA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        JSR PAGE_COPY
        JMP DNG_MAIN
@ %def DNG_ENTRY

\section{DNG: the first-person view}

[[DNG_DRAW]] is the whole reason a dungeon \emph{looks} like a
dungeon. It redraws the screen for the current position and
facing: a status line (level number and compass direction), then
the wireframe corridor itself --- the receding tunnel of walls,
doors and openings the player sees down the passage.

The corridor is drawn by \emph{ray marching}. Starting at the
player's own cell, [[DNG_DRAW]] steps one cell at a time in the
facing direction, and at each step --- a \emph{depth slice},
counted in [[VIEW_DEPTH]] --- it inspects three cells: the one
straight ahead ([[VIEW_CELL]]) and the two beside it
([[VIEW_L]] and [[VIEW_R]], the left and right walls of the
passage at that depth). It draws whatever those three cells call
for, then marches one cell deeper, until it hits something solid
(a wall, a closed-off door, or a blocking monster), at which
point [[VIEW_BLOCKED]] stops the walk and the page is flipped.

Everything is drawn in true perspective. The screen
coordinates for each depth slice come from a pool of pre-computed
tables, [[DNG_GEOM]], indexed by [[VIEW_DEPTH]]: as the depth
grows the box edges converge toward the screen centre
([[$7F]],[[$7F]]) at the vanishing point, so a corridor four cells
long telescopes correctly. The dozen line-drawing primitives
that follow ([[DRAW_BOX]] through [[DRAW_LADDER_DN]]) each read
the slice's edge coordinates out of that pool and connect them
with [[LINE_AGAIN]]; the perspective is entirely in the tables,
not the code.

The status line first: clear the viewport, print ``Level $N$'',
and translate the facing vector [[DNG_DY]]/[[DNG_DX]] into a
compass word. (The control bytes [[$18]] and [[$06]] in the text
are layout codes consumed by [[MSG_AT]].)

<<dng view>>=
        ORG $8982
DNG_DRAW
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Redraw the first-person view for the current cell/facing.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Print the "Level N" status line and a compass word, then
        ;   ray-march down the passage: at each depth slice inspect
        ;   the cell ahead and the two beside it, draw the wireframe
        ;   walls/doors/openings/features/monsters in perspective,
        ;   and stop at the first solid cell. Flips to the visible
        ;   page on exit.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   VIEW_DEPTH, VIEW_BLOCKED, VIEW_CELL, VIEW_L/R(_PREV),
        ;   WORK_X/Y, MON_SLOT, the line-draw workspace $06-$09
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        JSR VIEW_CLEAR                  ; blank the viewport
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        JSR WIN_FULL
        LDY #$00                        ; status line: "Level N"
        LDX #$0E
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $0E," Level ",$00
        LDX #$00
        STX NUM_PAD                     ; no leading zero
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        LDA #$20                        ; space
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDA #$18                        ; layout: move to compass col
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDA #$04
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDY #$13                        ; --- compass word ---
        LDX #$0F
        LDA DNG_DY
        BEQ .ew                         ; facing along X -> East/West
        BMI .north
        JSR MSG_AT                      ; dy>0 -> South
        DC.B $0E," South ",$18,$00
        JMP .compass_done
.north  JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $0E," North ",$18,$00
        JMP .compass_done
.ew     LDA DNG_DX
        BPL .east
        JSR MSG_AT                      ; dx<0 -> West
        DC.B $0E," West ",$18,$06,$00
        JMP .compass_done
.east   JSR MSG_AT                      ; dx>0 -> East
        DC.B $0E," East ",$18,$06,$00
.compass_done
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        ; --- ray-march setup ---
        LDA #$00
        STA VIEW_DEPTH                  ; start at the player's cell
        STA VIEW_BLOCKED
        LDX DNG_X                       ; is the player standing on a
        LDY DNG_Y                       ;   door/secret/field?
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .on_door
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .on_door
        CMP #$04
        BNE .march
.on_door
        ; Standing in a doorway with a wall immediately ahead: draw
        ; just the closing "X" of the doorframe and stop.
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$01
        BNE .march
        STA VIEW_BLOCKED
        LDA #$00                        ; the two diagonals of the
        STA $06                         ;   blocked doorway
        LDA #$FF
        STA $08
        LDA #$7F
        STA $07
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA #$00
        STA $08
        STA $07
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        JMP .check_blocked
.march
        ; --- the depth-slice loop ---
        ; Carry the previous slice's side features forward (the box
        ; primitive joins this slice's walls to the last one), set
        ; the wall colour, then walk WORK_X/Y out to this depth.
DNG_MARCH
        LDA VIEW_L
        STA VIEW_L_PREV
        LDA VIEW_R
        STA VIEW_R_PREV
        LDA #$07                        ; white
        JSR COLOR_SET
        LDA DNG_X                       ; WORK_X = DNG_X + depth*dx
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
.stepx  BEQ .gotx
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DX
        DEX
        JMP .stepx
.gotx   STA WORK_X
        LDA DNG_Y                       ; WORK_Y = DNG_Y + depth*dy
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
.stepy  BEQ .goty
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY
        DEX
        JMP .stepy
.goty   STA WORK_Y
        TAY
        LDX WORK_X
        JSR CELL_READ                   ; cell ahead: high nibble is
        PHA                             ;   the monster slot, low
        LSR                             ;   nibble the feature
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        STA MON_SLOT
        PLA
        AND #$0F
        STA VIEW_CELL
        ; The two side cells: rotate the facing vector +/-90 degrees.
        ; Left = (dx+dy, dy-dx) from WORK; Right = (dx-dy, dy+dx).
        LDA WORK_X
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY                      ; left cell
        TAX
        LDA WORK_Y
        SEC
        SBC DNG_DX
        TAY
        JSR CELL_FEAT
        STA VIEW_L
        LDA WORK_X
        SEC
        SBC DNG_DY                      ; right cell
        TAX
        LDA WORK_Y
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DX
        TAY
        JSR CELL_FEAT
        STA VIEW_R
        ; --- draw the cell ahead ---
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; door/secret/field -> front
        CMP #$01                        ;   face
        BEQ .ahead_face
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .ahead_face
        CMP #$04
        BNE .ahead_open
.ahead_face
        JSR DRAW_AHEAD_WALL
.ahead_open
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; wall/secret stops the walk
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .blocked
        CMP #$03
        BNE .not_solid
        LDA VIEW_DEPTH                  ; ...but a secret door at the
        BEQ .open_ahead                 ;   player's own cell does not
.blocked
        LDA #$01
        STA VIEW_BLOCKED
        JMP .after_ahead2
.not_solid
        LDA VIEW_CELL
        CMP #$04                        ; a door: draw the opening
        BNE .ahead_extras               ;   through it
.open_ahead
        JSR DRAW_AHEAD_OPEN
        LDA VIEW_DEPTH
        BNE .blocked
        JMP .after_ahead2
.ahead_extras
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; coffin marker
        CMP #$06
        BNE .chk_field
        JSR DRAW_COFFIN
        JSR WIN_TEXT
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$17
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $7E,"Coffin",$00
.chk_field
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; force field
        CMP #$0C
        BNE .after_ahead
        JSR DRAW_FIELD
.after_ahead
        ; --- draw the side walls ---
        LDA VIEW_L                      ; left wall (wall/secret/door)
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .lwall
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .lwall
        CMP #$04
        BNE .rwall
.lwall  JSR DRAW_WALL_L
.rwall  LDA VIEW_R                      ; right wall
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .rw
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .rw
        CMP #$04
        BNE .ldoor
.rw     JSR DRAW_WALL_R
.ldoor  LDA VIEW_L                      ; left door frame
        CMP #$04
        BNE .rdoor
        LDA VIEW_DEPTH
        BEQ .ldoor0
        JSR DRAW_DOOR_L
        JMP .rdoor
.ldoor0 JSR DRAW_DOOR_L
.rdoor  LDA VIEW_R                      ; right door frame
        CMP #$04
        BNE .lopen
        LDA VIEW_DEPTH
        BEQ .rdoor0
        JSR DRAW_DOOR_R
        JMP .lopen
.rdoor0 JSR DRAW_DOOR_R
.lopen  LDA VIEW_L                      ; left side-passage opening
        CMP #$01                        ;   (anything not wall-like)
        BEQ .ropen
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .ropen
        CMP #$04
        BEQ .ropen
        JSR DRAW_OPEN_L
.ropen  LDA VIEW_R
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .feats
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .feats
        CMP #$04
        BEQ .feats
        JSR DRAW_OPEN_R
.feats  ; --- ladders, then the chest/monster in the cell ahead ---
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; ladder down (7) or revealed
        CMP #$07                        ;   trapdoor (9)
        BEQ .ladder_dn
        CMP #$09
        BNE .ladder_up
.ladder_dn
        JSR DRAW_LADDER_DN
.ladder_up
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; ladder up (8)
        CMP #$08
        BNE .ladder_shaft
        JSR DRAW_LADDER_UP
.ladder_shaft
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; the shaft uprights for both
        CMP #$07
        BEQ .shaft
        CMP #$08
        BNE .chest
.shaft  JSR DRAW_LADDER_SHAFT
.chest  LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; a chest, but only if no live
        CMP #$05                        ;   monster occupies the cell
        BNE .after_ahead2
        LDA MON_SLOT
        BEQ .chest_yes
        CLC
        ADC MON_BASE                    ; slot $1E/$29 = chest/coffin
        CMP #$1E                        ;   placeholders, not monsters
        BEQ .chest_yes
        CMP #$29
        BEQ .chest_yes
        JMP .after_ahead2
.chest_yes
        JSR WIN_TEXT
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$17
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $7E,"Chest",$00
        LDA #$0B                        ; chest shape, drawn one slice
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH                  ;   nearer so it sits in front
        INC VIEW_DEPTH
        JSR SHAPE_DRAW
        DEC VIEW_DEPTH
.after_ahead2
        ; --- the monster occupying the cell ahead ---
        LDA MON_SLOT
        BEQ .check_blocked
        CLC
        ADC MON_BASE                    ; resolve to a STR_MONSTERS id
        PHA
        JSR WIN_TEXT                    ; name it on the message line
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$17
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B $7E,$00
        PLA
        PHA
        TAX
        CMP #$29                        ; $29 = coffin placeholder
        BEQ .name_done
        CMP #$20                        ; $20 = chest placeholder
        BNE .name_mon
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Chest",$00
        JMP .name_done
.name_mon
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
.name_done
        PLA
        CMP #$29                        ; placeholders draw no shape
        BEQ .check_blocked
        SEC
        SBC #$15                        ; monster id -> shape index
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        DEX
        JSR SHAPE_DRAW
        LDA MON_SLOT                    ; a real monster ahead blocks
        CLC                             ;   the view (sentinels $1E/
        ADC MON_BASE                    ;   $20 do not)
        CMP #$1E
        BEQ .check_blocked
        CMP #$20
        BEQ .check_blocked
        LDA #$01
        STA VIEW_BLOCKED
.check_blocked
        LDA VIEW_BLOCKED
        BEQ .deeper
.flip   JMP PAGE_FLIP
.deeper INC VIEW_DEPTH                  ; march one cell further
        JMP DNG_MARCH
@ %def DNG_DRAW DNG_MARCH

\section{DNG: the level generator}

[[DNG_GEN]] is why no dungeon map is stored anywhere on the disk.
The maze is rebuilt from scratch on every entry and every level
change, from a two-byte seed derived purely from \emph{where the
dungeon is} and \emph{how deep the player is}:

\begin{quote}
[[SEED_A]] $=$ 8$\cdot$[[PLR_PLACE]] $\oplus$ [[PLR_OUT_X]]
$\oplus$ level \\
[[SEED_B]] $=$ 4$\cdot$[[PLR_OUT_Y]] $\oplus$ [[PLR_CONT]]
\end{quote}

[[SEED_RND]] steps this state with a Fibonacci-style swap-add
([[SEED_A]]$'$ $=$ [[SEED_A]] $+$ [[SEED_B]] $+ 9$, [[SEED_B]]$'$
$=$ [[SEED_A]]), so the sequence --- and therefore the maze --- is
a pure function of the seed. Every structural decision draws from
it. Only two things are \emph{not} deterministic: whether each
container cell is a chest or a coffin (rolled on the library
[[RND]]), and everything about monsters.

Generation is five passes over the fresh [[DNG_TEMPLATE]] copy
(border walls and a lattice of pillars at even-even cells):

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Edges.} Every lattice edge --- the cells at
(even column, odd row) and (odd column, even row) --- gets a
feature from [[EDGE_PICK]]: open, secret door, or door, weighted
6/6/8 on a d20.
\item \textbf{Walls and fields.} $2\cdot\mathrm{level}+1$ times:
one of the 16 positions listed in [[WALL_POS_A]]/[[WALL_POS_B]]
(transposed on odd levels) becomes a wall, or --- with probability
96/256 --- a force field.
\item \textbf{Containers.} level times: a random lattice edge
becomes a chest or a coffin (the one non-seeded roll).
\item \textbf{Fixed cells.} $(1,2)$ is cleared so the entrance
never faces an immediate wall; ladders go in at $(7,3)$ and
$(3,7)$ --- down/up on even levels, up/down on odd. Level 10
deletes its down ladder (there is no level 11), and level 1
overrides $(1,1)$ with the up ladder the player arrived on and
deletes the other up ladder at $(7,3)$.
\item \textbf{Monsters.} Falls into [[LEVEL_INIT]] below: pick
the level's five kinds and release three of them.
\end{enumerate}

<<dng generator>>=
        ORG $8C5D
DNG_GEN SUBROUTINE
        ; Generate the current dungeon level into DNG_MAP.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   PLR_PLACE/PLR_OUT_X/PLR_OUT_Y/PLR_CONT -- the dungeon's
        ;     world identity (seed material)
        ;   DNG_LEVEL -- depth, 1-10
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Seed the deterministic generator, copy the 11x11
        ;   template, strew edge features, walls, fields and
        ;   containers, place the ladders, then fall into
        ;   LEVEL_INIT for the monsters.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   DNG_MAP, SEED_A/SEED_B, WORK_X/WORK_Y, ACC
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA PLR_PLACE                   ; seed A: place*8 ^ outdoor
        ASL                             ;   x ^ level
        ASL
        ASL
        EOR PLR_OUT_X
        EOR DNG_LEVEL
        STA SEED_A
        LDA PLR_OUT_Y                   ; seed B: outdoor y*4
        ASL                             ;   ^ continent
        ASL
        EOR PLR_CONT
        STA SEED_B
        LDY #$78                        ; copy the 121-byte
.copy   LDA DNG_TEMPLATE,Y              ;   template over the map
        STA DNG_MAP,Y
        DEY
        BPL .copy
        ; --- pass 1: a feature on every lattice edge ---
        LDA #$08                        ; even columns 8,6,4,2
        STA WORK_X
.col    LDA #$09                        ; odd rows 9,7,5,3,1
        STA WORK_Y
.row    JSR EDGE_PICK                   ; (even,odd) edge
        LDX WORK_X
        LDY WORK_Y
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JSR EDGE_PICK                   ; (odd,even) edge,
        LDX WORK_Y                      ;   transposed
        LDY WORK_X
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        DEC WORK_Y
        DEC WORK_Y
        BPL .row
        DEC WORK_X
        DEC WORK_X
        BNE .col
        ; --- pass 2: 2*level+1 walls / force fields ---
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        ASL
        STA ACC                         ; pass counter
.wall   JSR SEED_RND
        LDX #$01                        ; wall...
        CMP #$A0
        BCC .solid
        LDX #$0C                        ; ...or field, 96/256
.solid  STX ACC_HI                      ; feature to place
        JSR SEED_RND
        AND #$0F                        ; one of 16 listed spots,
        TAX
        LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ;   transposed on odd
        AND #$01                        ;   levels
        BEQ .even
        LDA WALL_POS_B,X
        TAY
        LDA WALL_POS_A,X
        TAX
        JMP .place
.even   LDA WALL_POS_A,X
        TAY
        LDA WALL_POS_B,X
        TAX
.place  LDA ACC_HI
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        DEC ACC
        BPL .wall
        ; --- pass 3: level chests/coffins on random edges ---
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        STA ACC
.chest  JSR SEED_RND                    ; even coordinate 2..8
        AND #$03
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        ASL
        STA WORK_X
        JSR SEED_RND                    ; second even coordinate
        AND #$03
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        ASL
        STA WORK_Y
        JSR SEED_RND                    ; nudge one axis odd:
        BMI .odd_x                      ;   lands on an edge
        INC WORK_Y
        JMP .roll
.odd_x  INC WORK_X
.roll   JSR RND                         ; the one true-random
        AND #$01                        ;   call: chest (5) or
        CLC                             ;   coffin (6)
        ADC #$05
        LDX WORK_X
        LDY WORK_Y
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        DEC ACC
        BNE .chest
        ; --- pass 4: the fixed cells ---
        LDA #$00                        ; the cell ahead of the
        LDX #$01                        ;   entrance is always
        LDY #$02                        ;   clear
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; ladders at (7,3)/(3,7):
        AND #$01                        ;   down/up on even
        BNE .odd_lvl                    ;   levels, up/down on odd
        LDA #$07
        LDX #$07
        LDY #$03
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA #$08
        LDX #$03
        LDY #$07
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JMP .fixups
.odd_lvl
        LDA #$08
        LDX #$07
        LDY #$03
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA #$07
        LDX #$03
        LDY #$07
        JSR CELL_WRITE
.fixups LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; level 10: no level below,
        CMP #$0A                        ;   delete the down ladder
        BNE .not10
        LDA #$00
        LDX #$07
        LDY #$03
        JSR CELL_WRITE
.not10  LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; level 1: the entry ladder
        CMP #$01                        ;   at (1,1) is the only
        BNE .done                       ;   way up
        LDA #$08
        LDX #$01
        LDY #$01
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA #$00
        LDX #$07
        LDY #$03
        JSR CELL_WRITE
.done   JMP LEVEL_INIT
@ %def DNG_GEN

\section{DNG: the main loop}

The turn loop has the same skeleton as \texttt{OUT} --- prompt,
poll, dispatch through a table by patching a \texttt{JSR} --- with
two dungeon twists. First, the whole view is redrawn at the top of
every turn ([[DNG_DRAW]]), because almost any command can change
what the corridor looks like. Second, the idle turn is cheaper
than outdoors: food burns at $0.01$ and the clock at $0.10$ per
idle beat (versus $0.05$/$0.50$), so standing around in a dungeon
is slow-motion --- but the monsters still get their turn
([[MON_TURNS]]) every beat.

[[DNG_PROMPT]] also watches [[FIGHT_FLAG]]: [[MON_STRIKE]] sets it
whenever a monster reaches the player, and the prompt reprints
itself after combat messages so the command echo never lands
mid-sentence.

<<dng prompt>>=
        ORG $8D99
DNG_PROMPT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Prompt and poll until a key arrives, idling the world.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Print the prompt glyph at (0,23). Poll briefly; on
        ;   timeout charge an idle tick (food 0.01, time 0.10),
        ;   run the monsters, and repeat -- reprinting the prompt
        ;   if combat messages scrolled it. On a key, GET_COMMAND;
        ;   "Huh?" re-prompts at no cost.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   X = 2 * command index (from GET_COMMAND)
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   FIGHT_FLAG, MON_CV
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$17
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B "|",$0E,$00                ; the prompt glyph
.idle   JSR STATS_VALUES
        JSR KEY_SHORT
        BNE .key
        LDA #$00
        STA FIGHT_FLAG
        JSR CURSOR_COL1                 ; wipe the cursor box
        LDA #$20
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        JSR MON_TURNS                   ; the monsters move
        LDY #$01                        ; idle: food -= 0.01,
        LDA #$10                        ;   time += 0.10
        JSR TICK_SND
        JSR SFX_DRAIN
        LDA FIGHT_FLAG                  ; combat messages? full
        BNE DNG_PROMPT                  ;   re-prompt
        LDA #$17                        ; otherwise just go back
        STA MON_CV                      ;   to the prompt row
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JMP .idle
.key    JSR GET_COMMAND
        BCS DNG_PROMPT                  ; "Huh?" costs nothing
        RTS
KEY_SHORT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Poll the keyboard up to 128 times.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   A short busy-poll so the idle loop ticks the world
        ;   at a steady rate between keys.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A = X = key, or 0 if the poll timed out (Z set)
        LDX #$80
.poll   JSR KEY_GET
        BNE .got
        DEX
        BNE .poll
.got    TAX
        RTS
@ %def DNG_PROMPT KEY_SHORT

The loop proper: redraw, check for death by wounds or starvation,
take a command, dispatch it, then give the monsters their turn.
The dispatch is the overlay idiom seen in \texttt{OUT}: the
handler's address is patched into the operand of a \texttt{JSR}
(stale [[$FFFF]] on disk). Unsupported commands point at the
engine's [[QUERY_MARK]]; \emph{ctrl-A} and \emph{Noise} go
straight to the engine toggles.

<<dng main loop>>=
        ORG $8DE6
DNG_MAIN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The turn loop. No return.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   DNG_DRAW, die at zero hits or food, prompt for a
        ;   command, dispatch via DNG_CMDS through the patched
        ;   JSR, run the monsters, repeat.
        JSR DNG_DRAW
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; dead?
        ORA PLR_HITS+1
        BNE .alive
.dead   JMP DNG_DEATH
.alive  LDA PLR_FOOD                    ; starved?
        ORA PLR_FOOD+1
        BEQ .dead
        JSR DNG_PROMPT
        LDA DNG_CMDS,X                  ; patch the JSR below with
        STA DNG_VEC                ;   the handler's address
        LDA DNG_CMDS+1,X
        STA DNG_VEC+1
DNG_VEC = *+1
        JSR STALE_FFFF                  ; (self-modified)
        JSR MON_TURNS
        JMP DNG_MAIN
DNG_CMDS
        DC.W MOVE_FWD                   ;  0 up      Forward
        DC.W TURN_BACK                  ;  1 down    Turn around
        DC.W TURN_RIGHT                 ;  2 right
        DC.W TURN_LEFT                  ;  3 left
        DC.W PASS_CMD                   ;  4 space   Pass
        DC.W SOUND_TOGGLE               ;  5 ctrl-A
        DC.W ATTACK_CMD                 ;  6 Attack
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ;  7 Board
        DC.W CAST_CMD                   ;  8 Cast
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ;  9 Drop
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 10 Enter
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 11 Fire
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 12 Get
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 13 HyperJump
        DC.W INFORM_CMD                 ; 14 Inform & search
        DC.W KLIMB_CMD                  ; 15 K-limb
        DC.W SFX_TOGGLE                 ; 16 Noise
        DC.W OPEN_CMD                   ; 17 Open
        DC.W QUIT_CMD                   ; 18 Quit (refused here)
        DC.W READY_DNG                  ; 19 Ready
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 20 Steal
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 21 Transact
        DC.W UNLOCK_CMD                 ; 22 Unlock
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 23 View
        DC.W QUERY_MARK                 ; 24 X-it
        DC.W ZTATS_CMD                  ; 25 Ztats
@ %def DNG_MAIN DNG_VEC DNG_CMDS

\section{DNG: turning and walking}

Turning is pure vector arithmetic on the facing pair
([[DNG_DX]],\,[[DNG_DY]]): \emph{Turn around} negates both;
\emph{Turn right} maps $(dx,0)\to(0,dx)$ and $(0,dy)\to(-dy,0)$;
\emph{Turn left} is the inverse. No time passes and nothing is
checked --- the redraw at the top of the loop does the rest.

<<dng turning>>=
        ORG $8E48
TURN_BACK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Turn around.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Negate both components of the facing vector.
        LDA DNG_DX
        JSR NEGATE
        STA DNG_DX
        LDA DNG_DY
        JSR NEGATE
        STA DNG_DY
        RTS
TURN_RIGHT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Turn right.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Rotate the facing vector a quarter turn clockwise:
        ;   (dx,0) -> (0,dx), (0,dy) -> (-dy,0).
        LDA DNG_DX
        BEQ .from_y
        STA DNG_DY                      ; (dx,0) -> (0,dx)
        LDA #$00
        STA DNG_DX
        RTS
.from_y LDA DNG_DY                      ; (0,dy) -> (-dy,0)
        JSR NEGATE
        STA DNG_DX
        LDA #$00
        STA DNG_DY
        RTS
TURN_LEFT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Turn left.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Rotate the facing vector a quarter turn
        ;   anticlockwise: (dx,0) -> (0,-dx), (0,dy) -> (dy,0).
        LDA DNG_DX
        BEQ .from_y
        JSR NEGATE                      ; (dx,0) -> (0,-dx)
        STA DNG_DY
        LDA #$00
        STA DNG_DX
        RTS
.from_y LDA DNG_DY                      ; (0,dy) -> (dy,0)
        STA DNG_DX
        LDA #$00
        STA DNG_DY
        RTS
@ %def TURN_BACK TURN_RIGHT TURN_LEFT

\emph{Forward} is the only movement. A wall, a secret door
(undetected, so it blocks like a wall) or anything at code
[[$A]]-plus stops the step; everything else is walked onto. The
sting is feature 2, the hidden trapdoor: stepping on one springs
it --- unless a \emph{rope \& spikes} is in the pack (one is
consumed), the player takes $2\cdot\mathrm{level}$ damage and
falls through to the next level down ([[GO_DOWN]] regenerates the
maze one level deeper).

<<dng forward>>=
        ORG $8E95
MOVE_FWD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Walk one cell in the facing direction.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Walls (1), undetected secret doors (3) and codes >=
        ;   $A block. Otherwise commit the move; a hidden
        ;   trapdoor (2) is sprung: rope & spikes saves (and is
        ;   consumed), else 2*level damage and fall through to
        ;   the level below.
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .blocked
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .blocked
        CMP #$0A
        BCC .step
.blocked
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " - path blocked!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.step   PHA                             ; the feature stepped on
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        STX DNG_X
        STY DNG_Y
        PLA
        CMP #$02                        ; hidden trapdoor?
        BEQ .trap
        RTS
.trap   LDA OWNED_WEAPONS+4             ; rope & spikes in the
        BEQ .fall                       ;   pack? spend one
        DEC OWNED_WEAPONS+4
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thy rope and spikes saved"
        DC.B "~thee from a trap!",$00
        RTS
.fall   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " - a trap!",$00
        LDA #$02                        ; the hurt sound
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; damage = 2 * level
        ASL
        STA ACC
        LDA PLR_HITS
        SEC
        SBC ACC
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC #$00
        STA PLR_HITS+1
        BCC .dead
        ORA PLR_HITS
        BEQ .dead
        JSR STATS_VALUES
        JMP GO_DOWN                     ; fall a level deeper
.dead   JMP DNG_DEATH
@ %def MOVE_FWD

Two fragments follow that nothing in \texttt{DNG} calls: a stray
[[JMP]] to the death exit, and a complete \texttt{TWN}-style
walker that moves by a caller-supplied $(dx,dy)$, prints
\emph{Blocked} on failure, and charges the move tick. They are
more shared ancestral source (the towns move with four arrows on
this very pattern); the bytes are kept byte-perfect here.

<<dng leftover move>>=
        ORG $8F43
DEAD_HOOK
        ; unreferenced in DNG
        JMP DNG_DEATH
MOVE_XY SUBROUTINE
        ; Unreferenced in DNG: arrow-move by (X,Y) offsets, the
        ; town/castle movement idiom.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   X, Y -- signed cell offsets to walk
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Try the cell, commit or print "Blocked" with a thunk,
        ;   then tick and redraw stats. The BCS expects a
        ;   passable/blocked carry from the sibling overlays'
        ;   cell-read; DNG's CELL_READ leaves carry set only for
        ;   row 0 -- more proof this walker is not DNG's code.
        TXA
        CLC
        ADC DNG_X
        STA TGT_X
        TAX
        TYA
        CLC
        ADC DNG_Y
        STA TGT_Y
        TAY
        JSR CELL_READ
        BCS .ok
        LDA #$0E                        ; the bump sound
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Blocked",$00
        JMP .tick
.ok     LDX TGT_X
        STX DNG_X
        LDY TGT_Y
        STY DNG_Y
.tick   LDY #$01                        ; food -= 0.01,
        LDA #$10                        ;   time += 0.10
        JSR TICK_SND
        JSR SFX_DRAIN
        JMP STATS_VALUES
@ %def DEAD_HOOK MOVE_XY

<<dng cmd pass>>=
        ORG $8F8C
PASS_CMD
        ; Pass: stand still for one move tick.
        LDY #$01
        LDA #$10
        JSR TICK_SND
        JMP SFX_DRAIN
@ %def PASS_CMD

\section{DNG: the Attack command}

Attacking is always along the facing line --- there is no
direction prompt in a corridor. The readied weapon contributes
three numbers: its \emph{reach} from [[WPN_RANGE]] (1 for hand
weapons, 5 for the bow, pistol, phazor and friends), its index as
a damage bonus, and an outright veto --- the rope \& spikes (4)
and the three magic implements (amulet 8, wand 9, staff 10) cannot
swing at all; the implements instead multiply the Magic Missile
spell below.

The projectile walk steps cell by cell up to the reach: walls,
doors and force fields stop it dead (\emph{Nothing}); the first
monster nibble takes the shot. To hit, $\mathrm{rnd} <
\mathrm{agility} + 128$; damage is rejection-sampled to
$1\ldots(\mathrm{strength} + 3\cdot\mathrm{weapon})$ and taken off
the slot's 16-bit [[MON_HP]]. A kill announces itself and falls
into the [[MON_KILLED]] machinery.

<<dng cmd attack>>=
        ORG $8F96
ATTACK_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Attack with the readied weapon along the facing line.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Print the weapon; refuse rope & spikes and the three
        ;   magic implements. Walk the shot up to WPN_RANGE cells:
        ;   solid features stop it, a monster takes a to-hit roll
        ;   (rnd < agility + 128) and rejection-sampled damage
        ;   1..(strength + 3*weapon).
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "with ",$00
        LDX READY_WEAPON
        JSR STR_NTH                     ; short weapon name
        DC.W STR_WEAPONS_S
        LDX READY_WEAPON
        CPX #$04                        ; rope & spikes: no
        BEQ .refuse
        CPX #$08                        ; amulet/wand/staff are
        BCC .armed                      ;   spell gear, not arms
        CPX #$0B
        BCS .armed
.refuse JMP QUERY_MARK
ATK_NOTHING
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Nothing",$00
        RTS
.armed  JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~",$00
        LDX READY_WEAPON
        LDA WPN_RANGE,X
        STA RANGE_CNT
        LDA DNG_X                       ; walk from the player...
        STA TGT_X
        LDA DNG_Y
        STA TGT_Y
.walk   LDA TGT_X                       ; ...one facing step at
        CLC                             ;   a time
        ADC DNG_DX
        STA TGT_X
        TAX
        LDA TGT_Y
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY
        STA TGT_Y
        TAY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$01                        ; walls, doors and fields
        BEQ ATK_NOTHING                 ;   soak the shot
        CMP #$03
        BEQ ATK_NOTHING
        CMP #$04
        BEQ ATK_NOTHING
        CMP #$0C
        BEQ ATK_NOTHING
        CMP #$10                        ; a monster!
        BCS .target
        DEC RANGE_CNT
        BNE .walk
        JMP ATK_NOTHING                 ; out of reach
ATK_MISS
        LDA #$06                        ; the swing sound
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Missed!",$00
        RTS
.target LSR                             ; monster slot from the
        LSR                             ;   cell's high nibble
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ACC
        LDX ACC
        LDA #$80                        ; hit if rnd < agi + 128
        CLC
        ADC PLR_AGI
        STA ACC_HI
        JSR RND
        CMP ACC_HI
        BCS ATK_MISS
        LDA #$06
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        LDA PLR_STR                     ; damage limit: strength
        CLC                             ;   + 3 * weapon index
        ADC READY_WEAPON
        ADC READY_WEAPON
        ADC READY_WEAPON
        STA ACC_HI
.roll   JSR RND                         ; rejection-sample
        CMP #$00                        ;   damage 1..limit
        BEQ .roll
        CMP ACC_HI
        BCS .roll
        STA ACC_HI                      ; damage, low
        LDA #$00
        STA TMP_CNT                     ; damage, high
        LDA #$02
        JSR SFX_PLAY
ATK_HIT JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Hit! ",$00
        LDX ACC                         ; MON_HP[slot] -= damage
        LDA MON_HP,X
        SEC
        SBC ACC_HI
        STA MON_HP,X
        LDA MON_HP_HI,X
        SBC TMP_CNT
        STA MON_HP_HI,X
        BCC .killed
        LDA TMP_CNT                     ; survived: report the
        LDX ACC_HI                      ;   number
        LDY #$00
        STY NUM_PAD
        JSR PRINT_NUM16
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " damage",$00
        RTS
.killed LDA ACC                         ; name = slot + the
        CLC                             ;   level's roster base
        ADC MON_BASE
        TAX
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " killed!",$00
        JMP MON_KILLED
@ %def ATTACK_CMD ATK_NOTHING ATK_MISS ATK_HIT

\section{DNG: Cast and the ten spells}

The dungeon is where magic happens --- outdoors only Prayer works,
but here all ten spells of [[STR_SPELLS]] are implemented, each
with its own Latin incantation from [[STR_INCANT]]. The readied
spell is consumed from [[OWNED_SPELLS]] and, unless the player is
class 2 (the cleric), may simply fizzle: failure if $\mathrm{rnd}
\ge \mathrm{intelligence} + 128$.

Spell 0, Prayer, is the wildcard: its stock is never checked (a
[[OWNED_SPELLS]] charge is decremented all the same), it cannot
fizzle, it shouts \emph{``POTENTIS-LAUDIS!''}, and it casts a
uniformly random spell 1--10 in place of a chosen one. The chosen ones dispatch through
[[SPELL_TBL]] by the same patched-\texttt{JMP} idiom as the
command table:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{cllp{5.2cm}}
\# & spell & incantation & effect \\
\hline
1 & Open & APERTUS! & open the coffin underfoot \\
2 & Unlock & PECUNIA! & open the chest underfoot \\
3 & Magic Missile & VASTO! & ranged damage, see below \\
4 & Steal & NUDO! & always fails (town magic) \\
5 & Ladder Down & INFERUS & conjure feature 7 underfoot \\
6 & Ladder Up & ASCENDO & conjure feature 8 underfoot \\
7 & Blink & DUCIS-EDUCO! & teleport within the level \\
8 & Create & STRUXI! & force field in the cell ahead \\
9 & Destroy & DELIO! & remove the field ahead \\
10 & Kill & INTERFICIO! & slay the monster ahead \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

<<dng cmd cast>>=
        ORG $90C5
CAST_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Cast the readied spell.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Spend one OWNED_SPELLS charge (Prayer needs no stock
        ;   check), roll failure (rnd >= int + 128, waived for
        ;   class 2), print the incantation, then dispatch
        ;   through SPELL_TBL via the patched JMP. Prayer picks
        ;   a random spell 1-10 first.
        LDX READY_SPELL
        BEQ .stocked                    ; Prayer is always stocked
        LDA OWNED_SPELLS,X
        BNE .stocked
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou hast used up that spell!",$00
        LDA #$08                        ; the fizzle sound
        JMP SFX_PLAY
.stocked
        DEC OWNED_SPELLS,X
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP                 ; echo the spell name
        DC.W STR_SPELLS
        LDA READY_SPELL
        BEQ .chant                      ; Prayer cannot fail
        LDA PLR_CLASS
        CMP #$02                        ; nor can the cleric
        BEQ .chant
        LDA #$80                        ; fail if rnd >= int + 128
        CLC
        ADC PLR_INT
        STA ACC
        JSR RND
        CMP ACC
        BCC .chant
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " - failed!",$00
        LDA #$08
        JMP SFX_PLAY
.chant  LDA READY_SPELL
        BNE .chosen
.pray   JSR RND                         ; Prayer: a random spell
        AND #$0F                        ;   1..10
        BEQ .pray
        CMP #$0B
        BCS .pray
        PHA
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~",$22,"POTENTIS-LAUDIS!",$22,$00
        JMP .cast
.chosen PHA
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~",$00
        PLA
        PHA
        TAX
        DEX                             ; incantation index 0..9
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_INCANT
.cast   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~",$00
        PLA
        ASL                             ; X = 2 * (spell - 1)
        TAX
        DEX
        DEX
        LDA SPELL_TBL,X                 ; patch the JMP below
        STA SPELL_VEC
        LDA SPELL_TBL+1,X
        STA SPELL_VEC+1
SPELL_VEC = *+1
        JMP STALE_FFFF                  ; (self-modified)
SPELL_TBL
        DC.W SP_OPEN                    ;  1 Open
        DC.W SP_UNLOCK                  ;  2 Unlock
        DC.W SP_MISSILE                 ;  3 Magic Missile
        DC.W SP_STEAL                   ;  4 Steal
        DC.W SP_LADDER_DN               ;  5 Ladder Down
        DC.W SP_LADDER_UP               ;  6 Ladder Up
        DC.W SP_BLINK                   ;  7 Blink
        DC.W SP_CREATE                  ;  8 Create
        DC.W SP_DESTROY                 ;  9 Destroy
        DC.W SP_KILL                    ; 10 Kill
@ %def CAST_CMD SPELL_VEC SPELL_TBL

Open and Unlock act on the cell underfoot, like their command
namesakes but with none of the risks: no coffin monster, no chest
trap --- the spell versions go straight to the payout. The shared
failure exit [[SPELL_FAIL]] serves every spell that finds the
wrong feature in its target cell.

<<dng spell open unlock>>=
        ORG $9195
SP_OPEN SUBROUTINE
        ; Open (APERTUS): open the coffin underfoot, risk-free.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Requires feature 6 underfoot, else SPELL_FAIL; clear
        ;   the cell and pay TREASURE through SP_OPENED.
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$06                        ; standing on a coffin?
        BNE SPELL_FAIL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Coffin",$00
SP_OPENED
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " opened!",$00
        LDA #$00                        ; the container is gone
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA #$0A                        ; the reward sound
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        JMP TREASURE
SPELL_FAIL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Failed!",$00
        LDA #$08
        JMP SFX_PLAY
SP_UNLOCK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Unlock (PECUNIA): open the chest underfoot, trap-free.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Requires feature 5 underfoot, else SPELL_FAIL; joins
        ;   SP_OPENED for the payout.
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$05                        ; standing on a chest?
        BNE SPELL_FAIL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Chest",$00
        JMP SP_OPENED
@ %def SP_OPEN SP_OPENED SPELL_FAIL SP_UNLOCK

Magic Missile is the casters' ranged attack: a 5-cell walk down
the facing line that passes over chests and ladders, stops at
walls and doors (\emph{Failed!}), and strikes the first monster.
Base damage is rejection-sampled to $1\ldots\mathrm{intelligence}$
--- and then the readied weapon multiplies it. This is what the
three unswingable implements are for: the amulet adds half again,
the wand doubles, and the staff (or the triangle) triples. The
result funnels into the weapon attack's [[ATK_HIT]].

<<dng spell missile>>=
        ORG $91F4
SP_MISSILE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Magic Missile (VASTO): strike the first monster within
        ; 5 cells along the facing line.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Walk 5 cells: features 1-4 stop the spell, 0 and 5-9
        ;   are passed over. Damage = rnd(1..int), then * 1.5
        ;   (amulet), * 2 (wand), * 3 (staff/triangle).
        LDA #$05
        STA ACC                         ; reach countdown
        LDA DNG_X
        STA TGT_X
        LDA DNG_Y
        STA TGT_Y
.walk   LDA TGT_X
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DX
        STA TGT_X
        TAX
        LDA TGT_Y
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY
        STA TGT_Y
        TAY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$10                        ; a monster!
        BCC .feature
        LSR                             ; slot from the high
        LSR                             ;   nibble
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ACC
.roll   JSR RND                         ; base damage:
        AND #$7F                        ;   rnd(1..int)
        CMP PLR_INT
        BCS .roll
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        STA ACC_HI                      ; damage accumulator
        STA ADDEND
        LDA #$00
        STA TMP_CNT
        STA ADDEND_HI
        LDA READY_WEAPON
        CMP #$08                        ; amulet: x 1.5
        BNE .wand
        LSR ADDEND_HI
        ROR ADDEND
.add    LDA ACC_HI                      ; accumulator += addend
        CLC
        ADC ADDEND
        STA ACC_HI
        LDA TMP_CNT
        ADC ADDEND_HI
        STA TMP_CNT
        JMP .strike
.wand   CMP #$09                        ; wand: x 2
        BNE .staff
        ASL ACC_HI
        ROL TMP_CNT
        JMP .strike
.staff  CMP #$0A                        ; staff or triangle: x 3
        BEQ .triple
        CMP #$0B
        BNE .strike
.triple ASL ACC_HI
        ROL TMP_CNT
        JMP .add
.strike LDA #$0A
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        JMP ATK_HIT
.feature
        CMP #$00                        ; floor and walk-on
        BEQ .pass                       ;   features pass the
        CMP #$05                        ;   missile through;
        BCS .pass                       ;   walls/doors eat it
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
.pass   DEC ACC
        BEQ .spent
        JMP .walk
.spent  JMP SPELL_FAIL
SP_STEAL
        ; Steal (NUDO) is town magic; in the dungeon it just
        ; fails.
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
@ %def SP_MISSILE SP_STEAL

The ladder spells conjure permanent geometry: a feature 7 or 8 in
the player's own cell, ready to K-limb. Ladder Down is refused on
level 10 (there is no deeper maze); Ladder Up needs no guard ---
climbing up from level 1 is the normal way out. Blink rerolls the
player's position to a uniformly random clear cell of the level.

<<dng spell ladders blink>>=
        ORG $92A6
SP_LADDER_DN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Ladder Down (INFERUS): conjure a down ladder underfoot.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Write feature 7 at the player's cell (refused on
        ;   level 10 -- there is nothing below).
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        CMP #$0A                        ; no level below 10
        BNE .ok
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
.ok     LDA #$07
LADDER_PUT
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Ladder created!",$00
        LDA #$0A
        JMP SFX_PLAY
SP_LADDER_UP
        ; Ladder Up (ASCENDO): conjure an up ladder underfoot.
        LDA #$08
        JMP LADDER_PUT
SP_BLINK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Blink (DUCIS-EDUCO): teleport to a random clear cell.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Reroll random interior coordinates until they name a
        ;   clear cell that is not the player's; move there.
.reroll JSR RND_CELL                    ; random interior (x,y)
        STA WORK_X
        JSR RND_CELL
        STA WORK_Y
        TAY
        LDX WORK_X
        CPX DNG_X                       ; same spot: roll again
        BNE .check
        CPY DNG_Y
        BEQ .reroll
.check  JSR CELL_READ                   ; clear floor only
        BNE .reroll
        LDA WORK_Y
        STA DNG_Y
        LDA WORK_X
        STA DNG_X
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Teleported!",$00
        LDA #$0A
        JMP SFX_PLAY
@ %def SP_LADDER_DN LADDER_PUT SP_LADDER_UP SP_BLINK

Create and Destroy manage force fields in the cell ahead ---
the corridor-plugging trick every Ultima veteran knows. Kill is
the assassin's version of Magic Missile: adjacent only, but no
damage roll --- the monster ahead is simply erased through the
[[MON_KILLED]] payout path (so it still yields experience, coin
and quest credit).

<<dng spell fields kill>>=
        ORG $9317
SP_CREATE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Create (STRUXI): force field in the cell ahead.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The cell ahead must be clear floor; write feature $C.
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        BEQ .clear
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
.clear  JSR AHEAD_XY
        LDA #$0C
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Field created!",$00
        LDA #$0A
        JMP SFX_PLAY
SP_DESTROY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Destroy (DELIO): remove the force field ahead.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The cell ahead must hold feature $C; clear it.
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$0C
        BEQ .field
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
.field  JSR AHEAD_XY
        LDA #$00
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Field destroyed!",$00
        LDA #$0A
        JMP SFX_PLAY
SP_KILL SUBROUTINE
        ; Kill (INTERFICIO): erase the monster in the cell ahead.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The cell ahead must hold a monster; announce it and
        ;   fall into MON_KILLED for the full payout.
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        STX TGT_X
        STY TGT_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$10
        BCS .victim
        JMP SPELL_FAIL
.victim LSR                             ; slot from the high
        LSR                             ;   nibble
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ACC
        CLC
        ADC MON_BASE
        TAX
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " destroyed!",$00
        LDA #$0A
        JSR SFX_PLAY
@ %def SP_CREATE SP_DESTROY SP_KILL

\section{DNG: kills, replacements and the quest check}

Every monster death --- by weapon, missile or Kill spell ---
lands here with the slot in [[ACC]] and the monster's cell in
[[TGT_X]]/[[TGT_Y]]. The bookkeeping has a twist that keeps a
dungeon level permanently dangerous: the dead monster's kind goes
back in the [[MON_FREE]] pool and a \emph{replacement is spawned
immediately}, fresh hit points and all, somewhere else on the
level. There are always three live monsters.

Experience is rejection-sampled to $1\ldots5\cdot\mathrm{slot}
\cdot\mathrm{level}$, credited twice: once to [[PLR_EXP]] (capped
at 9999 like every player 16-bit quantity) and once to
[[WINNINGS]], the dungeon bank that pays out as hit points on the
way up (see [[KLIMB_CMD]]).

The quest check is the heart of the king-quest system: killing
the \emph{slot-5} monster --- the toughest kind of the level pair
--- on levels 3 and deeper completes an odd-numbered
[[QUEST_FLAGS]] entry ($2t-1$ for tier $t = \lfloor(\mathrm{level}
-1)/2\rfloor$): the gelatinous cube, carrion creeper, lich and
balron quests. A flag must be \emph{assigned} (positive, set by a
king in a castle) before it can complete (then [[$FF]]); the
\texttt{TWN}/\texttt{CAS} round owns the other half of this
protocol.

<<dng monster killed>>=
        ORG $93A7
MON_KILLED
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A monster died: recycle it and pay the player.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ACC      -- the victim's slot (1-5)
        ;   TGT_X/Y  -- the victim's cell
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Return the kind to MON_FREE, strip the monster nibble
        ;   off its cell, spawn a replacement monster elsewhere,
        ;   award experience (and bank it in WINNINGS), check the
        ;   slot-5 quest, then fall into TREASURE.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   MON_FREE/MON_X/MON_Y/MON_HP, KILL_SLOT, WINNINGS,
        ;   PLR_EXP, QUEST_FLAGS, DNG_MAP
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX ACC
        STX KILL_SLOT
        LDA #$01                        ; kind back in the pool
        STA MON_FREE,X
        LDX TGT_X                       ; strip the monster off
        LDY TGT_Y                       ;   its cell, keep the
        JSR CELL_READ                   ;   feature under it
        AND #$0F
        LDX TGT_X
        LDY TGT_Y
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        ; --- spawn the replacement ---
.kind   JSR RND                         ; a free kind 1..5
        AND #$07
        BEQ .kind
        CMP #$06
        BCS .kind
        STA MON_SLOT
        TAX
        LDA MON_FREE,X
        BEQ .kind
        DEC MON_FREE,X                  ; now on the map
        LDA #$0A                        ; hit points: 10 +
        STA ACC                         ;   slot * rnd(level^2)
        LDA #$00
        STA ACC_HI
        LDY DNG_LEVEL
        LDA LEVEL_SQ,Y
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .one
        JSR RND_MOD
.one    LDY MON_SLOT
        JSR MUL_ADD
        LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA ACC
        STA MON_HP,X
        LDA ACC_HI
        STA MON_HP_HI,X
.place  JSR RND_CELL                    ; a clear cell that is
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ;   not the player's
        STA MON_Y,X
        JSR RND_CELL
        LDX MON_SLOT
        STA MON_X,X
        LDY MON_Y,X
        TAX
        JSR CELL_READ
        BNE .place
        LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA MON_X,X
        CMP DNG_X
        BNE .put
        LDA MON_Y,X
        CMP DNG_Y
        BEQ .place
.put    LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        LDA MON_SLOT                    ; cell <- slot << 4
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        ; --- experience: rnd(1 .. 5*slot*level) ---
        LDA #$00
        LDX DNG_LEVEL
.mul    CLC                             ; slot * level...
        ADC KILL_SLOT
        DEX
        BNE .mul
        STA ACC
        ASL                             ; ... * 5
        ASL
        CLC
        ADC ACC
        STA ACC
.roll   JSR RND
        CMP ACC
        BCS .roll
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        STA ACC
        LDA WINNINGS                    ; bank it for the climb
        CLC                             ;   out...
        ADC ACC
        STA WINNINGS
        LDA WINNINGS+1
        ADC #$00
        STA WINNINGS+1
        LDA PLR_EXP                     ; ...and score it now
        CLC
        ADC ACC
        STA PLR_EXP
        LDA PLR_EXP+1
        ADC #$00
        STA PLR_EXP+1
        LDA PLR_EXP                     ; cap at 9999
        CMP #$0F
        LDA PLR_EXP+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .quest
        LDA #$0F
        STA PLR_EXP
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_EXP+1
.quest  LDA KILL_SLOT                   ; the slot-5 monster of
        CMP #$05                        ;   tiers 1-4 is quest
        BNE TREASURE                    ;   game
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        SEC
        SBC #$01
        LSR                             ; tier 0-4
        BEQ TREASURE
        ASL
        TAX
        DEX                             ; quest slot 2*tier - 1
        LDA QUEST_FLAGS,X
        BEQ TREASURE                    ; not assigned by a king
        BMI TREASURE                    ; already completed
        LDA #$FF
        STA QUEST_FLAGS,X
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~A quest is completed!",$00
@ %def MON_KILLED

\section{DNG: treasure}

Kills, coffins and chests all pay through here. The amount is
$9 + m\cdot(5\ldots12)$ coins, where $m = \mathrm{rnd}(\mathrm{
level}^2)$ from the [[LEVEL_SQ]] table (a plain coin flip on
level 1) --- deep dungeons pay quadratically better. The purse is
capped at 9999 as ever.

The announcement is this engine's signature flourish: the binary
amount is read out as \emph{gold}, \emph{silver} and \emph{copper}
pieces --- hundreds, tens and ones --- with full English comma-and
itemization, down to ``and 3 copper!''.

<<dng treasure>>=
        ORG $94E0
TREASURE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Pay loot into the purse and read the amount out in
        ; period coinage.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Amount = 9 + rnd(level^2) * (5..12) coins, capped at
        ;   9999, announced as gold/silver/copper pieces
        ;   (hundreds/tens/ones) with comma-and itemization.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   PLR_COIN, ACC, ADDEND, TMP_CNT, NUM_PAD
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$09
        STA ACC
        LDA #$00
        STA ACC_HI
        LDY DNG_LEVEL
        LDA LEVEL_SQ,Y
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .flip
        JSR RND_MOD                     ; m = rnd(level^2)
        JMP .scale
.flip   JSR RND                         ; level 1: m = 0 or 1
        AND #$01
.scale  PHA
        JSR RND                         ; m * (5..12), added to
        AND #$07                        ;   the base 9
        CLC
        ADC #$05
        TAY
        PLA
        JSR MUL_ADD
        LDA PLR_COIN                    ; purse += amount,
        CLC                             ;   capped at 9999
        ADC ACC
        STA PLR_COIN
        LDA PLR_COIN+1
        ADC ACC_HI
        STA PLR_COIN+1
        LDA PLR_COIN
        CMP #$0F
        LDA PLR_COIN+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .announce
        LDA #$0F
        STA PLR_COIN
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_COIN+1
.announce
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou dost find: ",$00
        LDA #$00
        STA NUM_PAD
        STA TMP_CNT                     ; items printed so far
        LDA #$00
        STA ADDEND                      ; gold counter, 16-bit
        STA ADDEND_HI
.gold   LDA ACC                         ; whole hundreds are
        CMP #$64                        ;   gold pieces
        LDA ACC_HI
        SBC #$00
        BCC .saygold
        STA ACC_HI
        LDA ACC
        SBC #$64
        STA ACC
        INC ADDEND
        BNE .gold
        INC ADDEND_HI
        JMP .gold
.saygold
        LDA ADDEND
        ORA ADDEND_HI
        BEQ .silver
        INC TMP_CNT
        LDX ADDEND
        LDA ADDEND_HI
        JSR PRINT_NUM16
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " gold",$00
.silver LDX #$00                        ; whole tens are silver
        LDA ACC
.tens   CMP #$0A
        BCC .saysilver
        SEC
        SBC #$0A
        INX
        BNE .tens
.saysilver
        STA ACC                         ; the leftover coppers
        STX ADDEND
        LDA ADDEND
        BEQ .copper
        LDA TMP_CNT                     ; punctuate after gold
        BEQ .silv2
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B ",~",$00
        LDA ACC
        BNE .silv2
        JSR MSG_PRINT                   ; silver is the last item
        DC.B "and ",$00
.silv2  INC TMP_CNT
        LDX ADDEND
        LDA ADDEND_HI
        JSR PRINT_NUM16
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " silver",$00
.copper LDA ACC
        BEQ .bang
        LDA TMP_CNT
        BEQ .saycopper
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B ", ",$00
        LDA TMP_CNT
        CMP #$01
        BNE .and
        JSR PUTCH_NL_COL1
.and    JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "and ",$00
.saycopper
        LDA ACC
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " copper",$00
.bang   LDA #$21                        ; "!"
        JMP CHAR_OUT
@ %def TREASURE

\section{DNG: K-limb, and the way out}

K-limb works the ladder or trapdoor underfoot: an up ladder (8)
ascends, a down ladder (7) or a revealed trapdoor (9) descends.
Ladders --- but not trapdoors --- demand that the player
\emph{face} one ([[DNG_DY]] nonzero): the renderer only draws
ladders on north/south walls, so the rule is really ``you must be
able to see it''.

Each level change re-runs [[DNG_GEN]] for the new depth ---
descending and coming back up reproduces the upper maze exactly,
seeds being what they are.

Climbing up from level 1 is the exit, and the dungeon pays its
exit bonus: [[WINNINGS]] --- the banked kill experience ---
\emph{doubled} and added to the player's hit points (capped 9999).
This is the actual hit-point economy of Ultima I: hit points are
bought with dungeon crawls. Control returns to the engine at
[[EXIT_TO_OUT]], the entry of [[GAME_LOAD]] that reloads
\texttt{OUT} without the death sequence.

<<dng cmd klimb>>=
        ORG $961B
KLIMB_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; K-limb the ladder or trapdoor underfoot.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Feature 8 climbs up (level 0 = leave the dungeon,
        ;   paying 2 * WINNINGS as hit points); 7 and 9 climb
        ;   down. Ladders require facing north/south. The new
        ;   level is regenerated by DNG_GEN.
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        STA ACC
        CMP #$07
        BEQ .ladder
        CMP #$08
        BEQ .ladder
        CMP #$09                        ; a sprung trapdoor needs
        BEQ .climb                      ;   no facing
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " what",$00
        JMP QUERY_MARK
.ladder LDA DNG_DY                      ; ladders are on the
        BNE .climb                      ;   north/south walls
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou must face the ladder!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.climb  LDA ACC
        CMP #$08
        BEQ .up
        JMP GO_DOWN
.up     DEC DNG_LEVEL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " up to level ",$00
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        LDX #$00
        STX NUM_PAD
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        BEQ .out                        ; level 0: daylight
        JMP .regen
.out    ASL WINNINGS                    ; the exit bonus: twice
        ROL WINNINGS+1                  ;   the banked winnings,
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ;   paid in hit points
        STA ACC
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        STA ACC_HI
        LDA PLR_HITS
        CLC
        ADC WINNINGS
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        ADC WINNINGS+1
        STA PLR_HITS+1
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; capped at 9999
        CMP #$0F
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .gain
        LDA #$0F
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_HITS+1
.gain   LDA PLR_HITS                    ; report the actual gain
        SEC
        SBC ACC
        STA ZP_GAIN
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC ACC_HI
        STA ZP_GAIN+1
        ORA ZP_GAIN
        BEQ .leave
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou dost gain ",$00
        LDA #$00
        STA NUM_PAD
        LDX ZP_GAIN
        LDA ZP_GAIN+1
        JSR PRINT_NUM16
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " hit points",$00
.leave  JSR STATS_VALUES
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        JSR DRAW_BORDERS
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JSR PAGE_COPY
        JMP EXIT_TO_OUT                 ; back to the overworld
.regen  JSR DNG_GEN
        RTS
GO_DOWN INC DNG_LEVEL
        ; descend: regenerate one level deeper (also the
        ; trapdoor-fall entry from MOVE_FWD)
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " down to level ",$00
        LDA DNG_LEVEL
        LDX #$00
        STX NUM_PAD
        JSR PRINT_NUM8
        JSR DNG_GEN
        RTS
FOOD_CLAMP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Unreferenced in DNG: clamp PLR_FOOD at 9999.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The standard 16-bit 9999 cap; the sibling overlays
        ;   cap food after purchases/boons with this.
        LDA PLR_FOOD
        CMP #$0F
        LDA PLR_FOOD+1
        SBC #$27
        BCC .done
        LDA #$0F
        STA PLR_FOOD
        LDA #$27
        STA PLR_FOOD+1
.done   RTS
@ %def KLIMB_CMD GO_DOWN FOOD_CLAMP

\section{DNG: Open, Quit, Ready, Unlock, Ztats}

The Open \emph{command} (as opposed to the spell) opens the
coffin underfoot the hard way: about half the time the occupant
objects. If a kind is free in the pool and the cell ahead is
clear, the coffin's monster materializes there with hit points
$5\cdot\mathrm{level} + \mathrm{slot}$ and a \emph{Watch out!} ---
and the coffin stays shut, free to try again. Otherwise the
coffin empties through [[LOOT_CELL]] into [[TREASURE]].

<<dng cmd open>>=
        ORG $9768
OPEN_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Open the coffin underfoot. Half the time the corpse
        ; gets up first.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Requires feature 6 underfoot. Roll: on the unlucky
        ;   half (and a free kind, and a clear cell ahead) spawn
        ;   the occupant ahead with 5*level + slot hit points
        ;   and leave the coffin. Otherwise clear the cell and
        ;   pay TREASURE.
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " coffin",$00
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$06
        BEQ .coffin
        JMP NONE_HERE
.coffin JSR RND                         ; the (signed) luck roll
        CMP #$68
        BPL .loot
        LDA MON_FREE                    ; any kind left to wake?
        ORA MON_FREE+1
        ORA MON_FREE+2
        ORA MON_FREE+3
        ORA MON_FREE+4
        ORA MON_FREE+5
        BEQ .loot
        JSR AHEAD_XY                    ; somewhere to stand?
        JSR CELL_READ
        BEQ .wake
.loot   JMP LOOT_CELL
.wake   JSR RND                         ; pick a free kind
        AND #$07
        BEQ .wake
        CMP #$06
        BCS .wake
        STA MON_SLOT
        TAX
        LDA MON_FREE,X
        BEQ .wake
        LDA #$00                        ; it walks the map now
        STA MON_FREE,X
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Watch out!",$00
        JSR AHEAD_XY                    ; it stands in the cell
        TXA                             ;   ahead
        LDX MON_SLOT
        STA MON_X,X
        TYA
        STA MON_Y,X
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        LDA MON_SLOT
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; hit points: 5 * level
        ASL                             ;   + slot
        ASL
        CLC
        ADC DNG_LEVEL
        ADC MON_SLOT
        LDX MON_SLOT
        STA MON_HP,X
        LDA #$00
        STA MON_HP_HI,X
        RTS
@ %def OPEN_CMD

Quit-and-save is an outdoor privilege --- the dungeon refuses it
with a column-aligned snub. Ready is a thin shim over the
engine's [[READY_CMD]] picker, redrawing the frame first because
the picker pops a window over the wireframe.

<<dng cmd quit ready>>=
        ORG $9804
QUIT_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Quit & save is refused underground.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Align the cursor after the echoed command name and
        ;   scold; no time passes.
        LDA #$12                        ; align after the echoed
        STA MON_CH                      ;   "Quit & save"
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " is~only allowed outdoors!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
READY_DNG
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Ready: prompt S/W/A and hand off to the engine picker.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Any other key cancels. The frame is redrawn first
        ;   because READY_CMD pops a window over the wireframe.
        JSR KEY_SHORT
        CMP #$53                        ; 'S'pell
        BEQ .pick
        CMP #$57                        ; 'W'eapon
        BEQ .pick
        CMP #$41                        ; 'A'rmour
        BEQ .pick
        RTS
.pick   PHA
        JSR WIN_SAVE                    ; the picker pops a
        JSR DRAW_BORDERS                ;   window; clean the
        JSR WIN_RESTORE                 ;   frame first
        PLA
        JSR READY_CMD
        RTS
@ %def QUIT_CMD READY_DNG

Unlock opens the chest underfoot. Chests are trapped: any class
but the thief (4) must beat $\mathrm{rnd} < \mathrm{agility} +
128$ or take \emph{level} damage --- potentially fatal. Either
way the chest then pays out normally; the trap is a toll, not a
lock.

<<dng cmd unlock>>=
        ORG $9848
UNLOCK_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Unlock the chest underfoot, springing its trap.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Requires feature 5 underfoot. Unless the class is
        ;   thief (4) or rnd < agility + 128, the trap deals
        ;   level damage (possibly fatal). Then LOOT_CELL pays
        ;   out either way.
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " chest",$00
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$05
        BEQ .chest
NONE_HERE
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " - none here!",$00
        JMP BEEP_HUH
.chest  LDA PLR_CLASS
        CMP #$04                        ; thieves disarm free
        BEQ LOOT_CELL
        LDA #$80                        ; dodge: rnd < agi + 128
        CLC
        ADC PLR_AGI
        STA ACC
        JSR RND
        CMP ACC
        BCC LOOT_CELL
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou hast set off a trap!",$00
        LDA #$02
        JSR SFX_PLAY
        LDA PLR_HITS                    ; trap damage = level
        SEC
        SBC DNG_LEVEL
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC #$00
        STA PLR_HITS+1
        BCC DNG_DEATH
        RTS
LOOT_CELL
        ; empty the container underfoot into the purse
        LDX DNG_X
        LDY DNG_Y
        LDA #$00
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JMP TREASURE
@ %def UNLOCK_CMD NONE_HERE LOOT_CELL

<<dng cmd ztats death>>=
        ORG $98D1
ZTATS_CMD
        ; Ztats: clean the frame, then the engine inventory.
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        JSR DRAW_BORDERS
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JMP INVENTORY
DNG_DEATH
        ; dead underground: tidy the screen and let the engine
        ; run the death-and-respawn sequence (reloads OUT)
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        JSR DRAW_BORDERS
        JSR WIN_RESTORE
        JSR PAGE_COPY
        JMP RESPAWN
@ %def ZTATS_CMD DNG_DEATH

\section{DNG: the monsters' turn}

After every command and every idle beat, slots 5 down to 1 each
get a move. The brain is simple but effective in a corridor maze:
measure the true Euclidean distance to the player
([[MON_DIST]] computes $\lfloor\sqrt{dx^2+dy^2}\rfloor$ with an
odd-number square root --- remarkable trouble for a monster AI).
At distance exactly 1 (orthogonally adjacent), strike. Beyond
distance 4 (offscreen), sleep. In between, approach: step one
cell along $x$ if that changes anything and is passable,
otherwise along $y$. Monsters refuse walls, \emph{unsprung}
trapdoors and force fields, but walk freely through doors and
even undetected secret doors --- they live here, after all. A
monster stepping onto a chest or ladder carries the feature in
the low nibble of its cell and puts it back on leaving.

<<dng monster turns>>=
        ORG $98EC
MON_TURNS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; One action for each live monster, slots 5 down to 1.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Skip pooled kinds. Distance 1: MON_STRIKE. Distance
        ;   >= 4: sleep. Else step toward the player, x first
        ;   then y, carrying any feature in the cell.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   MON_SLOT, MON_X/MON_Y, DNG_MAP, STEP_X/STEP_Y,
        ;   TGT_X/TGT_Y
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX #$05
        STX MON_SLOT
.slot   LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA MON_FREE,X                  ; in the pool = not on
        BEQ .alive                      ;   the map
        JMP MON_NEXT
.alive  JSR MON_DIST
        BEQ .strike                     ; on top of us (cannot
        CMP #$02                        ;   happen) -- strike
        BCS .far
        TXA                             ; distance 1 + remainder
        BNE .far                        ;   = diagonal: approach
.strike JMP MON_STRIKE
.far    CMP #$04                        ; beyond 4: out of sight,
        BCC .approach                   ;   sleep
        JMP MON_NEXT
.approach
        LDY #$00                        ; STEP_X = sign(player.x
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ;   - monster.x)
        LDA DNG_X
        CMP MON_X,X
        BEQ .sgnx
        BMI .negx
        INY
        BNE .sgnx
.negx   DEY
.sgnx   STY STEP_X
        LDY #$00                        ; STEP_Y likewise
        LDA DNG_Y
        CMP MON_Y,X
        BEQ .sgny
        BMI .negy
        INY
        BNE .sgny
.negy   DEY
.sgny   STY STEP_Y
        LDA MON_Y,X                     ; the diagonal target
        CLC                             ;   cell
        ADC STEP_Y
        STA TGT_Y
        TAY
        LDA MON_X,X
        TAX
        CLC
        ADC STEP_X
        STA TGT_X
        LDA TGT_X                       ; try the x step first:
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ;   only if it moves
        CMP MON_X,X
        BEQ .try_y
        LDY MON_Y,X
        TAX
        JSR CELL_READ                   ; (TGT_X, mon.y) passable?
        CMP #$01                        ; walls, unsprung
        BEQ .try_y                      ;   trapdoors and fields
        CMP #$02                        ;   block monsters
        BEQ .try_y
        CMP #$0C
        BCS .try_y
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ; leave the old cell:
        JSR MON_XY                      ;   put the feature back
        JSR CELL_READ
        PHA
        LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        PLA
        AND #$0F
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ; commit the x move
        LDA TGT_X
        STA MON_X,X
        JSR MON_XY                      ; pick up the feature in
        JSR CELL_READ                   ;   the new cell
        STA ACC
        LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        LDA MON_SLOT
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ORA ACC
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        JMP MON_NEXT
.try_y  LDX MON_SLOT                    ; the y step, same dance
        LDA MON_X,X
        TAX
        LDY TGT_Y
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$01
        BEQ MON_NEXT
        CMP #$02
        BEQ MON_NEXT
        CMP #$0C
        BCS MON_NEXT
        LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        PHA
        LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        PLA
        AND #$0F
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA TGT_Y
        STA MON_Y,X
        JSR MON_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        STA ACC
        LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        LDA MON_SLOT
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ORA ACC
        JSR CELL_WRITE
MON_NEXT
        DEC MON_SLOT
        BEQ .done
        JMP .slot
.done   RTS
@ %def MON_TURNS MON_NEXT

An adjacent monster attacks. The to-hit roll is against the
player's armour: $\mathrm{rnd} \ge \mathrm{stamina}/2 +
8\cdot\mathrm{armour} + 56$ hits, so plate and high stamina
genuinely tank. Four kinds skip the damage roll for signature
moves --- the thief steals a spare weapon (with correct
\emph{a/an} grammar for the axe and the amulet), the gelatinous
cube eats the readied armour, the gremlin halves the food, and
the mind whipper (half the time) whips the mind: intelligence
$\leftarrow$ intelligence$/2 + 5$. Plain damage is
rejection-sampled below $\mathrm{level} +
\mathrm{slot}\cdot\mathrm{level}^2$, plus one. The sampler is
\emph{built} for 16 bits --- a balron on level 10 has a 510-point
limit --- but its high byte is initialized to zero and only
re-rolled when already nonzero, so it never engages: actual
damage caps at 256. A latent bug, kind to deep divers.

<<dng monster strike>>=
        ORG $9A0A
MON_STRIKE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The monster in MON_SLOT attacks the player.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Announce; set FIGHT_FLAG (the prompt reprints). Roll
        ;   rnd >= sta/2 + 8*armour + 56 to hit. Specials by
        ;   kind: thief steals, gelatinous cube strips armour,
        ;   gremlin halves food, mind whipper drains int (50%).
        ;   Else damage = rnd(1 .. level + slot*level^2) -- but
        ;   the sample's high byte never engages (see prose), so
        ;   at most 256.
        LDA #$17                        ; messages at the bottom
        STA MON_CV
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Attacked by ",$00
        LDA MON_SLOT
        CLC
        ADC MON_BASE
        TAX
        JSR STR_NTH_CAP
        DC.W STR_MONSTERS
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "!~",$00
        LDA #$04                        ; the attack sound
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDA PLR_STA                     ; defense: stamina/2
        LSR                             ;   + 8*armour + 56
        CLC
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC READY_ARMOUR
        ADC #$38
        STA ACC
        STA FIGHT_FLAG                  ; nonzero: combat output
        JSR RND
        CMP ACC
        BCS .hit
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Missed!",$00
        JMP MON_NEXT
.hit    LDA MON_SLOT                    ; the four specialists
        CLC                             ;   dispatch by name
        ADC MON_BASE                    ;   index
        CMP #$17                        ; 23 = thief
        BNE .not_thief
        JMP .thief
.not_thief
        CMP #$1E                        ; 30 = gelatinous cube
        BNE .not_cube
        JMP .cube
.not_cube
        CMP #$25                        ; 37 = gremlin
        BNE .not_grem
        JMP .gremlin
.not_grem
        CMP #$2A                        ; 42 = mind whipper
        BNE MON_DAMAGE
        JMP .whip
MON_DAMAGE
        LDY DNG_LEVEL                   ; damage limit: level +
        STY ACC                         ;   slot * level^2,
        LDA #$00                        ;   16 bits of trouble
        STA ACC_HI
        STA ADDEND_HI
        LDA LEVEL_SQ,Y
        LDY MON_SLOT
        JSR MUL_ADD
.roll   JSR RND                         ; 16-bit rejection sample
        STA ADDEND
        LDA ADDEND_HI
        BEQ .low
        JSR RND
        STA ADDEND_HI
.low    LDA ADDEND
        CMP ACC
        LDA ADDEND_HI
        SBC ACC_HI
        BCS .roll
        LDA ADDEND                      ; damage = sample + 1
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        STA ACC
        LDA ADDEND_HI
        ADC #$00
        STA ACC_HI
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Hit... ",$00
        LDX #$00
        STX NUM_PAD
        LDA ACC_HI
        LDX ACC
        JSR PRINT_NUM16
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " damage",$00
        LDA #$02                        ; the hurt sound
        JSR SFX_QUEUE
        LDA PLR_HITS
        SEC
        SBC ACC
        STA PLR_HITS
        LDA PLR_HITS+1
        SBC ACC_HI
        STA PLR_HITS+1
        BCC .dead
        JMP MON_NEXT
.dead   JMP DNG_DEATH
.thief  JMP THIEF_STEAL
.cube   JMP CUBE_ARMOUR
.gremlin
        JMP GREMLIN_FOOD
.whip   JSR RND                         ; mind whipper: 50%
        BMI .mental                     ;   mental attack
        JMP MON_DAMAGE
.mental JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Mental attack!",$00
        LDA PLR_INT                     ; int <- int/2 + 5
        LSR
        CLC
        ADC #$05
        STA PLR_INT
        RTS
THIEF_STEAL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The thief's signature move.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Steal the first spare weapon (not readied, not
        ;   hands), with a/an grammar; a bare pack falls back to
        ;   plain MON_DAMAGE. A successful theft ends the whole
        ;   monster phase (RTS, not MON_NEXT).
        LDX #$01
.scan   LDA OWNED_WEAPONS,X
        BEQ .next
        CPX READY_WEAPON
        BEQ .next
        DEC OWNED_WEAPONS,X
        STX ACC
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Thief stole a",$00
        LDA ACC
        CMP #$03                        ; axe and amulet take
        BEQ .an                         ;   "an"
        CMP #$08
        BNE .a
.an     LDA #$6E                        ; "n"
        JSR CHAR_OUT
.a      LDA #$20
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDX ACC
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W STR_WEAPONS
        LDA #$21                        ; "!"
        JMP CHAR_OUT
.next   INX
        CPX #$10
        BNE .scan
        JMP MON_DAMAGE
CUBE_ARMOUR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; The gelatinous cube's signature move.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Dissolve the readied armour (one count, unreadied);
        ;   a player in skin takes plain MON_DAMAGE instead.
        LDA READY_ARMOUR
        BNE .melt
        JMP MON_DAMAGE
.melt   JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "Armour destroyed!",$00
        LDX READY_ARMOUR
        DEC OWNED_ARMOUR,X
        LDA #$00
        STA READY_ARMOUR
        JMP MON_NEXT
GREMLIN_FOOD
        ; Halve the food supply (16-bit shift).
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "A gremlin stole some food!",$00
        LSR PLR_FOOD+1
        ROR PLR_FOOD
        JMP MON_NEXT
@ %def MON_STRIKE MON_DAMAGE THIEF_STEAL CUBE_ARMOUR GREMLIN_FOOD

\section{DNG: stocking a level with monsters}

[[LEVEL_INIT]] runs at the tail of every [[DNG_GEN]]: pick the
level pair's name base, mark all five kinds free, then release
three of them at random clear cells with hit points
$10 + \mathrm{slot}\cdot\mathrm{rnd}(\mathrm{level}^2)$ ---
the same formula the kill-replacement spawner uses, so the
population is uniform from entry to exit.

<<dng level init>>=
        ORG $9BED
LEVEL_INIT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Set the level's monster roster and release three.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   MON_BASE = 5 * floor((level-1)/2) + 20; all kinds
        ;   to the pool; spawn three at random clear cells.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   MON_BASE, MON_FREE/MON_X/MON_Y/MON_HP, DNG_MAP
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA DNG_LEVEL                   ; the roster base for
        SEC                             ;   this level pair
        SBC #$01
        LSR
        STA ACC
        ASL
        ASL
        CLC
        ADC ACC
        ADC #$14
        STA MON_BASE
        LDX #$05                        ; all five kinds free
        LDA #$01
.pool   STA MON_FREE,X
        DEX
        BNE .pool
        LDA #$03                        ; release three
        STA WORK_X
.kind   JSR RND                         ; a free kind 1..5
        AND #$07
        BEQ .kind
        CMP #$06
        BCS .kind
        STA MON_SLOT
        TAX
        LDA MON_FREE,X
        BEQ .kind
        DEC MON_FREE,X
        LDA #$0A                        ; hit points: 10 +
        STA ACC                         ;   slot * rnd(level^2)
        LDA #$00
        STA ACC_HI
        LDY DNG_LEVEL
        LDA LEVEL_SQ,Y
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .one
        JSR RND_MOD
.one    LDY MON_SLOT
        JSR MUL_ADD
        LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA ACC
        STA MON_HP,X
        LDA ACC_HI
        STA MON_HP_HI,X
.place  JSR RND_CELL                    ; a clear cell that is
        LDX MON_SLOT                    ;   not the player's
        STA MON_Y,X
        JSR RND_CELL
        LDX MON_SLOT
        STA MON_X,X
        LDY MON_Y,X
        TAX
        JSR CELL_READ
        BNE .place
        LDX MON_SLOT
        LDA MON_X,X
        CMP DNG_X
        BNE .put
        LDA MON_Y,X
        CMP DNG_Y
        BEQ .place
.put    LDX MON_SLOT
        JSR MON_XY
        LDA MON_SLOT
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        ASL
        JSR CELL_WRITE
        DEC WORK_X
        BEQ .done
        JMP .kind
.done   RTS
MON_XY  ; X/Y := MON_X/MON_Y of the monster in (6502) X
        LDA MON_Y,X
        TAY
        LDA MON_X,X
        TAX
        RTS
RND_CELL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := a random interior coordinate.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Rejection-roll 1..9; X and Y are preserved (callers
        ;   use it once per axis).
        STX ACC
        STY ACC_HI
.roll   JSR RND
        AND #$0F
        BEQ .roll
        CMP #$0A
        BCS .roll
        LDX ACC
        LDY ACC_HI
        RTS
MUL_ADD SUBROUTINE
        ; ACC (16-bit) += A * Y, by repeated addition.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A -- addend; Y -- repeat count (>= 1)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The poor man's multiply behind hit points, damage
        ;   limits and treasure amounts.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ACC/ACC_HI, ADDEND
        STA ADDEND
.add    LDA ACC
        CLC
        ADC ADDEND
        STA ACC
        BCC .next
        INC ACC_HI
.next   DEY
        BNE .add
        RTS
@ %def LEVEL_INIT MON_XY RND_CELL MUL_ADD

\section{DNG: Inform \& search}

Inform examines the cell \emph{ahead} for the two hidden
features: an unsprung trapdoor (2) becomes a visible, K-limbable
hole (9), and a secret door (3) becomes a drawn, walkable door
(4). Everything else --- including a wall that really is just a
wall --- earns ``nothing.''

<<dng cmd inform>>=
        ORG $9CD2
INFORM_CMD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Inform & search: examine the cell ahead.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   A hidden trapdoor (2) becomes a K-limbable hole (9);
        ;   a secret door (3) becomes a drawn door (4);
        ;   anything else is "nothing.".
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "~Thou dost find ",$00
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        JSR CELL_READ
        CMP #$02
        BNE .door
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "a trapdoor!",$00
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        LDA #$09                        ; sprung: K-limb works
        JMP CELL_WRITE
.door   CMP #$03
        BNE .nothing
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "a secret door!",$00
        JSR AHEAD_XY
        LDA #$04                        ; drawn and walkable
        JMP CELL_WRITE
.nothing
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "nothing.",$00
        RTS
@ %def INFORM_CMD

\section{DNG: map access and the distance root}

The 11$\times$11 map is addressed by repeated addition --- no
row table, just $+11$ per row. [[CELL_READ]]'s one quirk matters
to [[MOVE_XY]] above: the carry is only meaningfully set for row
0, so it is no passable flag. [[RND_STEP]] and [[MON_WANDER]] are
the town walker's random-drift kit, unreferenced here.

<<dng map helpers>>=
        ORG $9D32
CELL_READ
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := the map cell at column X, row Y.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   DNG_MAP[X + 11*Y], the row offset built by repeated
        ;   addition; Z reflects the cell byte.
        TXA
        CPY #$00
.row    BEQ .get
        CLC
        ADC #$0B
        DEY
        JMP .row
.get    TAX
        LDA DNG_MAP,X
        RTS
CELL_FEAT
        ; A := the feature nibble at (X,Y)
        JSR CELL_READ
        AND #$0F
        RTS
RND_STEP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := a random drift step. (Unreferenced in DNG.)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   -1, 0 or +1, one third each; the town walker's
        ;   random-drift kit.
        JSR RND
        CMP #$55
        BCS .third2
        LDA #$FF
        RTS
.third2 CMP #$AA
        BCS .third3
        LDA #$00
        RTS
.third3 LDA #$01
        RTS
MON_WANDER
        ; TGT := monster Y's cell plus a random step on each
        ; axis. (Unreferenced in DNG: town-walker kit.)
        JSR RND_STEP
        CLC
        ADC MON_X,Y
        STA TGT_X
        JSR RND_STEP
        CLC
        ADC MON_Y,Y
        STA TGT_Y
        RTS
POPUP_NOTE
        ; Unreferenced in DNG: message-window popup shell.
        JSR WIN_TEXT
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$17
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B "~",$00
        JMP PRESS_SPACE
@ %def CELL_READ CELL_FEAT RND_STEP MON_WANDER POPUP_NOTE

[[MON_DIST]] is the most mathematically earnest routine in the
overlay: it squares $|dx|$ and $|dy|$ by summing ($n^2 =
n + n + \cdots$, $n$ times), adds them in 16 bits, and extracts
the integer square root by subtracting successive odd numbers
($1+3+5+\cdots+(2k-1) = k^2$). The remainder distinguishes a true
orthogonal neighbor ($d=1$ exactly) from a diagonal one
($d^2=2$) --- that is how the walker knows when to strike versus
sidestep.

<<dng monster distance>>=
        ORG $9D81
MON_DIST
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := the Euclidean distance from monster X to the
        ; player.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   floor(sqrt(dx^2 + dy^2)): squares by repeated
        ;   addition, 16-bit sum, root by subtracting odd
        ;   numbers.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   X -- monster slot
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   A = Y = the distance; X = the remainder low byte
        ;   (nonzero means the distance is not exact);
        ;   DIST = distance. A coordinate of $FF returns $FF.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   DIST, SQRT_STEP, NEG_TMP, SLOT_SAVE
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        STX SLOT_SAVE
        LDA MON_X,X
        CMP #$FF                        ; unplaced sentinel
        BEQ .inf
        LDA DNG_X
        CMP #$FF
        BEQ .inf
        SEC                             ; |dx|
        SBC MON_X,X
        BCS .sq1
        STA NEG_TMP
        SEC
        LDA #$00
        SBC NEG_TMP
.sq1    LDY #$00                        ; dx^2 by repeated
        STY DIST                        ;   addition
        STY DIST+1
        TAY
        TAX
        INX
.add1   DEX
        BEQ .dy
        TYA
        CLC
        ADC DIST
        STA DIST
        BCC .add1
        INC DIST+1
        BCS .add1
.dy     LDX SLOT_SAVE                   ; |dy|
        LDA DNG_Y
        SEC
        SBC MON_Y,X
        BCS .sq2
        STA NEG_TMP
        SEC
        LDA #$00
        SBC NEG_TMP
.sq2    LDY #$00                        ; dy^2, accumulated
        STY SQRT_STEP                   ;   separately
        STY SQRT_STEP+1
        TAY
        TAX
        INX
.add2   DEX
        BEQ .sum
        TYA
        CLC
        ADC SQRT_STEP
        STA SQRT_STEP
        BCC .add2
        INC SQRT_STEP+1
        BCS .add2
.sum    CLC                             ; DIST = dx^2 + dy^2
        LDA SQRT_STEP
        ADC DIST
        STA DIST
        LDA SQRT_STEP+1
        ADC DIST+1
        STA DIST+1
        BCC .sqrt
.inf    LDA #$FF                        ; overflow / sentinel:
        STA DIST                        ;   infinitely far
        RTS
.sqrt   LDY #$01                        ; subtract odd numbers:
        STY SQRT_STEP                   ;   1+3+5+...+(2k-1)=k^2
        DEY
        STY SQRT_STEP+1
.odd    SEC
        LDA DIST
        TAX
        SBC SQRT_STEP
        STA DIST
        LDA DIST+1
        SBC SQRT_STEP+1
        STA DIST+1
        BCC .done
        INY
        LDA SQRT_STEP                   ; next odd (carry is set)
        ADC #$01
        STA SQRT_STEP
        BCC .odd
        INC SQRT_STEP+1
        BCS .odd
.done   STY DIST                        ; Y = root, X = remainder
        STX DIST+1
        TYA
        RTS
@ %def MON_DIST

\section{DNG: the perspective tables}

[[DNG_GEOM]] is the pool of pre-computed screen coordinates the
wireframe primitives read, indexed by [[VIEW_DEPTH]]. It is a
tight pack of ten-entry columns (one entry per depth, $1$--$10$),
each giving one edge coordinate of the corridor box at that
depth. The values converge: an X column runs
[[$00]]\,[[$40]]\,[[$60]]\,[[$70]]\,$\ldots$ toward [[$7F]] (the
screen centre), a Y column similarly, so the box edges close on
the vanishing point as the corridor recedes.

The columns are packed without gaps and the code reaches them by
adding a fixed byte offset to [[DNG_GEOM]] before indexing by
[[VIEW_DEPTH]]. The geometric roles that the box primitive
([[DRAW_COFFIN]]) makes explicit, by offset:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{ll}
offset & role \\
\hline
\texttt{+\$00} & near/inner left X ramp (and \texttt{+\$01} its
                  depth$+1$ neighbour) \\
\texttt{+\$0B} & inner right X ramp \\
\texttt{+\$16} & top edge Y (ceiling line) \\
\texttt{+\$21} & bottom edge Y (floor line) \\
\texttt{+\$22} & far floor Y (\texttt{BOX\_YF} source) \\
\texttt{+\$54} & near top Y (\texttt{BOX\_YN} source) \\
\texttt{+\$9A} & far-left X (\texttt{BOX\_XFL}) \\
\texttt{+\$A4} & near-left X (\texttt{BOX\_XNL}) \\
\texttt{+\$AE} & far-right X (\texttt{BOX\_XFR}) \\
\texttt{+\$B8} & near-right X (\texttt{BOX\_XNR}) \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The other offsets the primitives use (\texttt{+\$36},
\texttt{+\$40}, \texttt{+\$4A}, \texttt{+\$5E}, \texttt{+\$68},
\texttt{+\$72}, \texttt{+\$7C}, \texttt{+\$86}, \texttt{+\$90})
are intermediate ramps for the ceiling/floor diagonals and the
side-opening and ladder geometry. Rather than split one
hand-packed pool into two dozen aliased labels, the table stays
a single blob and the primitives address it by offset.

<<dng perspective tables>>=
        ORG $9E42
DNG_GEOM
        HEX 00406070787C7E7F
        HEX 7F7F7FFFBF9F8F87
        HEX 8381808080800020
        HEX 30383C3E3F3F3F3F
        HEX 3F7F5F4F47434140
        HEX 4040404010486472
        HEX 797C7F7F7F7F3058
        HEX 6C767B7C7F7F7F7F
        HEX EFB79B8D86838080
        HEX 8080CFA793898483
        HEX 80808080775B4D46
        HEX 4240404040406753
        HEX 4944424040404040
        HEX 2A353B3D3E3F3F3F
        HEX 3F3F385C6E7A7D7E
        HEX 7F7F7F7FC7A39185
        HEX 8281808080801008
        HEX 0402010000000000
        HEX 6F574B4542404040
        HEX 40404C6673797C7E
        HEX 7F7F7F7F586C767A
        HEX 7D7E7F7F7F7FB098
        HEX 8C86838281808080
        HEX A8948A8582818080
        HEX 8080
@ %def DNG_GEOM

\section{DNG: the wireframe primitives}

Each primitive draws one feature of one depth slice. They all
share an idiom: load [[VIEW_DEPTH]] into [[X]], read box-edge
coordinates from [[DNG_GEOM]] indexed by [[X]] into the line
workspace ([[$06]]/[[$07]] start point, [[$08]]/[[$09]] end
point), and call [[LINE_AGAIN]] (which draws from the start point
to the end point and leaves the end point as the next start).
The colour is set by the caller; only [[DRAW_FIELD]] changes it
(to red) and restores it.

[[DRAW_COFFIN]] is the workhorse: it draws a full perspective
box --- the floating cube used for a coffin or a closed chamber.
It reads all four near/far corners and three interpolated mid-Y
values ([[BOX_YA]]/[[BOX_YB]]/[[BOX_YC]]) and strokes the twelve
visible edges. (A monster standing in the cell suppresses it ---
the [[$1E]]/[[$29]] sentinels are the chest/coffin placeholders,
which \emph{do} get the box.)

<<dng primitive box>>=
        ORG $9F04
DRAW_COFFIN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw a perspective box at VIEW_DEPTH (coffin / chamber).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Suppress if a live monster occupies the cell. Otherwise
        ;   compute the eight box corners and three mid-Y rungs from
        ;   DNG_GEOM and stroke the twelve edges with LINE_AGAIN.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA MON_SLOT                    ; skip if a real monster is
        BEQ .draw                       ;   here (not a chest/coffin
        CLC                             ;   sentinel)
        ADC MON_BASE
        CMP #$1E
        BEQ .draw
        CMP #$29
        BEQ .draw
        RTS
.draw   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X              ; BOX_YN = near top Y
        STA BOX_YN
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X              ; BOX_YF = far floor Y
        STA BOX_YF
        CLC
        ADC DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        LSR                             ; BOX_YB = (YF+YN)/2
        STA BOX_YB
        CLC
        ADC DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        LSR                             ; BOX_YC = (YB+YN)/2
        STA BOX_YC
        LDA BOX_YB
        CLC
        ADC DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        LSR                             ; BOX_YA = (YB+YF)/2
        STA BOX_YA
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$9A,X              ; the four near/far X corners
        STA BOX_XFL
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$AE,X
        STA BOX_XFR
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$A4,X
        STA BOX_XNL
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$B8,X
        STA BOX_XNR
        LDA BOX_XFL                     ; start at far-left, BOX_YA
        STA $06
        LDA BOX_YA
        STA $07
        LDA BOX_XNL
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YF
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XFR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YA
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XFR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YC
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YN
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNL
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YN
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XFL
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YC
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XFL
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YA
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNL
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YB
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YB
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YN
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNL                     ; close the near face
        STA $06
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YN
        STA $07
        LDA BOX_YB
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA BOX_XNR
        STA $06
        LDA BOX_YB
        STA $07
        LDA BOX_XFR
        STA $08
        LDA BOX_YA
        STA $09
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
@ %def DRAW_COFFIN

[[DRAW_LADDER_SHAFT]] draws the vertical shaft frame for a ladder
cell (codes 7 and 8); [[DRAW_LADDER_DN]] and [[DRAW_LADDER_UP]]
add the rungs, the up-ladder mirroring the down-ladder through
the horizon at [[$7F]].

<<dng primitive ladder shaft>>=
        ORG $A00F
DRAW_LADDER_SHAFT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the vertical shaft of a ladder cell at VIEW_DEPTH.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Skip if a monster occupies the cell. A side-on view (dy=0)
        ;   draws one centred upright; a head-on view draws both
        ;   uprights and four cross-rungs from the perspective tables.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA MON_SLOT                    ; skip if a monster is here
        BEQ .draw
        CLC
        ADC MON_BASE
        CMP #$1E
        BEQ .draw
        CMP #$20
        BEQ .draw
        CMP #$29
        BEQ .draw
        RTS
.draw   LDA DNG_DY
        BNE .deep                       ; facing along Y: full shaft
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH                  ; facing along X: a single
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X              ;   centred vertical stroke
        STA $07
        LDA #$7F
        STA $06
        STA $08
        SEC
        SBC $07
        STA $09
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
.deep   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $07
        LDA #$7F
        SEC
        SBC $07
        STA $09
        PHA
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$38,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        PLA
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$4C,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA #$04                        ; four rungs
        STA ACC
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$86,X
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ACC_HI
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        CLC
        ADC ACC_HI
        STA $07
        STA $09
.rung   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$38,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$4C,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$86,X
        LSR
        CLC
        ADC DNG_GEOM+$86,X
        ADC $07
        STA $07
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        DEC ACC
        BNE .rung
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_LADDER_SHAFT

<<dng primitive field>>=
        ORG $A0AE
DRAW_FIELD
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw a red force field (three horizontal bars) at depth.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Switch the pen to red, stroke three evenly-spaced
        ;   horizontal bars across the cell-ahead opening, restore
        ;   white.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$03                        ; three bars
        STA ACC
        LDA #$05                        ; red
        JSR COLOR_SET
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$86,X
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ACC_HI
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$68,X
        SEC
        SBC ACC_HI
        STA $07
        STA $09
.bar    LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$2C,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$40,X
        STA $08
        LDA $07
        CLC
        ADC DNG_GEOM+$86,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        DEC ACC
        BNE .bar
        LDA #$07                        ; restore white
        JMP COLOR_SET
@ %def DRAW_FIELD

<<dng primitive ladder down>>=
        ORG $A0F2
DRAW_LADDER_DN
        ; Draw the rails of a downward ladder at VIEW_DEPTH.
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$72,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$37,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$5E,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$4B,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$7C,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$72,X
        STA $08
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
@ %def DRAW_LADDER_DN

<<dng primitive ladder up>>=
        ORG $A132
DRAW_LADDER_UP
        ; Draw the rails of an upward ladder (down-ladder mirrored
        ; through the horizon at $7F).
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$72,X
        STA $06
        LDA #$7F
        SEC
        SBC DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$37,X
        STA $08
        LDA #$7F
        SEC
        SBC DNG_GEOM+$5E,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$4B,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$7C,X
        STA $08
        LDA #$7F
        SEC
        SBC DNG_GEOM+$54,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$72,X
        STA $08
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
@ %def DRAW_LADDER_UP

[[DRAW_OPEN_L]] and [[DRAW_OPEN_R]] paint the floor/ceiling
edges of a \emph{side passage} --- the dark opening where a
corridor branches off left or right. Each peeks one cell further
([[AHEAD_FEAT]]) to decide whether to close the far edge.

<<dng primitive open left>>=
        ORG $A17B
DRAW_OPEN_L
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the left side-passage opening at VIEW_DEPTH.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Stroke the floor and ceiling edges of a branch opening on
        ;   the left; close the far edge only if the cell one step
        ;   deeper (AHEAD_FEAT) is solid.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        BEQ .near
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
.near   LDA DNG_GEOM+$17,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$01,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        JSR AHEAD_FEAT
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .skip
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .skip
        CMP #$04
        BEQ .skip
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
.skip   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $08
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
@ %def DRAW_OPEN_L

<<dng primitive open right>>=
        ORG $A1D7
DRAW_OPEN_R
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the right side-passage opening at VIEW_DEPTH.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Mirror of DRAW_OPEN_L for a branch opening on the right.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        BEQ .near
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
.near   LDA DNG_GEOM+$17,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0C,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        JSR AHEAD_FEAT
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .skip
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .skip
        CMP #$04
        BEQ .skip
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
.skip   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $08
        JMP LINE_AGAIN
@ %def DRAW_OPEN_R

[[AHEAD_FEAT]] is the look-ahead helper [[DRAW_OPEN_L]]/[[_R]]
use: the feature of the cell one step deeper than the slice
being drawn, so the opening's far edge is closed only when the
passage really ends there.

<<dng primitive ahead feat>>=
        ORG $A233
AHEAD_FEAT
        ; A := feature nibble of the cell one step ahead of WORK.
        LDA WORK_X
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DX
        TAX
        LDA WORK_Y
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY
        TAY
        JSR CELL_READ
        AND #$0F
        RTS
@ %def AHEAD_FEAT

[[DRAW_WALL_L]] and [[DRAW_WALL_R]] paint a solid side wall ---
the two diagonals (ceiling and floor) of a wall panel beside the
passage.

<<dng primitive wall left>>=
        ORG $A249
DRAW_WALL_L
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the left wall panel at VIEW_DEPTH.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Stroke the ceiling and floor diagonals of a solid wall
        ;   panel on the left side of the passage.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$01,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$17,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $07
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_WALL_L

<<dng primitive wall right>>=
        ORG $A27C
DRAW_WALL_R
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the right wall panel at VIEW_DEPTH.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Mirror of DRAW_WALL_L for the right side of the passage.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0C,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$17,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
        STA $07
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_WALL_R

[[DRAW_AHEAD_WALL]] draws the face straight ahead --- the end of
the corridor, or the visible face of a door/secret/field cell ---
and joins it to the previous slice's side walls so the tunnel
reads as continuous.

<<dng primitive ahead wall>>=
        ORG $A2AF
DRAW_AHEAD_WALL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the cell-ahead face and connect it to the last slice.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Stroke the rectangular face that closes the corridor
        ;   straight ahead, then add ceiling/floor connectors back to
        ;   whichever side walls the previous slice drew, so the
        ;   tunnel reads as one continuous surface.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0C,X
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $07
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$01,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        LDA VIEW_CELL                   ; a door at depth 0 needs no
        CMP #$04                        ;   ceiling diagonal
        BNE .ceil
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        BEQ .left_prev
.ceil   LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0C,X
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
.left_prev
        LDA VIEW_L_PREV                 ; join to the previous left
        CMP #$01                        ;   wall if it was solid
        BEQ .join_l
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .join_l
        CMP #$04
        BNE .right_prev
.join_l LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $09
        LDA DNG_GEOM,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
.right_prev
        LDA VIEW_R_PREV                 ; ...and the previous right
        CMP #$01
        BEQ .join_r
        CMP #$03
        BEQ .join_r
        CMP #$04
        BNE .done
.join_r LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$0B,X
        STA $06
        STA $08
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$16,X
        STA $07
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$21,X
        STA $09
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
.done   RTS
@ %def DRAW_AHEAD_WALL

[[DRAW_AHEAD_OPEN]] draws the opening through a doorway in the
cell straight ahead: the doorframe rectangle the player will walk
through.

<<dng primitive ahead open>>=
        ORG $A347
DRAW_AHEAD_OPEN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the doorway opening in the cell straight ahead.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Skip if a monster blocks it. Otherwise stroke the inner
        ;   rectangle of the doorframe the player will walk through.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
