\section{SPA}

\texttt{SPA} --- the space-combat overlay, 9930 bytes at [[$8956]]. It is
the most unusual of the six gameplay overlays: where \texttt{OUT},
\texttt{DNG}, \texttt{TWN} and \texttt{CAS} are turn-based grid worlds,
\texttt{SPA} is a real-time rotation-and-thrust flight model in the
spirit of \emph{Asteroids} or \emph{Star Raiders}. The player launches a
ship into a sector of space, flies it under inertia (thrust and retro
along a heading that rotates in $90^\circ$ steps), and hunts enemy craft
in a first-person targeting view. It is reached from the overworld by
boarding a space-going transport and lifting off; it is the engine that
grows [[PLR_VESSELS]], the destroyed-craft counter, to the \emph{Space
Ace} threshold of twenty that the castle's Princess rescue gates the
time-machine reveal on (see the \texttt{CAS} chapter). Destroy twenty
enemy ships here and the endgame opens.

\texttt{SPA} reuses the resident library and the \texttt{MI.U1} engine
API exactly as the other overlays do, but almost none of their gameplay
code: it has its own physics, its own RNG-seeded starfield, its own
sprite blitter and its own fixed-point projection math. Unlike the grid
overlays it does \emph{not} use the patched-\texttt{JSR} dispatch idiom;
commands run through [[GET_COMMAND]] and then a word table of handler
addresses ([[DISPATCH_TBL]]) that is self-modified into a [[JMP]] in the
main loop.

\subsection{The flight model}

The ship has a position [[SHIP_X]]/[[SHIP_Y]] on a wrap-around torus
(coordinates wrap at [[$0E]] and [[$F4]]), a signed velocity vector
[[ZP_VX]]/[[ZP_VY]], and a heading [[HEAD_CUR]] that is one of four
compass directions. \texttt{Thrust} adds the heading's
[[THRUST_DX]]/[[THRUST_DY]] delta to the velocity; \texttt{Retro}
subtracts it; \texttt{Clockwise} and \texttt{Counter-Clockwise} rotate
the heading. Each physics step ([[PHYSICS]]) integrates the velocity into
the position, advances a rotation animation, then tests the ship against
the docking base and the enemy. Fuel ([[PLR_FUEL]]) and shield
([[PLR_SHIELD]]) are 16-bit figures shown in the status panel; flying
near the central star drains the shield, and a collision bounces the ship
and costs a shield hit.

\subsection{The targeting view and combat}

In the front view the player aims a reticle and fires
([[CMD_FIRE]]); a shot connects when the reticle lies inside the enemy
craft's hit box, whose extent scales with range through the
[[SHAPE_XOFF]]/[[SHAPE_YOFF]] tables. A kill drains the enemy's HP, awards
$+100$ experience (capped at $9999$), and increments [[PLR_VESSELS]];
reaching exactly twenty triggers the ``rank of Space Ace'' popup. The
enemy fires back ([[ALIEN_FIRES]]) with a probability that climbs as the
fight wears on. The enemy is drawn by projecting its relative position
through the fixed-point rotation math ([[MUL8_FIXED]]/[[DIV16]]) and
blitting one of nine distance-scaled sprites.

\subsection{Bases, docking and landing}

A sector may hold a base. Docking ([[DOCK]]) costs a 500p fee, then
refuels the ship and opens the bay so the player can stow the current
craft into one of four berths and board another ([[CHOOSE_SHIP]],
[[BOARD_SHIP]]). Landing on a planet ([[LAND]]) requires the
heat-shielded space shuttle; any other craft burns up, and a successful
landing returns to the overworld via [[EXIT_TO_OUT]].

\subsection{Engine and state symbols}

\texttt{SPA} reuses the resident-library and \texttt{MI.U1} engine API
and the shared player-state block. Only the flight-specific zero-page
scratch, the \texttt{SPA} BSS state bands, and the in-file tables are new.
The player's food/experience slots are repurposed here as the ship's
fuel and shield.

