\texttt{WRITE\_VOLDIR} is the thin wrapper that calls the directory writer and,
on any ProDOS error, prints the code in hex so a failure is at least
diagnosable.

<<gen write voldir>>=
        ORG $933F
WRITE_VOLDIR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Call FORMAT_VOLUME and report any error.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Invoke FORMAT_VOLUME (the ProDOS directory writer) with the unit
        ;   number; on success return, on failure clear the line and print
        ;   "Format failed -- error NN." (the ProDOS error code in hex) before
        ;   restarting the formatter.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA FMT_UNIT
        LDX #$00
        LDY #$BB
        JSR FORMAT_VOLUME
        PHA
        LDA #$01
        STA MON_CH
        LDA #$0F
        STA MON_CV
        JSR CLEAR_LINES
        PLA
        BNE .L9359
        RTS
.L9359
        PHA
        JSR PROMPT_LINE
        DC.B "Format failed.  MLI error #",0
        PLA
        JSR PRINT_HEX
        LDA #$2E
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        JSR FMT_PRESS_SPACE
        JMP FORMAT_RESTART
@ %def WRITE_VOLDIR

\subsection{Local text helpers}

These few routines are \texttt{GEN}'s own window furniture: a bottom-line
prompt printer that accepts inline text, a ``press space'' wait, and a couple
of line-clearing helpers used between chargen steps.

<<gen text helpers>>=
        ORG $9388
PROMPT_LINE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Bottom-line prompt printer and text-window helpers.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   PROMPT_LINE homes the cursor to the bottom prompt line (row $14)
        ;   and falls into MSG_PRINT, so callers can pass inline text.
        ;   PRESS_SPACE prints "Press Space to continue:" and waits.
        ;   CLEAR_FROM20 / WINFULL_HOME / CLEAR_LINES blank ranges of text rows
        ;   around the cursor (used between chargen steps).
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDX #$02
        STX MON_CH
        LDY #$14
        STY MON_CV
        JSR CLEAR_LINES
        JMP MSG_PRINT
FMT_PRESS_SPACE
        LDX #$02
        LDY #$15
        JSR MSG_AT
        DC.B "Press Space to continue: ",0
        JSR MLIB_ONLINE
        JSR KEY_WAIT
CLEAR_FROM20
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        LDA #$14
        STA MON_CV
        BNE CLEAR_LINES
WINFULL_HOME
        JSR WIN_FULL
        JSR HOME_CURSOR
CLEAR_LINES
        JSR WIN_SAVE
        DEC $21
.L93D1
        JSR CLR_EOL
        JSR CURSOR_COL1
        INC MON_CV
        LDY MON_CV
        INY
        CPY $23
        BCC .L93D1
        JMP WIN_RESTORE
@ %def PROMPT_LINE FMT_PRESS_SPACE CLEAR_FROM20 WINFULL_HOME CLEAR_LINES

The \texttt{READ\_BLOCK} parameter block and a fourteen-byte scratch buffer
(used to preserve zero page [[$D0]]--[[$DD]] across the RWTS call) sit here.

<<gen rdblk data>>=
        ORG $93E3
RDBLK_PARAM
        HEX 03
FMT_UNIT
        HEX 0000bb0200
ZP_SAVE
        HEX 0000000000000000
        HEX 000000000000
@ %def RDBLK_PARAM FMT_UNIT ZP_SAVE

\texttt{BORDER\_DRAW} strokes the decorative double-ruled frame around the
screen using the font's box glyphs.

<<gen border>>=
        ORG $93F7
BORDER_DRAW
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw the decorative double-line screen border.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Stroke the top rule, the side rules down to row $16, and the bottom
        ;   rule using the font's box-drawing glyphs, then HOME_CURSOR resets
        ;   the text cursor to (1,1).
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA #$10
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDX #$26
        LDA #$04
        JSR CHAR_REPEAT
        LDA #$12
        JSR FONT_DRAW
.L9408
        INC MON_CV
        JSR CR
        LDA #$0A
        JSR FONT_DRAW
        LDA #$27
        STA MON_CH
        LDA #$08
        JSR FONT_DRAW
        JSR KEY_POLL
        LDA MON_CV
        EOR #$16
        BNE .L9408
        STA MON_CH
        INC MON_CV
        LDA #$14
        JSR CHAR_OUT
        LDX #$26
        LDA #$02
        JSR CHAR_REPEAT
        LDA #$16
        JSR FONT_DRAW
HOME_CURSOR
        LDX #$01
        STX MON_CH
        STX MON_CV
        RTS
@ %def BORDER_DRAW HOME_CURSOR

\subsection{The initial game-state image}

