\section{NIF: the ending screen}

\texttt{NIF} --- \emph{fin} reversed --- is the game's victory screen:
a full hi-res page of calligraphic text recounting Mondain's death and
Lord British's reward, displayed when the player completes the game.
The format is unusually simple: a \textbf{line-sequential raster},
192 rows of 40 bytes top to bottom, with none of the hi-res screen's
interleave and none of its eight-byte holes (hence 7680 bytes rather
than 8192). Whatever displays it must copy row by row through a line
address table --- the renderer
(\texttt{.claude/scripts/render\_nif.py}) does exactly that.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{images/nif_ending_screen.png}
\caption{The \texttt{NIF} ending screen, rendered from the
line-sequential raster.}
\label{fig:nif-ending}
\end{figure}

The file loads at [[$4000]] (hi-res page 2's address, though as a
raster it cannot be displayed there directly). The image data:

<<nif.asm>>=
        PROCESSOR 6502
<<nif raster>>
